<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-STADIUMS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL TEAMS DOING THE STADIUMTANGO  
 CARDS AMONG TEAMS SEEKING NEW FACILITY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFLD   
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Picture this scenario: Metropolitan Denver residents
defeat a referendum next month to build the Denver Broncos a new
$360 million stadium, prompting team owner Pat Bowlen to announce
that the club is up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles super agent Michael Ovitz, rebuffed in his bid to
get the city an expansion team, buys the Broncos from Bowlen and
says he wants to move them to the nation's second-largest market,
where he has plans for a stadium-entertainment mall project he is
calling The Hacienda. It would be the only stadium in the world
with mission bells that toll after every home-team touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft, frustrated
in his bid to get the team a new stadium in the Boston area, makes
a deal with the city of Providence, R.I., to get a stadium there.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Broncos and Patriots play in 2002, one team is based
in Los Angeles and playing in the Rose Bowl until the bells toll at
The Hacienda, and the other team is playing in a city that hasn't
had football since 1931 when the Providence Steam Rollers rolled
out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh. It's not that absurd because the NFL clearly is in
flux.
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland Raiders, who play the Cardinals today at Sun Devil
Stadium, again are talking about moving back to Los Angeles, the
city they left in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say there's a chance the Raiders could come back to LA,''
NFL attorney Frank Rothman told the ``Los Angeles Times.'' ``(It's)
about the same chance of me getting pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, meanwhile, still are trying to get a new stadium
as part of the $1.7 billion Rio Solado Crossing stadium and
convention center project and hope that residents of Gilbert, Mesa
and Queen Creek can vote on the issue in May.
</P>
<P>
   Seven NFL teams are scheduled to get new stadiums in the next
four years _ Detroit, Cincinnati, Pittsburgh, Seattle, Cleveland,
San Francisco and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Vikings want out of the 64,000-seat Metrodome in
downtown Minneapolis or at least re-work the lease team owners
maintain is the worst in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Eagles owner Jeff Lurie is desperate to get his
team out of Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft is losing patience that his quest for a new stadium in
Boston has gone nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Bears owner Michael McCaskey was so frustrated a few
years ago by the inability to get a new stadium, he even considered
moving the team to Gary, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody you talk in the league wants to see stabilization,''
said Michael Bidwill, the Cardinals' vice president who has
spearheaded the stadium project. ``No one wants to move. It's not
good for teams, communities or the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   But team owners also think it's not good for their clubs to stay
in stadiums they consider antiquated. They don't think they can
compete financially or on the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The latest collective-bargaining agreement in this league
created a system in which teams that have control over local
revenue and stadiums have the ability to attract and maintain
marquee players much greater than teams that don't,'' Bidwill said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty NFL teams are playing in stadiums built in 1976 or
earlier, including the Cardinals, who play in the fifth-oldest
facility in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Devil Stadium was built in 1958. Only Green Bay's Lambeau
Field (built in 1957), Denver's Mile High Stadium (1948), Chicago's
Soldier Field (1923) and Jacksonville's Municipal Stadium (1920)
are older. The Jaguars' stadium, however, was razed and rebuilt
before the expansion team played its first game.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these stadiums are old and people expect more for
their entertainment dollar,'' said Bruce Allen, Raiders senior
assistant who formerly was general manager of the Arizona Wranglers
of the now-defunct United States Football League. ``I can envision
in 30 years people going to want to have interactive capabilities
in suites.''
</P>
<P>
   When St. Louis lost out to Carolina and Jacksonville for
expansion franchises, city leaders went out and lured away the Los
Angeles Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, Houston and Los Angeles will make one-hour
presentations to NFL owners in Kansas City for an expansion team,
the NFL's 32nd franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, which lost the Oilers to Tennessee two years ago, is
considered the front-runner because prospective owner Bob McNair, a
billionaire who owns Cogen Technologies, has been able to get the
city of Houston, Harris County, the Houston Livestock Show and
Rodeo and the Harris County/Houston Sports Authority working
together.
</P>
<P>
   There already are financial plans set to build a 70,000-seat,
all-glass, retractable dome stadium near the site of the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Mayor Lee Brown, former police chief in Houston and New
York, will tell all who will listen that he went to college on a
football scholarship and knows what it's like to sack a
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston has a mayor who wants the NFL,'' said Brown, a shot at
former Houston Mayor Bob Lanier and at Los Angeles Mayor Richard
Riordan, who has not gone out of his way to help his city's attempt
to get a team.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there are two Los Angeles groups trying to attract a
team _ Ovitz's and the New Coliseum Partners, which is trying to
attract a team back to Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum, where the
Raiders played.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz has put together a star-studded group that includes actors
Tom Cruise and Kevin Costner, Los Angeles Lakers Executive Vice
President Jerry West, former Lakers star Magic Johnson and Lakers
center Shaquille O'Neal, who came on board last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love football; it's the first sport I ever played,'' O'Neal
said. ``I remember intercepting a pass my freshman year in high
school and returning it for a touchdown and then someone hitting me
in the knee late. That was it for my football career.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is impressed that glitz will get a team for Ovitz,
whose plans for The Hacienda include a 78,000-seat stadium in
Carson, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the owners weren't going to allow Don Shula and Jim Brown
in, I don't think they care about Jerry West and Shaq,'' the
Raiders' Allen said of failed Cleveland bids.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said much of the talk about the Raiders returning to Los
Angeles has quieted because the team is ``focusing on football.''
</P>
<P>
   But the team's problems in Oakland won't go away. The city of
Oakland and Alameda County (Calif.) have sued the team, and the
Raiders have countersued.
</P>
<P>
   The team sold only about 30,000 season tickets, the number of
personal seat licenses (one-time fee that gives a fan the right to
own a seat) has fallen to about 29,000 and the city of Oakland is
expected to lose $20 million as the result of their deal with the
Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   So even though longtime Raiders fans are trying to get Bay Area
fans excited about the team by promoting the theme ``Trek to
Football Mecca,'' it's realistic that the Raiders could return to
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes noises like he wants to come back to LA and all his
problems will go away, and we'll be lovers forever,'' Rothman said
of Raiders owner Al Davis. ``The only difference between these guys
_ the NFL and Jesse James _ is that James always had the personal
integrity to wear a mask.''
</P>
<P>
   Things haven't gotten as ugly in Denver, where voters are
expected to extend the 0.1 percent Coors Field sales tax to 2012,
which would pay for 75 percent of the cost of a new football
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But if they don't, Broncos owner Pat Bowlen said he likely will
sell the team, and that there is no guarantee that he would sell to
someone that would keep the Super Bowl champions in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be likely to keep the team until it's not competitive, and
that wouldn't be far down the line,'' Bowlen said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
