<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIOCRITY WOULD BE IMPROVEMENT FOR MANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The richest rookie in NFL history threw only 11 interceptions as
a senior at Tennessee. Now, Indianapolis'  &UR; Peyton Manning is on a
pace to finish with 44, which would break the NFL record of 42 that
 &UR; George
 &UR; Blanda threw for Houston of the American Football League in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   The second-richest rookie in NFL history, now being referred to
as Cryin' (instead of  &UR; Ryan) Leaf, &UR; is averaging $1 million per
turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's offensive line, coached by former Cardinals assistant
 &UR; Carl
 &UR; Mauck, has given up 22 sacks in three games. If the Bills continue
at that pace, they'll finish with a league-record 117.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bears have been outscored, 44-0, in the third
quarter this season. If that continues, they'll finish the season
allowing 176 points while scoring none in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They say the meek shall inherit the earth. Maybe that explains
how at the quarter mark, the league's have-nots have engulfed the
rest of the league.
</P>
<P>
   There still are six winless teams, three more than at this time
last year.
</P>
<P>
   One of those six, the Washington Redskins, were the preseason
favorites to win the NFC East, a division in which three .500 teams
are tied for the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Another winless club, Carolina, was in the NFC championship game
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's  &UR; Ray Rhodes, coach of the winless Philadelphia
Eagles, who is so frustrated that he stays up all night trying to
find solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obsessed with it,'' he said. ``It's driving me crazy. It's
driving me up a wall. You can't sleep. How can you sleep when
you're getting your butt kicked? I can't close my eyes. My wife
thinks I'm out of my mind. She's right.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme are seven unbeaten teams, led by the San
Francisco 49ers, who are averaging 533 yards and 37 points, and the
Denver Broncos, who have scored 141 points in three games.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers are on a pace to finish with 8,528 yards and 597
points this season. They've had three consecutive 500-yard games.
They hadn't had two 500-yard games in a row since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the Broncos' impressive start,  &UR; Mike Shanahan,
coach of the defending Super Bowl champions, is our Coach of the
Year, barely edging  &UR; Mike Ditka, whose New Orleans Saints are 3-0
but have beaten teams that are a combined 1-10.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay quarterback  &UR; Brett Favre, who has won three
consecutive Most Valuable Player awards, again is the MVP after
four games. He has thrown a league-high 10 touchdown passes and is
completing 66.2 percent of his throws.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos running back  &UR; Terrell Davis, who has nearly 500 rushing
yards in four games, is the Offensive Player of the Year at this
point.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's  &UR; Jermaine Lewis, who has returned two punts for
touchdowns, is the Special Teams Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina defensive end  &UR; Kevin Greene, who has seven sacks, is
the Comeback Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   The Rookies of the Year are Minnesota wide receiver  &UR; Randy Moss
(17 catches for 273 yards and four scores) on offense, Green Bay
tackle
 &UR; Vonnie Holliday (four sacks) on defense and South Mountain High
School graduate  &UR; Terry Fair of Detroit (two kickoff returns for
touchdowns) on special teams. &QL; 
Reality check &QL; 
Manning, 0-4 this season, lost only six games in four years at
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot, Peyton hasn't lost four games in a row since he played
in the back yard against me,'' said Manning's older brother,
 &UR; Cooper, 24. &QL; 
 &UR; Terry Bradshaw, the Hall of Fame quarterback for the Pittsburgh
Steelers who works for FOX, thinks Manning has handled his
struggles much better than Leaf, who continues to battle the San
Diego media.
</P>
<P>
   Manning and Leaf will face each other today in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan Leaf is going to be a great quarterback in the NFL, but
right now he has to understand he is going to struggle,'' Bradshaw
said. ``Ryan, you have to grow up and learn to deal with the media
because no matter what you do, there's always going to be
criticism. You just have to accept it. It's all part of the
maturation process.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaf has thrown six interceptions and lost three fumbles in the
past two games and has a turnover-touchdown ratio of 11-1.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, he said, ``I feel like my heart's been ripped
out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradshaw added: ``One of the biggest reasons why Peyton Manning
was drafted ahead of Ryan Leaf was because Manning is much more
mature. Leaf has to learn how to deal with criticism. It's easy to
accept praise, but it's very difficult to live with people
criticizing you.'' &QL; 
Impeach Norv?
</P>
<P>
   The ``Washington Pos''t's Style section had a picture of
embattled Redskins Coach  &UR; Norv Turner this week next to a headline
that said, ``This Town's Other Scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   A subhead said, ``We've Tried Censure. What's next for Norv?''
</P>
<P>
   Writer  &UR; Frank Ahrens said: ``Forget about the other guy. It's
time to get rid of the man who's really an embarrassment to
Washington. Impeach Norv!''
</P>
<P>
   The story quoted a Washington TV personality as saying Turner
was the opposite of  &UR; President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a bad job rating but good personal character,'' said
 &UR; William Kristol, who is a regular on ABC-TV's ``This Week'' Sunday
news program. &QL; 
Friend of the president &QL; 
Saints offensive tackle  &UR; Willie Roaf, a page to Clinton when he was
Arkansas governor in the early 1980s, was an overnight guest in the
White House in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``What President Clinton did was wrong,'' Roaf said of Clinton's
acknowledged womanizing. ``But it's been known for years, even when
he was governor in Arkansas, that he chased skirts. I don't think
it's right what he did, but I don't think he should be impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   Roaf said he stayed in the Queen's Room on the second floor of
the north wing of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Did he meet  &UR; Monica Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, by then they had broken it off,'' Roaf said. &QL; 
Quick kicks &QL; 
Lions safety  &UR; Mark Carrier said he didn't deserve to be suspended
for one game for his hit on Tampa Bay wide receiver  &UR; Brice Hunter.
``Because it was on ``Monday Night Football'' and everyone saw it,
they think they should do something,'' said Carrier, who broke his
silence on the incident in a Thursday interview on Phoenix radio
station KMVP-AM (860).
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis Rams Coach  &UR; Dick Vermeil, on suggestions from fans and
media that he is out of touch with the NFL game: ``If it was
 &UR; Bill Walsh, Jim Mora or  &UR; Bill Parcells . . . if it were the coaches
who felt I lost it, then I'd resign. But I feel good about the
progress we're making and think we're moving faster than what
people give us credit for.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle linebacker  &UR; Chad Brown still can't believe he was booed
by Steelers fans in his first time returning to Three Rivers
Stadium since he signed as a free agent with the Seahawks. ``Two
years ago, the fans loved me,'' he said. ``Now, they give me the
finger. Their $45 (ticket) doesn't obligate them to cuss at me. If
they saw me on the street and cussed at me, I'd beat their
(butts).'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at 602-444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
