<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOCUSED BRUINS DOMINATE WSU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The questions, the memories, the chatter
during practice _ everything was Washington State this, Washington
State that for the UCLA Bruins this week.
</P>
<P>
   But truth be told, what transpired Saturday at the Rose Bowl had
very little to do with Washington State and everything to do with
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Houston? UCLA's offensive linemen did. They remembered
quarterback Cade McNown getting knocked down 16 times. They
remembered the Bruins rushing for a meager 89 yards and looking
unusually mortal against a second-rate team in a third-rate
facility.
</P>
<P>
   And they did not forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were much more focused on what happened at Houston than we
were the (1997) Washington State game,'' UCLA guard Andy Meyers
said. ``We talked about it in practice. We had to shore up our
protection and get the running game going.''
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of action in UCLA's 49-17 victory Saturday in
front of 67,210. It had long runs and longer passes. It had blocked
punts, blocked kicks, fumbles and spirited defense. It had human
pinballs _ McNown impersonating, well, McNown _ and a dose of
redemption for a certain tailback from Lancaster.
</P>
<P>
   Just as they did last year, the No.4 Bruins took advantage of
opponent turnovers and the resulting short fields _ average
starting position: their 48-yard line _ to score early and score
often. They bolted to a 28-0 lead in the second quarter on scoring
drives of 42, 48, 54 and 6 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fumbled the ball (three) times and gave UCLA good field
position,'' Cougars coach Mike Price said. ``Anytime you give UCLA
a chance to score, they're going to score. They're a damn good
offensive football team.''
</P>
<P>
   And at the heart of the Bruins' 13th consecutive victory was a
dominating performance by their offensive line, which did not
confuse the Houston Cougars with the Wazu Cougars. Meyers, Shawn
Stuart and Kris Farris established their presence instantly,
knocking Washington State off the ball and carving huge holes for
Jermaine Lewis and Co.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA rushed for a season-high 256 yards, and did it against the
Pac-10's No.2 run defense. The Cougars had been allowing just 105.5
yards per game on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offensive line took command early in the game,'' offensive
coordinator Al Borges said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins rushed for 98 yards just in the first quarter,
beginning with Lewis' 15-yard charge on the first play and ending
with his 9-yard burst through the right side.
</P>
<P>
   The tailback finished with 94 yards and two touchdowns, finally
and completely exterminating the lingering demons from his failed
fourth-and-1 run last year at Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let it go last season, but it carried over for this game,''
Lewis said. ``People started bringing it up. It's good to finally
clear my name.... I have to give credit to the line. There were big
holes, and I just made the right reads.''
</P>
<P>
   If not Lewis, it was Keith Brown (two touchdowns) or impressive
freshman DeShaun Foster (77 yards). The Bruins rotated their
tailbacks seamlessly; each had plenty of running room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we could move the pile, and we moved the pile,'' coach
Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing, too, because McNown did not play to his lofty
standards. Yes, he completed 14 of 27 passes for 205 yards, but he
underthrew open receivers several times and was intercepted once.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he was rusty; the Bruins (3-0, 1-0) hadn't played in two
weeks because of the canceled game at Miami. Perhaps Washington
State's defense disrupted his rhythm; the Cougars are young but
swift. Either way, UCLA managed 49 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense played well enough to get yards and score
points,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   For once, in fact, the offense was UCLA's least-impressive unit.
The special teams blocked two punts: one by DuVal Hicks, which set
up a 6-yard touchdown drive, the other by Ali Azziz. And the
defense _ porous at Houston, riddled with injuries on the line _
played its most complete game of the season, holding Washington
State's sputtering offense to 314 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased with the way we swarmed to the ball,'' Toledo
said. ``It was hard to tell who played well because we had so many
guys flying around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
