<HEADLINE>
BRUINS BOW AS ALLISON RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Pesky forward Esa Tikkanen scored at the 11-minute mark
of the third period, lifting the New York Rangers to a 3-1 victory
over the Bruins at the FleetCenter. It marked the exhibition debut
of center Jason Allison, who came to contract terms with the Bruins
Thursday, practiced for the first time Friday, and jumped right
into the lineup Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take him long to make his presence felt.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers drew first blood at 2:08 of the opening period when
former New Jersey Devil John MacLean banged in a rebound of a Scott
Fraser shot past goalie Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two minutes later, the Bruins pulled even, with
Allison setting up the score on the power play. Allison,
maneuvering behind the net, dished a pass to Steve Heinze, who
fired a shot on goalie Mike Richter. The netminder stopped Heinze's
bid for one of his 34 saves, but rookie Peter Nordstrom was there
to bang home the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, who had outshot New York, 11-8, in the first period,
outshot the visitors in the second, 13-3. Neither team, however,
could score. Boston had a five-on-three advantage for 1:20 but
overpassed the puck and managed just two shots on Richter.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie defenseman Jonathan Girard, the Bruins' first pick
(second round) in last June's draft, showed some flair on the power
play as he manned the right point with Ray Bourque on the left. No
doubt, he will be urged to shoot more.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers decided the game midway through the third when
flashy Alexei Kovalev dished a pass to Wayne Gretzky. Gretzky, off
to Dafoe's right, fired a backhander into the left circle for
Tikkanen, who one-timed it past Dafoe, who faced a total of just 19
shots, at 11:00.
</P>
<P>
   Niklas Sundstrom added a shorthanded empty-net goal with 27
seconds left as Boston's exhibition record fell to 2-5-1 with one
game left, Sunday's 5 p.m. rematch Hartford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
