<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER FOLLOWING SHORTSTOP'S FOOTSTEPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He drove in 11 runs in four games, a record for any
Division Series, even those that have gone the maximum five games.
He drove in at least one run in all four games the Red Sox played
and hit home runs in three of them, accounting Saturday night for
Boston's only run.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Nomar Garciaparra had just finished one of the great
postseason performances by anyone. Would the time come when he
could look back on what he'd done and appreciate it for what it
was?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he said, ``when we win the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Red Sox clubhouse at Fenway Park, where family and
friends were gathered, Ramon Garciaparra, who had taken some time
off from his job as a high school coach in southern California, was
awaiting his son.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to the father and perhaps you will understand why Nomar
Garciaparra's career has known only an upward curve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell him, `Somebody always is better than you,''' said Ramon
Garciaparra, who is never more than a phone call away from his son,
who calls on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a satellite dish and we always go over his game, how
he's doing,'' added the elder Garciaparra, who can recall only one
week in which he did not see his son's games in the three sports in
which he excelled in high school: soccer, football, and of course,
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went as a family to Mexico,'' Ramon Garciaparra said.
``Nomar had some club soccer games and stayed home. Those are the
only games I missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it was so hard for me when Nomar went to college. I
couldn't see any of his games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox shortstop gave his father an eyeful this weekend. On
Friday, his two-run home run in the bottom of the ninth drew the
Sox within a run in their 4-3 loss to the Indians. Saturday he led
off the fourth with a 411-foot home run off Bartolo Colon, the
Indians starter who had held Garciaparra hitless in 10 at-bats
during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday, Garciaparra hit a three-run homer and sacrifice
fly for four RBIs in Game 1, a two-run double and sacrifice fly for
three RBIs in Game 2, and a fielder's choice and two-run homer for
three RBIs in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy who weighed 137 pounds his last year in high
school, according to his father, a small but well-built man who at
Don Bosco High in Rosemead, Calif., coaches the junior varsity
soccer team and is the baseball team's pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was young, he was always the smallest kid on every
team he played,'' his father said.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra had other options besides Georgia Tech when he
graduated from St. John Bosco in nearby Whittier. UCLA wanted him
to be its football placekicker and play baseball, while Arkansas
wanted him strictly to kick for the football team. ``They didn't
even know he played baseball,'' Ramon Garciaparra said. ``UCLA was
very tempting, but Nomar just had a gut feeling about Georgia
Tech.''
</P>
<P>
   Father expects son to return home to California this winter,
even though he maintains a home in the Boston area. He likes to
watch his sisters, Monique, 16, and Yvette, 13, play soccer and his
brother, Michael, 15, play the same three sports in which Nomar
excelled.
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman, Michael earned varsity letters in football,
baseball, and soccer. ``He actually could be ahead of Nomar,''
Ramon Garciaparra said. ``He's already almost as big as Nomar is
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
