<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ READY, BUT HE DIDN'T GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hello, no, Pedro won't go.
</P>
<P>
   Such remained the battle cry in the corner office of the Red Sox
clubhouse Saturday afternoon, manager Jimy Williams sticking by his
decision not to reach for his $75 million arm in the club's biggest
money game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro rode the pine and Pete Schourek, the 1-2 lefthander, toed
the rubber. And the rest was inked in the annals of Red Sox
history, inning by inning.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief pregame news conference, Williams was asked to assess
Schourek's frame of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete? ... Pete ... Pete Schourek?'' said Williams, in a tone
that could only be interpreted as practiced nonchalance. ``I
haven't seen him, so I imagine he's pretty good. I imagine he's
looking forward to pitching, and I'm looking forward to watching
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams wasn't alone in his anticipation, but it appeared he
shared a minority opinion in Red Sox Nation. Following Game 3, a
4-3 Cleveland victory that gave the Indians a 2-1 advantage in the
best-of-five American League Division Series, radio talk shows
filled the air with royal rooters lamenting the fact that Williams
wouldn't call on Martinez to be his main man.
</P>
<P>
   Even former Sox first baseman George Scott got in on the airwave
act of angst. The Boomer, manager of the Massachusetts Mad Dogs in
Lynn, called Ted Sarandis on WEEI and cast his vote for Martinez.
The Boomer talked of Jim Lonborg in '67. In times of need, reach
for the obvious. Why wait for Game 5 when Game 5 may never come?
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said Friday night that he twice asked Williams if he
could have the ball in Game 4. He said he was twice denied. The
manager told him he was looking out for his arm, his future, the
days and decades to come in Red Sox history.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he understood. He said he appreciated what the
manager was saying, doing. But he also said he wanted the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been strong in the arm and shoulder,'' said
Martinez, whose 1-2 record in September didn't make a strong
supporting case for his statement. ``I've never had a problem with
my arm or shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   It came down to this: Martinez was willing, but Williams and
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan didn't feel he was able. On Friday,
hours before Game 3, Kerrigan was making reference to Martinez's
slight build (167 pounds) and the great number of innings and
pitches he logged this season. Kerrigan watched Martinez throw
after his fine Game 1 performance and felt the staff ace didn't
have the necessary steam to pitch on only three days of rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be very impatient,'' said Martinez, asked what his
emotions would be watching Game 4 from the sidelines. ``Especially
if we don't start out ... but I'm thinking positively, positive
that they can do it without me. I'll have my cleats on and I'll be
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The hours on the baseball sundial burned away silently. Some 18
hours after leaving the park Friday night, Martinez was back in the
Back Bay ballyard, uniform clean, cleats laced and at the ready. No
need. There would be no call.
</P>
<P>
   In the pregame news conference, Williams was asked whom he had
ready for bullpen duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody but Pedro,'' said the manager. He was sticking by
his decision _ and while Schourek's 5 1/3 shutout innings justified
it, there will be no Game 5. So Martinez will be fresh for his next
start. In April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-04-98 0110EDT &QL; 
