u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-KIM-BOS &LR;      10-04 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-KIM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIM WAVED RUN GOODBYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Wendell Kim's body language, the shrug of his shoulders
and his limited words, said what had to be said. The Red Sox third
base coach gave John Valentin the go-ahead to try for home in the
sixth inning Saturday, which turned out to be a one-way ticket to a
dead end.
</P>
<P>
   But what was Kim to do? Time was running out, and this was no
time to be playing cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the lead, 1-0, and I thought it was a good move,'' said
Kim, needlessly offering himself up for blame. ``It didn't work
out. That's part of it. There's a lot more involved, but I'm not
going to explain myself.''
</P>
<P>
   No need, really. Holding tenuously to the lead, faced with
postseason elimination, the light-hitting Sox were forced into
trying to manufacture a run. A one-run lead in Fenway Park means
little for any team, but it was clear early on in this series _
even in the Game 1 assault in Cleveland _ that much of the Boston
lineup wasn't going to make much of a contribution on offense.
</P>
<P>
   When Kim gave Valentin the order to wheel around third on Mike
Stanley's single to left, Troy O'Leary was the on-deck hitter, with
Scott Hatteberg to follow. O'Leary came into the evening with an
.083 average in the series. Hatteberg had gone 1 for 7 (.143). All
that considered, a loose ball in left field was all Kim had to see.
Valentin got the green light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to be aggressive,'' said Valentin, who was cut down
easily and cleanly by David Justice's peg to catcher Sandy Alomar,
a play that proved fatal in the Sox' 2-1 season-ending loss. ``I
didn't really know the place the ball went, whether (Justice) is
bobbling it or what. I'm just reading my third base coach.''
</P>
<P>
   As Valentin raced for home, dead duck to be, Nomar Garciaparra,
on first with an intentional walk after Valentin's double, set his
sights on taking third. His hope, with only one out, was to draw
Justice's throw, make himself a living, huffing, one-run sacrifice.
If Garciaparra was out at third, it meant Valentin was home free.
</P>
<P>
   Justice wasn't biting. Third baseman Travis Fryman, the cutoff
man on the play, also wasn't going for Garciaparra's wounded duck
decoy. Justice's heave was ticketed for home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw (Garciaparra) and I knew we had an easy out at third
base,'' said Fryman. ``But we are down one run and I thought we had
a chance on the play at the plate. It's easy for me to give up that
out at third base because I thought we had a good chance (at
home).''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary then came to the plate with two outs and ended the
inning with a fly to center. He finished the day 0 for 4. After
him, the Nos. 7, 8, and 9 hitters went a collective 0 for 9. The
bottom half of the the Sox lineup was a constant rerun of ``Death
Valley Days.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams, as always refusing to point fingers, said
the offensive failures didn't factor into Kim's thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wendell made the right decision,'' said Williams. ``Valentin
made a good effort. That's all you can ask. We put the pressure on
the defensive side, and they executed well.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Sox had been ahead by two runs, said Kim, the decision
would not have been the same. He would have flashed the hold sign,
Valentin would have pulled up at third, and the bases would have
been loaded with one out. A deep fly then would have pushed
Valentin home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were other reasons (for sending Valentin),'' said Kim,
still not wanting to elaborate on the obvious, ``if you look at the
situation. I made the decision and it didn't turn out. Basically,
it was my fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, too, said Kim, that Justice had to run toward the
left-field line to retrieve Stanley's single.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what arm does he throw with?'' asked Kim, noting that the
play was slightly harder for Justice, a lefthander, because he
would have to stop, change momentum, and make his throw. ``I
figured we had a good chance.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be Boston's only chance. O'Leary fanned to end
the inning, not even swinging at strike three. The Sox got
Hatteberg as far as second base in the seventh, but he died there.
Vaughn doubled in the eighth, and pinch runner Donnie Sadler soon
moved to third, where he was stranded on an O'Leary inning-ending
fly. The Sox went 1-2-3 in the ninth, with hitters 7, 8, and 9
erased on two rollers and a strikeout. The bottom five hitters
finished 1 for 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I surprised? Not really,'' said Valentin, asked once more
about getting the go-ahead from Kim. ``It's a short left field and
everything, but you want him to make the play. And he did. Justice
isn't usually in left field, so you want him to make the throw. You
want to be aggressive. I look at the third base coach, I see his
arm being waved, and I just follow the instructions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
