</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GORDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON'S ARRIVAL PART OF MASTER PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In baseball times not so long ago _ but before Tony La
Russa and the breakdown of specialists into sub-specialists _ the
decision on when to call a pitcher out of the bullpen and into a
playoff game might not have been made before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is what Red Sox manager Jimy Williams and pitching
coach Joe Kerrigan decided before Saturday's season-ending 2-1 loss
to the Indians. If the Sox had the lead going into the eighth
inning of this survival game, Tom Gordon would be brought in.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox had a 1-0 lead. Gordon, the Red Sox closer, was
brought in to pitch. Never before this season had he been brought
in to start the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had it set up just the way we planned it before the game,''
said Kerrigan. ``There wasn't even a decision to make. We had
planned it out before the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet if there is one constant in playoff baseball, it is that
some players respond to pressure and some don't, just as some
managers respond to pressure and some don't. Williams and Kerrigan
had insisted before Saturday's game that starting Pete Schourek
instead of Pedro Martinez was merely a continuation of what had
been done all season _ staying with the rotation. But by using
Gordon this way, the brain trust deviated from what had been done
all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had (Gordon) down on our card because he'd had two full
days off,'' said Kerrigan. ``He could get six outs.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, in baseball times not so long past, the fact that
Derek Lowe had pitched so strongly in the sixth and seventh innings
for the Red Sox, retiring all five batters he faced, might have
been a consideration when deciding who should pitch the eighth. The
decision to remove Lowe had been made even before the seventh
inning had been completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lowe had been up the day before, and then three innings two
days before that, 38 pitches, long innings, with a pitching
change,'' said Kerrigan. ``After (Lowe) got the second out in the
seventh (a ground out to third by Richie Sexson), I just looked at
Jimy and Jimy looked at me, and we both just nodded. We both knew
what we were going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was, after Saturday's game and the season were done,
Gordon sat by his locker for long minutes. From time to time,
Gordon would stare into his locker and then he would bury his face
in his hands. Teammates came by to console him, first Mo Vaughn,
then Kerrigan, and next Bret Saberhagen. In time, Gordon was able
to talk about the night his 43 consecutive saves went for naught in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Was getting six outs an issue for him?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' replied Gordon. ``Not for me, no. I was ready to pitch,
regardless if they brought me in in the seventh.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said he went through the same routine he always had,
threw many of the same pitches he had all year, did all the same
things that had resulted in save after save.
</P>
<P>
   ``All year I've been able to throw those pitches (fastballs
inside) and get ground-ball outs and even fly-ball outs with broken
bats,'' said Gordon. ``But tonight it didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, after retiring Joey Cora on a soft fly to left to open
the eighth, Gordon threw to Kenny Lofton, who broke his bat but
flared a single to center. Next, the light-hitting Omar Vizquel hit
Gordon hard, stroking a single to right.
</P>
<P>
   After Lofton stole third, bringing the tying run only 90 feet
from the plate, ``I threw a pitch to (David) Justice, and Justice
is a good hitter. If he gets his pitch, he's going to hit it.''
Justice did, a rope double to the triangle in right-center, driving
in the tying and winning runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't change my approach. I didn't change one thing,'' said
Gordon. ``I stuck with the program.''
</P>
<P>
   If only the Red Sox brain trust could say the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
