<HEADLINE>
REFLECTIVE TIME FOR DUQUETTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``I'll tell you soon,'' responded Red Sox general
manager Dan Duquette when he was asked what his club's playoff loss
to the Indians told him about his team and what improvements must
be made for next season. ``I don't have an answer for you now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the minutes following the Sox' season-ending 2-1 loss to the
Indians Saturday night, Duquette made his rounds in the dressing
room, quietly shaking hands with his charges, softly speaking words
of encouragement. He said he was proud of his team and he singled
out three players for their season-long leadership: Mo Vaughn, Bret
Saberhagen, and Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll address next year another time,'' said Duquette. ``We
needed to score some more runs. We wanted to score some more runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, you need five runs to win at Fenway Park. Everyone
in your lineup needs to produce offensively in the American League.
How many did we score in the first game here? Three, right? Three
yesterday and only one today. It's not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox' offensive attack disappeared after the meat of the
order. All of Red Sox Nation had its eyes focused on why Pete
Schourek and not Pedro Martinez was the Game 4 starter. It turned
out to be a nonissue. Schourek pitched splendidly, easily well
enough for the Sox to win. He had to pitch through a nine-man
batting order, while Indians starter Bartolo Colon faced only a
four-man lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made some good progress this year,'' said Duquette. ``We
won 90 games for the first time in a long time and we won a playoff
game. Both are good achievements for our organization. But we're
disappointed that we aren't playing deeper in October. We're
disappointed it ended so abruptly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
