<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-JUSTICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE A TWO-WAY STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There was an added sense of satisfaction in David
Justice's smile. He got his wish to play both ways, and, well, the
Red Sox are checking tee times Sunday because he did.
</P>
<P>
   Justice delivered two game-turning plays _ one in the field and
one at the plate _ in Cleveland's 2-1 victory over the Red Sox
Saturday at Fenway Park that clinched the best-of-five American
League Division Series in four games. They came two innings apart
and they illustrated not only Justice's versatility but also his
dependability.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to play left field when the series moved to Boston. He
let management know about it, and after two games in Cleveland as
the designated hitter, he was in left for Games 3 and 4. The
Indians are mighty glad they made the change.
</P>
<P>
   Justice's big play in the field kept the Indians in the game.
His big play at the plate gave the Indians the lead and silenced
Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed you why David Justice is David Justice,'' said
Indians manager Mike Hargrove. ``He is able to do things like that
because he is a tremendous athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how it went down. The Red Sox led, 1-0, in the sixth
when John Valentin doubled to left. Justice almost nailed Valentin
then and there. He got a second chance a few minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   After Mo Vaughn popped to Kenny Lofton in center and Nomar
Garciaparra was intentionally walked, Mike Stanley lined a single
to left. Valentin was given the green light and Justice made him
pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I was thinking was catch the ball, but the
ball had such overspin that I knew I wouldn't be able to catch
it,'' Justice said. ``So I just needed to set up and make a throw.
I felt like I was going to make a perfect throw on one hop.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he surprised to see Valentin sent home? No. The company line
from the Indians clubhouse was that it was worth the risk in a
close game.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't even close. Justice's one-hopper was taken in by Sandy
Alomar, who had time for tea and crumpets before applying the tag.
</P>
<P>
   This was the way Justice envisioned himself helping the Indians.
He was a big star as the DH in Game 2, delivering a three-run
homer, and has by far the most postseason at-bats of any Cleveland
regular. But he also wants to play in the field, which can be a
challenge sometimes because of injuries. He underwent knee surgery
last November and was slow coming around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them to start me,'' he said. ``I'm a career National
Leaguer and I play defense, too. You can help your team as a
designated hitter, but if you're the DH and you're not hitting,
that's no good.''
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't the DH and he was hitting. He got the second and
last of the two hits off Pete Schourek, chasing the Sox starter
with a double to left-center in the sixth. He got to third but died
there.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the eighth. Lofton and Omar Vizquel delivered one-out
singles off Tom Gordon, and Justice was in the spotlight again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a man on third, so I was just thinking, `Don't strike
out or pop up,''' he said. ``If I just put the ball in play, I have
a chance to drive in a run and I was able to hit it pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I went up there, I said, `God, you have put me in
situations like this and here is a time when I need your strength.'
When I walked into the box, I said, `This may be my last at-bat for
the evening.' So I took the first pitch just to get a feel for his
velocity and then I was looking for a pitch I could handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon gave him a fastball and Justice sent a laser to the
triangle in center. Both runners scored. Justice ended up on
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hit it, I was just saying, `Thank you, God. Thank you,
God,' all the way to first base. You can check the tape,'' he said.
``I was so excited. But the way I hit it, I probably should have
had a triple.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been the only thing he didn't do all game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
