<HEADLINE>
VICTORY CELEBRATION LASTS JUST ONE WEEK FOR PRAIRIE VIEW A&AMP;M
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The after-party for the Prairie View A&AMP;M football team
lasted exactly seven days.
</P>
<P>
   A week after breaking its NCAA-record 80-game losing streak, the
celebration finally stopped for the Panthers. Grambling State
University unleashed a powerful second-half attack to turn out the
lights on the Panthers, 55-40, before a crowd of 33,549 in the Al
Lipscomb State Fair Classic last night at the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Grambling is now 2-2 overall and 2-0 in the Southwestern
Athletic Conference. Prairie View dropped to 1-3 overall and 0-2 in
the SWAC.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers entered the game on a high after last week's
record-breaking 14-12 victory against Langston University. Prairie
View rode that confidence builder into Dallas, and was tied with
GSU at the half, 21-21.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Tigers unleashed a scoring surge that brought the
Panthers to their knees. In particular, a 12-second spurt late in
the third period all but settled this battle.
</P>
<P>
   GSU fullback Rodney Beaudoin tallied his third touchdown of the
game on a 16-yard burst with 24 seconds left in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   On the ensuing kickoff, Prairie View's Kevin Bell fumbled at his
20, and Grambling's Vyron Brown picked up the ball and dashed into
the end zone for a 55-27 lead with 12 seconds to go in the period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think conditioning and the fact we had a little bit more
depth probably made the difference,'' GSU coach Doug Williams said.
``I told the kids before the game that Prairie View came to play,
and it was evident that they came to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the second half, Grambling moved ahead, 35-21, after
scoring a pair of touchdowns in 1:30. The first one came on a
47-yard pass from quarterback Lionel Hayes to David Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   The next touchdown came three plays after Prairie View's
third-string quarterback _ freshman Jamaal Foster _ entered the
game. Foster fumbled after he was stacked up in the backfield, and
defensive lineman Michael Johnson scooped up the ball and rambled
15 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fatigue and mental focus cost us,'' PV coach Greg Johnson
said. ``If we don't come in focused, we can't make plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a first for us \Rtrying to win two consecutive
games\S. But my kids played with a lot of heart and a lot of fight.
I was proud of them. But we didn't have enough people to play with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The one consolation for the Panthers is that they scored the
most points in a game since they defeated Bishop College, 44-21, in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   GSU tied the game at 21-21 with 4:34 left before halftime when
Lionel Hayes scrambled out of the pocket and found Scotty Anderson
for a 19-yard touchdown. Anderson caught the ball at the 10, and
did a tightrope job the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-play, 73-yard march was basically a gift from the
Panthers as they twice prolonged the Tigers' excursion with costly
penalties. On the latter one, the Tigers were in punt formation on
fourth-and-four. But an illegal substitution by Prairie View cost
it 5 yards and gave GSU a first down.
</P>
<P>
   Three plays later, Hayes connected with Anderson for the
touchdown. Hayes completed 20 of 35 passes for 341 yards for two
touchdowns, and also ran for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew Prairie View was going to be high, so we wanted to
jump out on top of them early,'' Hayes said. ``But I wasn't worried
about anything at the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were going to get it together. I knew our offense
was going to finally start clicking, and I knew our defense was
going to start making some plays.''
</P>
</TEXT>
