<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-SCHOUREK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDING SCHOUREK BALL RIGHT CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The gloom enveloping the Red Sox locker room lasted
long minutes. Player after player sat at his locker staring ahead,
seeing nothing or seeing the chance that had slipped away. Finally,
Pete Schourek stepped forward and spoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to answer many questions,'' the Red Sox' Game 4
starter began in the middle of the locker room. ``I just want to
say thanks to the Boston fans. You know, when I came out of the
dugout (at the start of the game), and they were behind me. I
really appreciated that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Achilles' heel of the Red Sox all season _ inconsistent and
weak hitting _ did in a Boston team that was good enough to beat
the Indians, if not any more teams in this postseason. For sure,
the fatal problem was not the choice of starter Saturday _ Schourek
over staff ace Pedro Martinez _ which had prompted an endless media
howl the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   If the media had been howling instead that Martinez should take
a bat in his hand and start in left field instead of Troy O'Leary,
that paragon of mediocrity, or in right field instead of Darren
Bragg, it might have been more to the point. Schourek proved the
howl was misplaced: The Red Sox had the right starting pitcher,
even though they wound up losing to the Indians, 2-1, and being
eliminated in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually got to say thanks to Jimy (Williams), too, for
putting his ass out on the line for me,'' Schourek said. ``You know
... I hope ... it felt like he made the right decision. I pitched
pretty good; it just wasn't in the cards for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek gave up no runs and a mere two hits in 5 1/3 innings,
walking four but proving as gutsy as his postseason ERA (1.35 in
four appearances spanning 26 innings) indicates.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, for instance, Travis Fryman doubled with
one out and stole third as yet another Red Sox catcher _ this time
Scott Hatteberg _ held the ball in a tight situation. But Schourek
got Richie Sexson with heat for a swinging strikeout and ended the
inning when Sandy Alomar grounded to Nomar Garciaparra at
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, after Fryman walked, Schourek ended the inning by
picking the Cleveland third baseman off first. And in the fifth,
Schourek walked Sexson and Alomar with one out but retired Enrique
Wilson on a long fly to right, allowing Sexson to reach third.
</P>
<P>
   Then he bore down again with a runner on third as Kenny Lofton
flied out to Darren Lewis in center for the third consecutive time.
It was clutch pitching at its best in a tight ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians were duly impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest,'' said Fryman, ``when he walked off the field
and got that standing ovation, I felt like clapping, too. I can't
imagine what pressure he must have been under. I've got a lot of
respect for Jimy Williams for sticking to his guns. The guy pitched
a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alomar concurred: ``Schourek pitched a great game. I don't
see how Pedro would do any better. He kept them in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And David Justice, whose two-run eighth-inning double off Tom
Gordon settled the series, paid the ultimate tribute: ``Schourek
was Pedro-like out there. Two hits, no runs. He did his job. How
much better is Pedro going to do than that? Schourek was
outstanding. He shut us down.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it made no difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a whole lot you can say,'' said Schourek.
</P>
<P>
   But you pitched a good game?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Could he be at least partially happy with his performance,
considering how the media had howled that he should be pushed off
the mound?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah ... but still, the bottom line is we lost. There's not a
whole lot more you can really think about or really say,'' said
Schourek. ``We're on our way home.''
</P>
<P>
   But not because of Pete Schourek.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
