<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-VANDERBILT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORNED FROGS EKE OUT VICTORY IN OVERTIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERRANCE HARRIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It could be that the fans in Amon Carter
Stadium are becoming accustomed to these on-the-edge-of-your-seat
and down-to-wire forays.
</P>
<P>
   That was certainly the scenario last night as the TCU Horned
Frogs needed to rally twice to escape with a 19-16 double-overtime
victory against Vanderbilt before 26,210 spectators. It marked the
third time in as many games at Amon Carter Stadium that the outcome
came down to the waning moments.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 12, Oklahoma won, 10-9, on a field goal in the final
seconds, and on Sept. 26, TCU's defense provided a late stand to
preserve a 35-34 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you, you don't leave early with this team. You better
hang until the end,'' said first-year TCU coach Dennis Franchione,
whose team improved to 3-1. ``Don't give up on these kids. They
won't, so don't you.
</P>
<P>
   ``You better stay there until the last tick is on the clock
because they will keep fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is exactly what the Frogs did in this non-conference
matchup after missed offensive opportunities and a subpar second
half forced them into an overtime situation.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs prevailed with a gutsy defensive performance in
overtime capped by a 4-yard touchdown run up the middle by tailback
LaDainian Tomlinson to seal the game. The win marked TCU's first
overtime victory and its first back-to-back triumphs since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't execute during the game like we should have,''
said TCU quarterback Patrick Batteaux. ``I don't know if we were
tired, but we just made a couple of mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the big thing is we executed in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   First-year kicker Chris Kaylakie kicked a career-best 50-yard
field goal to tie the game with :04 remaining and force overtime
after TCU ran its two-minute offense to near perfection down to the
Vanderbilt 33.
</P>
<P>
   But the Frogs found themselves forced in that situation after
allowing Vanderbilt to score 13 unanswered points in the second
half to rally and go ahead 13-10 on an 18-yard scoring run by
tailback Rodney Williams with 1:31 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   John Markham of Vanderbilt (0-4) kicked field goals of 49 and 26
yards in the second half to go with a 47-yarder in the second
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs' offense, meanwhile, sputtered during the second half
after missing three key scoring opportunities during the first two
quarters. Vanderbilt, stacking its defensive front during the
second half, stymied the TCU running attack with strong pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   TCU tailback Basil Mitchell finished with 125 yards, and
Batteaux had his strongest outing as a passer, 12-of-18 for 131
yards and one interception, but mental breakdowns throughout
preempted the offense's effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating, no doubt about it,'' said Franchione, who
was also coaching his first collegiate overtime game. ``Sound
defensive philosophy says make people drive it 80 or 90 yards and
they'll make a mistake. And eventually that happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get a first down, and we had the two turnovers in
the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   During the first half, it was only the Frogs who could stop
themselves. They managed to march into Vanderbilt territory on all
five offensive possessions during the half, but two turnovers and a
costly turf tackle preempted three potential scoring drives as they
held a 10-0 lead at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs made 18 first-half first downs and had 273 yards of
offense. With long and methodical drives, TCU won the time of
possession battle, 21:17 to 8:43.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson led TCU with 78 yards and a touchdown on the ground
during the first half. The Frogs, with four rushers over 30 yards,
completed the half with 196 rushing yards on 38 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   TCU put together a near-perfect opening 80-yard drive,
culminating in a 9-yard touchdown run by Tomlinson. The drive,
which lasted 13 plays and 5:57, including Batteaux pass completions
of 11 and 17 yards to receivers Michael Crawford and Mike
Scarborough, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Kaylakie kicked a 42-yard field goal in the second quarter
to put TCU ahead by 10 points with 11:44 to play in the half.
</P>
<P>
   TCU could have done much more damage were it not for a fumbled
handoff exchange between Batteaux and fullback Lance Williams on
the Vanderbilt 31-yard line in the second quarter and an
interception by Batteaux down on the Commodores' 16.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs also missed an opportunity when receiver Cedric James'
feet got tangled on a reverse for an 8-yard loss back to the
Vanderbilt 29 early in the first half. It stymied a drive that
ended two plays later when Kaylakie's 44-yard field-goal attempt
went wide right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
