<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-TECH-BAYLOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TECH STOPS 2-POINT TRY, DEFEATS BAYLOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ Two dormant offenses erupted after quarterback
changes last night at Jones Stadium, with Texas Tech's Rob Peters
and Baylor's Jermaine Alfred coming off the bench to produce a
combined 561 yards and six touchdown drives.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest piece of real estate covered by either player
was the final step Alfred took that carried him out of bounds
before throwing a potential game-tying, two-point conversion pass
with 1:10 remaining. That provided Texas Tech's winning margin in a
31-29 shootout.
</P>
<P>
   However, it did not end postgame disagreements between players
about the accuracy of referee John Laurie's call, which nullified a
catch in the end zone by Bears' receiver Derrius Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred, who was under heavy pressure while rolling toward the
right sideline, said he made sure he planted his foot in bounds
before leaping into the air to throw a desperation heave toward the
end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the feeling I was in,'' Alfred said. ``It's very
disappointing, but it was their call.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said Alfred clearly was in bounds, and a replay on the
stadium scoreboard seemed to support his conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad call,'' Thomson said. ``They did us wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Not in the mind of Taurus Rucker, the closest Tech defender in
pursuit of Alfred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most definitely, I saw his foot step out before he threw the
ball,'' Rucker said. ``Some calls went our way and some didn't. But
the last one definitely went our way.''
</P>
<P>
   It proved to be the difference between allowing the Red Raiders
(5-0, 2-0) to continue their best start in 22 years or running the
risk of surviving in overtime against the Bears (1-3, 0-2), who
closed a 31-16 deficit in the final 4:47.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred, who threw for 225 yards and a touchdown after entering
the game with 2:29 remaining in the third quarter, made the Red
Raiders sweat down the stretch and might have earned a starting
role in next week's game against Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's accurate to say we'll at least consider it,'' said Baylor
coach Dave Roberts, who lifted starter Odell James in the fourth
quarter for a second consecutive week.
</P>
<P>
   Tech coach Spike Dykes, on the other hand, said he definitely
plans on handing the reins to Peters, who rushed for 106 yards and
threw for 226 in his first extended action of the season. The Red
Raiders' projected starter during fall drills, Peters played little
in the team's first five games because of shoulder and thumb
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But he led the Red Raiders on touchdown drives of 80, 80, 80 and
66 yards last night. He capped the first with a 1-yard sneak and
hit Donnie Hart for a 38-yard touchdown strike on another.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was our starter when he got hurt, and I always said he'd be
the starter when he came back,'' Dykes said. ``Rob's a winner. He
looked even better than I'd hoped. He just got hot and we left him
in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters entered the game on Tech's third series and starter Matt
Tittle never returned.
</P>
<P>
   For a fifth consecutive week, Tech tailback Ricky Williams (29
carries, 159 yards) topped the 100-yard mark and scored two
touchdowns. For a fifth consecutive week, Hart grabbed a touchdown
pass. But this night belonged to Peters, who finished with 332
yards total offense and helped the Raiders build a 31-16 lead when
Williams scored his second touchdown with 6:44 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred, however, played a stirring game of beat the clock in
leading Baylor on a pair of seven-play touchdown drives covering 78
and 72 yards on the Bears' last two possessions. But he stepped out
of bounds on the game's biggest play.
</P>
<P>
   Or did he?
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't matter,'' Roberts said. ``It's what the
official called. I thought the officials did a good job. If we take
advantage of other chances we had, we never put ourselves in that
position.'' Extra points Nikia Codie, a senior from Cleburne,
blocked a second-quarter punt, giving the Bears a blocked kick in
each of their past three games. ... Ricky Williams' halftime totals
(12 carries, 21 yards, 1.8 average) marked the least productive
half of the season for the back who was the nation's leading rusher
coming into the game. ... Tech offensive guard Curtis Lowery
strained his knee in the second quarter and did not return.
</P>
</TEXT>
