<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK AGAIN! FEDERAL SURPLUS IS AN ILLUSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The estimated $70 billion budget surplus is a mirage.
Actually, it's worse than a mirage. It's the fictional creation of
cynical and duplicitous politicians who take advantage of the
public's ignorance of federal finance.
</P>
<P>
   Most media types lend credibility to the hoax by accepting
Washington's numbers at face value. One story this week proclaimed
it the biggest surplus ever and said government was ``on course to
continue piling up surpluses for years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be further from the truth. When the 1998 fiscal
year ended Wednesday, the ``Government finances'' table for that
day in The Kansas City Star business section showed the federal
government's total public debt at $5.439 trillion. When the 1997
fiscal year ended one year ago, the same table showed public debt
at $5.327 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   How, pray tell, could the budget be $70 billion in the black
when the national debt expanded by $112 billion? It can't in the
context of accounting integrity, but anything is possible when
Uncle Sam is doing the accounting.
</P>
<P>
   This year's budget surplus is largely attributable to excess
Social Security tax receipts. This extra revenue was spent and the
Social Security trust fund received a credit, which amounts to an
IOU.
</P>
<P>
   The games played with Social Security explain part of the trust
fund scam, but not all. Social Security is only the most visible of
the many government activities funded by tax receipts dedicated to
specific purposes. Other examples include taxes for such pursuits
as highway maintenance and air transportation infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   These activities also have trust funds because the amount spent
on them usually lags the total revenue collected by the tax levied
for the program. The surplus revenue, as with Social Security, is
spent and the trust fund gets the same sort of IOU that Social
Security gets.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do the IOUs credited to these myriad trust funds add to
the national debt, but debt is piled upon debt as those
nonmarketable Treasury IOUs earn interest.
</P>
<P>
   As discerning readers may have noticed, there is $182 billion
worth of difference between the $70 billion surplus and the $112
billion rise in outstanding debt. This implies, of course, that the
federal budget for '98 was really substantially in the red. The
amount may be debatable, but the reality is obvious.
</P>
<P>
   An actual surplus could not have occurred during a period when
the national debt rose. Thus, the surplus is a bookkeeping
artifact. Given the Wonderland nature of federal accounting, Uncle
Sam not only feels comfortable, but also proud, to be able to
proclaim a surplus.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the mendacity of the putative surplus that is
irksome, either. The accompanying claim that there will be a series
of surpluses with which to ``save'' Social Security and do other
good works is not true. All that is true is that debt load of
future generations is higher than it was last year.
</P>
<P>
   The nature and scope of this fiscal flimflammery underscore
several critical needs. One need is a federal accounting system
that prevents rather than abets financial fraud. Another is
abandonment of the trust fund system that allows the back-door
misappropriation of tax revenues for general budget purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, no reform will work until Americans learn enough about
federal fiscal practices to understand how the vaunted surplus is
the usual Washington smoke-and-mirrors trick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-04-98 0145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
