<SLUG> BC-DILBERT-ADAMS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DILBERT' CREATOR TAKES TEMPERATURE OF WORKPLACE CLIMATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ``Dilbert'' creator Scott Adams started
putting his e-mail address on his daily comic strip in 1993. Since
then, he's received hundreds of messages a day from workers who
share the pulse of their workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   Their tales of dehumanization and angst are depressingly
endless, right?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   Adams' newest book, ``The Joy of Work: Dilbert's Guide to
Finding Happiness at the Expense of Your Co-Workers'' may have a
cynical bent, but Adams says don't blame it on what he hears from
the work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not at all sad about the state of work right now,'' Adams
said in a telephone interview. ``I think people are generally
happier than they've been in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't get chains of complaints about low raises, impossible
bosses and excessive workloads. In fact, when he calls some of his
correspondents (yes, he does this on occasion), he finds that
almost all profess to be content with their pay and their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they're sort of schizophrenic,'' Adams said. ``They say
they like their jobs, but they'll (complain) like crazy about the
last 10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams theorizes the sustained, strong national economy and the
accompanying tight labor market created this climate of
contentment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may sound strange, but I think there's more recognition now
that everyone's a temp worker, that everyone looks at their jobs as
disposable,'' he said. ``Most everyone who was downsized _ or knows
someone who was downsized _ got a better job.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the economy is good, you know you can leave and get a
better job somewhere else. I think you rationalize that you must be
happy where you are or you'd be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get the impression, though, that Adams' new book is full
of corporate rah-rah and optimism. Far from it. Like his earlier
``The Dilbert Principle,'' it has the darkly comedic ``Dilbert''
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't make the mistake of working extra hard in hopes of
getting the biggest raise in your department. The difference
between performing at `exceeds expectations' levels versus `meets
expectations' is likely to be about 2 percent per year.
Mathematically speaking, in the long run you're much better off
doing a lousy job at something that looks good on a resume as
opposed to doing a superb job at something that sounds dull.''
</P>
<P>
   And:
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't invent the term Reverse Telecommuting, but I wish I
had. It refers to the process of bringing your personal work into
the office. It's the perfect place for paying bills, playing games,
checking on your stock investments, handling errands, calling
friends and making copies. To the casual observer, those things
look just like work.''
</P>
<P>
   In a related vein, Adams gives credit to a reader for exposing
him to ``multishirking'' _ the practice of doing two non-work
activities at once, thus doubling ``the odds that an observer will
think you're doing at least one work-related activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the book's title emphasizes having fun at the expense
of co-workers, Adams made no apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``All humor is at someone else's expense,'' he said. ``You can
poke fun at yourself, but there are more of them than you, so you
can always count on having a lot of material.''
</P>
<P>
   The cartoonist, who absorbed much ``Dilbert'' material in his
former job as a Pacific Bell cubicle worker, said workplaces in the
last couple of years seem to be less frenzied about adopting the
trendy business practice of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Adams suggested, some of the best elements of mission
statements, team building, re-engineering and so forth have ``taken
their proper place in the toolbox.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The overselling of these micro trends has been beaten back,
and we're left with something good,'' he said. ``People have been
educated and exposed to new processes.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``micro trend'' Adams says he's watching now, and expects to
focus on in upcoming strips, is ``EVA,'' the economic-value-added
concept that ``breaks your company into individual units to see if
the value of each is exceeding its cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Real companies don't work that way _ broken apart in units _ he
said. Organizations will realize, he predicted, that true value is
added by interaction between units, not by measuring individual
parts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-04-98 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
