<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8540 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     10-04 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Oct. 11.)  
 (HLW)  
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; The Wind-Up Bird Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Haruki Murakami. Translated by Jay Rubin. Vintage
International, $14.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's most popular novelist begins humbly enough with a young
man's search for his lost cat but before long tackles some mighty
heavy subjects: the transitory nature of love, the vacuity of
contemporary politics and the legacy of aggression in World War II.
``Murakami has written a bold and generous book,'' Jamie James
wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Miriam's Kitchen: A Memoir &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Elizabeth Ehrlich. Penguin, $13.95.
</P>
<P>
   This culinary meditation-cum-family history tells of the
author's deepening relationship with her mother-in-law, a Holocaust
survivor whose religion is one first of deeds -- mostly cooking and
housework -- and then of faith. ``The stories of Elizabeth and
Miriam's encounters, and the memories that they draw forth, are a
celebration of everyday life,'' Peter Kaminsky said here in 1997.
In  &UR; M.F.K. Fisher and Me: A Memoir of Food &AMP; Friendship &LR; , by
Jeannette Ferrary (St. Martin's Griffin, $14.95), a fan letter
leads to a complex relationship between the young California author
and the aging food writer, whose celebrated works are a continuous
reminiscence about places, people and herself. It becomes
abundantly clear that ``the rewards of thrilling friendships of
this kind are not only one way,'' Victoria Glendinning wrote in the
Book Review in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Reader &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Bernhard Schlink. Translated by Carol Brown Janeway. Vintage
International, $11.
</P>
<P>
   A high school student falls in love with a former Auschwitz
worker in this offbeat German novel about the moral failures of
``the lucky late-born,'' those too young to be held accountable for
Nazi crimes. The result is ``a moving, suggestive and ultimately
hopeful work'' that ``leaps national boundaries and speaks straight
to the heart,'' Suzanne Ruta said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; African Exodus: The Origins of Modern Humanity &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Christopher Stringer and Robin McKie. Owl/Holt, $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   The authors present a well-researched case for the ``out of
Africa'' model of human origins, which holds that Homo sapiens
arose on the African continent alone and then spread out across the
world. ``The interlocking patterns of the different kinds of
evidence ... give powerful support to the theory,'' Robert J.
Richards wrote here in 1997.  &UR; Eco Homo: How the Human Being Emerged
From the Cataclysmic History of the Earth &LR; , by Noel T. Boaz (Basic
Books, $14), argues that human evolution was driven by environment
changes -- particularly by climatic shifts -- and links mankind's
origins to the drying up of the Mediterranean five or six million
years ago, which turned the forests of North Africa into the
Sahara. Last year in these pages, Mark Ridley found this a
``stimulating and enjoyable'' book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Great Apes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Will Self. Grove, $12.
</P>
<P>
   This satirical novel imagines a world in which chimpanzees stand
at the top of the food chain and civilized behavior includes
promiscuous copulation and deferential public grooming. The plot
turns on the psychiatric treatment of a famous artist who suffers
from the delusion that he is human. ``What should have been the
literary equivalent of a parlor trick turns out to be an utterly
absorbing and affecting work of fiction,'' Gary Krist wrote here in
1997.  &UR; The Bear Comes Home &LR; , by Rafi Zabor (Norton, $15), features
the exploits of an alto sax prodigy given to quoting Shakespeare
and reading Stendhal: he also happens to be a 400-pound bear. Last
year in the Book Review, Bruce Allen said this first novel
``adroitly contrasts the bear's richly expressive inner life with
the impressions he makes on human companions.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In a Glass House &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Nino Ricci. Picador USA, $13.
</P>
<P>
   A lonely Italian boy and his infant half sister move to a
Canadian farm, where they struggle to adjust to a new life and
language. In 1995 our reviewer, Ron Hansen, called this ``a
haunting, lyrical, intelligent coming-of-age novel'' and ``a
genuine achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Art of the Impossible Politics as Morality in Practice:
Speeches and Writings, 1990-1996 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Vaclav Havel. Fromm International, $14.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the Czech Republic reveals a mystical side as
he discusses how to create citizens who are aware of both their
potential for evil and their obligation to do good. Last year our
reviewer, Douglas A. Sylva, admired ``the inspiring optimism of
someone who has seen the worst of humanity without losing faith in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; True Colors: The Real Life of the Art World &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Anthony Haden-Guest. Atlantic Monthly, $15.
</P>
<P>
   This scathing critique of the contemporary art world skewers
everyone in its path: artists, dealers, collectors and critics.
Last year our reviewer, David Kaufman, called the author ``a
valuable guide'' to an era in which esthetic concerns gave way to
purely mercenary forces.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Secrets of a Fire King: Stories &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Kim Edwards. Picador USA, $13.
</P>
<P>
   The characters in these far-flung stories -- whether circus
performers or Malaysian prostitutes -- find wonder, and terror, in
the familiar. ```The Secrets of a Fire King' gives eloquence to
their astonishing range of discoveries, and leaves the reader
entranced,'' Nina Sonenberg wrote here last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
