<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CoxNet Cox News Service budget
 &HT;    FOR MONDAY, OCT. 5, 1998
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For questions, please call 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   THE WEEKEND DUTY EDITORS ARE:
</P>
<P>
   IN ATLANTA: Chante LaGon at 404 526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   IN WASHINGTON: Art Dalglish at 301 460-6176 or (cell phone) 301
996-3036.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   DEMS _ WASHINGTON _ When he built his winning coalition for the
presidency in 1992, President Clinton relied heavily on fellow
southern Democrats like himself. This week, when he may need them
the most, many of those same southern Democrats are likely to break
ranks and vote to open a formal inquiry into whether Clinton lied
under oath, encouraged others to lie and obstructed justice in his
affair with Monica Lewinsky. The House Judiciary Committee will
meet today and may vote on opening the inquiry, with a full House
vote later in the week. About 75 Democrats may feel forced to vote
with the Republicans for an impeachment inquiry. Rep. Sanford
Bishop (D-Ga.), the only member of the Black Caucus who voted with
the Republicans in the Alcee Hastings impeachment, may be in that
position. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TV _ A look at which stations will carry the House
Judiciary Committee debate and vote live on today and Tuesday.
(Harris, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ WASHINGTON _ Rep. Henry Hyde, chairman of the House
Judiciary Committee, said Sunday he hoped the House could reach a
decision by New Year's on whether to impeach President Clinton. But
Democrats pressed for guidelines that would limit both the scope
and length of the House probe, saying they feared that otherwise it
could turn into a ``two-year fishing expedition'' for more charges
against the president. (Dalglish, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   Attention news and national editors:
</P>
<P>
   Starting Monday October 5, the Dayton Daily News will have
pictures available of John Glenn's training for the space shuttle
mission. If Interested, call Jeff Adams, Editorial Photo/Imaging,
at (937) 225-2118
</P>
<P>
   PRISON _ Gangs have come to occupy a central role in Texas
prisons. Even though gang activities are banned, membership has
more than quadrupled since the start of the decade. But rather than
separate gang members, prison authorities usually house them
together because they're easier to manage that way. And though
prison officials say they try to prevent gang activities, they have
in some instances enlisted gang leaders in efforts to maintain
order. A look at prison gangs behind the walls. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GANGSTERS _ Vignettes in which prison gang members discuss
racism, why they joined gangs, what life's like inside. (Ward,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   MAIL _ Prison officials play a cat-and-mouse game with gang
members that is worthy of the CIA. They intercept mail that's
written in code, in invisible ink that's made with urine and in
obscure places. (Ward, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   RENAUD _ Perspective on gangs from behind the bars written by
Jorge Renaud, former Statesman copy editor and convicted armed
robber who is serving time at the Wynne Unit in Huntsville. A
three-time loser who has been in and out of prison since the '70s,
he writes about his past experiences with prison gangs _ including
the time he witnessed a gang stabbing. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL REPORT: RIVERS IN THE SOUTH
</P>
<P>
   WATERWARS _ With its humid climate, bottomland swamps and lazy
streams, the South has long been regarded as water rich. But that
concept is evaporating. Because of the region's growth, experts say
there is not enough water to satisfy competing demands - for
consumption, waste treatment, development, hydropower, recreation,
irrigation and navigation. Nowhere are those concerns being aired
more dramatically than here, with Georgia, Alabama and Florida
negotiating to divide up the waters of the Chattahoochee and other
rivers flowing through the region. ``The stakes are huge,'' says
Aaron Wolf, who has consulted in international water conflicts.
``The tri-state water dispute has all the trappings of the bitter
water conflicts waged...in the dry Middle East between countries
like Jordan and Israel.'' A look at the blossoming water wars and
their potential impact on growth and environmental protection in
metro Atlanta. (Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 70 WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   APALACHICOLA _ For 50 years, Donny Wilson has reaped a rich
bounty from Apalachicola Bay: oysters, shrimp, crabs. His business
has survived hurricanes and droughts. But now, he sees a new threat
upstream. He is one of many fishermen expressing concern that
Atlanta's growing demand for water is siphoning off the water that
nourishes the bay's shellfish beds. ``We don't want to pay the
price for Atlanta's growth,'' he says. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30
</P>
<P>
   AGRICULTURE _ You didn't have to be a plant scientist to figure
out who irrigated their crops and who didn't this summer in
southwest Georgia. Long stretches of stunted corn and shriveled
cotton baked in bone-dry fields - farms without irrigation - while
others were green or lush with ripening crops, a sure sign of
watering. ``If I hadn't had irrigation, I would have been wiped
out,'' says farmer Jerry Long. Scores of farmers like Long fear
that the water for their irrigation wells could become a casualty
of the water wars. (Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30
</P>
<P>
   NAVIGATION _ The Georgia State Ports Authority's docks in
Columbus stand empty. Only 11 barges checked in on this inland port
on the Chattahoochee River in 1997. And shippers fear there may be
even fewer barges in the future, leaving barge navigation a
footnote of Southern history, a victim of the water wars.
(Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30
</P>
<P>
   WESTWARS _ Nebraska, Colorado and Kansas signed a deal in 1943
spelling out how much water each could use from the Republican
River. But it's been anything but an amicable deal. The squabble
may be an omen for Georgia, Alabama and Florida. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 7.
</P>
