   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   WORLDBANK-IMF (Washington) _ Developments; meetings; and social
events. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   WORLDBANK-ECON (Washington) _ Issues of economic development
from the World Bank. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ELECTION (Rio de Janeiro) _ Brazilians vote in
presidential elections. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PROTESTS (Moscow) _ Labor protests are expected this
week, with some protests today on the anniversary of Yeltin's
shelling of the White House. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA-POPE (Split) _ At a seaside Mass, Pope John Paul II
calls for ``reconciliation'' throughout the former Yugoslavia and
urges the world to do more for the victims of the Balkan civil war.
By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-POLITICS (Rome) _ The Communists say they will pull out of
the government over a budget bill. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT-SYRIA (Cairo) _ The Egyptian president flies to Syria in
an effort to calm tensions between Syria and Turkey over the Kurds.
By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CHIAPAS (San Juan Chamula) _ In a setback to the
government's efforts to pacify Chiapas, state elections are thrown
into question when the government's own supporters stage a
rebellion over five men arrested on murder charges. By Julia
Preston.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-GANDHI (Bombay) _ A banned play touches on Indians'
complicated attitudes toward Gandhi. By Celia Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   SPRINT-HEALTHCARE (Kansas City, Mo.) _ At the start of the '90s,
when employers' health insurance costs were surging 15 percent a
year, the giant Sprint Corp. was quick to shift to health
maintenance organizations and their businesslike management of
medical care. Sprint's costs promptly stabilized. Today, its
comprehensive benefit program stands as a model of what Congress
and industry envisioned four years ago when they rejected President
Clinton's health plan and left the health-care system to the tides
of the marketplace. Yet along the hallways at Sprint headquarters
here, the great expectations for managed care have dimmed. In a
score of interviews with workers and managers, no one recounted the
kind of HMO horror story that makes headlines: the wrong leg
amputated, a child denied a transplant. Instead, they had found
managed care to be exasperating, callous, and sometimes just
senseless. By Peter Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LAWSCHOOLS (Baltimore) _ The era of the permanent
investigation of the president has produced all sorts of legal
curiosities. The latest is a crop of courses at law schools across
the country that deal with investigating the president, like the
class that met in the downtown Baltimore law school on Friday
night. In such classes, leaks, politics and the president's
videotaped testimony are as important as the old precedents law
students have been poring over for generations. By William
Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   BEERLESS-BLAST (Cullman, Ala.) _ Cullman's annual Oktoberfest
kicks off this weekend. Only catch is, it's in a dry county; so the
Oktoberfest is beerless. So what's the point, you might ask. By
Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-SUIT (Undated) _ Developments concerning movement toward
a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Developments in advance of House
Judiciary Committee vote on Monday on the course of the
investigation. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR-RDP (Washington) _ Developments, as required. By
James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-NEWTERM (Washington) _ Curtain-raiser on new Supreme
Court term: census sampling case, sexual harassment in schools,
challenge to two-tier welfare policies, more redistricting, etc. By
Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
