A8581 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMS-COX     10-04 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern Democrats may cross party line in favor of formal probe
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When he built his winning coalition for the
presidency in 1992, President Clinton relied heavily on fellow
southern Democrats like himself.
</P>
<P>
   This week, when he may need them the most, many of those same
southern Democrats are likely to break ranks and vote to open a
formal inquiry into whether Clinton lied under oath, encouraged
others to lie and obstructed justice in his affair with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee will meet today and may vote on
opening the inquiry, with a full House vote later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, whose aides have been aggressively seeking censure
rather than impeachment, would like nothing more than a party-line
vote to substantiate the White House claim that the inquiry is a
partisan witch hunt designed to hurt the president and harm
Democratic chances in the Nov. 3 mid-term elections.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton won't get that. Some Democrats are already on record
saying they support an inquiry. Others, including Rep. Sanford
Bishop (D-Ga.), have remained largely silent, an indication of how
many Democrats are wrestling with such a politically potent vote
just weeks before the election.
</P>
<P>
   The political stakes for Bishop and other southern Democrats who
represent majority white districts are enormous. While national
polls indicate that most Americans are against impeaching Clinton,
there are strong regional differences.
</P>
<P>
   Many rural voters, who tend to be more conservative, are
outraged at Clinton's affair with a former White House intern half
his age and want Congress to act. Core Democratic voters,
especially black voters, want the inquiry to end quickly, leaving
some of these Democratic incumbents caught in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very polarizing in my district or any other district,''
said Rep. Charlie Stenholm (D-Texas), ranking member of the House
Agriculture committee, who represents a large ranching district in
west Texas. ``No matter what you do, someone is going to be unhappy
with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Stenholm said he will vote to proceed with the inquiry, a
position that is supported by fellow Texan Rep. Jim Turner
(D-Texas) and Rep. Bud Cramer (D-Ala.), whose Alabama district
includes Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``The few Democrats who represent conservative districts could
create real problems for themselves if they vote to exonerate
(Clinton) before the investigation is complete,'' said Whit Ayres,
a Republican pollster from Atlanta whose clients are drawn mostly
from the South.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Democrats who say they will vote for an impeachment
inquiry are so-called Blue Dog Democrats, conservative Democrats
whose ranks are drawn largely from the South. One Blue Dog, Rep.
Gene Taylor (D-Miss.), is already on record saying Clinton should
resign.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the predicament facing Georgia's Bishop, another
Blue Dog Democrat, is even more politically dicey. More than
one-third of Bishop's 2nd District is black. Nationally, black
voters have been Clinton's most loyal backers, saying they want
Congress to accept Clinton's apology and move on.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, members of the Congressional Black Caucus and other
white, liberal Democrats vented their frustration with the Clinton
investigation by offering a resolution to impeach independent
counsel Ken Starr for abusing his authority and attempting to
``demean, embarrass and defame'' the president.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop and Rep. Sheila Jackson-Lee (D-Texas) were the only
members of the black caucus who voted against the measure, which
was tabled 340 to 71.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop's district is also heavily agricultural and typical of
the more rural South, whose voters are more likely to be critical
of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Letters and phone calls to Bishop's Washington office have been
overwhelmingly in favor of impeaching Clinton or forcing him to
resign, said Selby McCash, Bishop's spokesman. Of 150 letters
received so far, 135 have been for impeachment, McCash said, and
phone calls have been three to one for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop will likely wait until the day he casts his vote on the
inquiry to state his position publicly. ``He really wants to give
himself every opportunity to understand this thing fully,'' McCash
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democratic strategists argue that the political pressure is
for Democrats to vote against proceeding with an inquiry, since
that is what national polls are saying Americans want. These
strategists warn that Democrats risk alienating their core
Democratic voters if they vote with the Republicans to take
impeachment to the next phase.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it do for a Democrat to stick a finger in the eye of
the Democratic base?'' said Mark Mellman, one Democratic
strategist. ``What does that do to turnout? In most places, the
(Democratic) base is clearly opposed to impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democratic strategists, however, say that such worries are
greatly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democratic voters can be opposed to his resignation or
impeachment even as they are appalled by his personal behavior,''
said Democratic pollster Alan Secrest, who has clients in the
South. ``But they aren't necessarily going to take it out on an
incumbent who votes to proceed with an investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Secrest said he is telling his clients to ignore the White House
line about how a vote for an impeachment inquiry could affect
turnout and worry more doing what's best for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 answer is follow your conscience,'' Secrest said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
