<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA TALK: SUIT AGAINST DISCREDITED WRITER; ANTI-PAPARAZZI LAW;
PARTY TIME IN L.A. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stories about journalistic invention have been distressingly
common these last few months, with their impact upon the
credibility of the news media well dissected. But what of the legal
consequences of questionable attributions and fictitious ``facts''?
</P>
<P>
   On June 29, DARE America, an anti-drug group, filed suit in
federal Court in Los Angeles against Stephen Glass, an associate
editor dismissed in May by The New Republic for making up people,
quotes and situations in several articles he had written for the
magazine. Among the articles was ``Don't You DARE,'' a critique of
the organization in which, the magazine has acknowledged, Glass
admitted inventing several of the people he quoted, including an
Illinois college professor who was supposedly harassed for research
unfavorable to DARE. Glass also wrote a similar piece about DARE
that subsequently appeared in Rolling Stone.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking $10 million in damages on grounds that it lost national
sponsors, DARE contends that Glass knowingly fabricated ``false and
defamatory articles'' meant to suggest that the organization
``regularly engages in harassing, threatening and terrifying its
critics.'' Skip Miller, the lawyer representing DARE, said the
group first considered legal action in 1997, when The New Republic
article appeared, and again in March, when the Rolling Stone piece
was published. But it was only when Glass admitted his fabrications
that the organization decided to sue.
</P>
<P>
   The two magazines have not been named in the suit, Miller said,
adding that his client was ``taking a separate, close look'' at
them, while engaging in settlement negotiations with Glass and his
lawyer, Gerson Zweifach. Zweifach declined to be interviewed for
this article.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers who handle First Amendment claims said the
complaint made a strong case for libel if not, perhaps, for
damages. Richard Emery, a former lawyer for the New York Civil
Liberties Union who is now in private practice, said the complaint
made a ``classic case for defamation.''
</P>
<P>
   Victor Kovner, whose clients have included publications like The
Village Voice, said, though, that other people had criticized DARE.
``If the gist of the criticisms about DARE are true,'' he said,
``they will have to show how the damages from these articles are
different from the damages from the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, at age 25, Glass presumably does not have the deepest
of pockets. ``I've never seen a situation like this, where the
magazines aren't also being sued,'' said Martin Garbus, the lawyer.
``Instead of money, I presume what they want from Glass is some
kind of retraction or formal apology.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bernard Stamler
</P>
<P>
   California Law Will Allow Celebrities to Sue Paparazzi
</P>
<P>
   Granting the wishes of an industry that at once promotes and
protects its famed charges, Gov. Pete Wilson of California signed
legislation last week intended to allow celebrities to sue
paparazzi for invasion of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The law will allow photographers to be found liable for invasion
of privacy if it is proved that they trespassed or used telephoto
lenses to capture images of people engaging in personal or familial
activity, and provides for hefty damage awards against both
photographers and their organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The law is thought to be the first of its kind in the country,
said Tom Newton, general counsel for the California Newspaper
Publishers Association. It is one of four measures pushed by
California legislators after the death of Diana, Princess of Wales,
in a car accident while being pursued by photographers in Paris in
1997. A similar measure is being sponsored in the U.S. Senate by
Sens. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., and Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's approval will certainly come as a pleasure to an
industry that already exerts considerable control over the
journalists who cover it, with stars often denying access to those
whose coverage they find unflattering and even at times demanding
the right to select the people who write profiles about them.
Indeed, the bill was supported by a virtual Hollywood A-list, in
addition to victims'-rights and law enforcement groups (the bill
extends the same rights to crime victims and exempts police from
liability).
</P>
<P>
   But it has drawn the opposition of major media organizations and
professional associations that while condemning the acts of tabloid
photographers, nonetheless fear the law will be used to punish
legitimate, aggressive reporting techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Erbin, a lawyer who represented NBC, CBS, ABC and CNN
during a committee hearing on the bill earlier this summer, said
stars sometimes encouraged intense personal coverage. ``They wish
to expose their private lives to their advantage, but don't want to
when it detracts from their celebrity,'' Erbin said. ``I'm not sure
you can have it both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Christian Berthelsen
</P>
<P>
   In the Battle for Advertisers, Parties, Parties Everywhere
</P>
<P>
   One of the great perks of working in the media department of a
New York advertising agency is the wining and dining you're treated
to. Even a lowly media planner has enormous discretion over where
an advertiser spends its money. But such largesse usually stops at
the banks of the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   That won't be the case in mid-October, when the American Society
of Travel Agents holds its annual conference in Los Angeles. Conde
Nast, the magazine company, plans to overwhelm the often-overlooked
Los Angeles ad industry with four parties over two nights.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest is being sponsored by Conde Nast Traveler. The
magazine uses the conference as the staging area for its annual
Readers' Choice Awards. Invitations for this year's black-tie
awards presentation on Oct. 14 resemble elaborate wedding
invitations.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 heavyweights from the travel industry _ foreign
ministers of tourism, general managers of hotels, airline marketing
chiefs and advertising folk _ are to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Other battles for the hearts, minds, stomachs and media budgets
will take place the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Architectural Digest has invited a select group of advertisers
and friends to the home of the film director Kathryn Bigelow, a
residence with ``the scale of an industrial warehouse and the
finesse of Japanese fabrication,'' the invitation says. The New
Yorker is sponsoring a dinner at the Cicada. Can't decide which to
attend? No matter, but feel free to drop by Bon Appetit's ``special
evening of cocktails, billiards, fine wines and cigars'' at the
Wine Merchant of Beverly Hills. The fun starts at 10.
</P>
<P>
   _ Greg Farrell
</P>
</TEXT>
