A8676 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN     10-04 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN'S DEPARTURE WILL BE RED SOX' LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Shame on the Red Sox for letting it come to this.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn is the heart, bones, and soul of the Red Sox
clubhouse. He is the Sox' best hitter and a true leader. He has
made himself part of the community more than any sports star in New
England history. And he is a black athlete who told the world he
likes living in Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is a free agent and he's probably played his last game
for the Red Sox. It's going to be about the money and the Sox are
going to tell you that Team X is offering just too much cash and
poor Boston just can't afford to match the offer. They will paint
Mo as the greedy guy who just doesn't want to stay here.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way it ended with Roger Clemens. The Sox dragged
their feet, then said it wouldn't be prudent to compete with
Toronto's whopping offer. It was too much money for a pitcher in
the ``twilight'' of his career. Boston lost the best pitcher in
franchise history in exchange for a draft pick, and Clemens has
gone on to win back-to-back Cy Young trophies, solidifying his
place in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Dan Duquette promised that he would not allow
Vaughn to leave the same way Clemens left. But it's happening
again. No doubt the offer Mo gets will be too eye-popping to match.
And that will be the team's spin _ Mo's too expensive. But everyone
who's been paying attention knows it never should have gotton to
this point.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, specifically Duquette and CEO John Harrington, have
alienated Vaughn and his family. Certainly, they have paid Vaughn
well and made sizeable donations to his youth foundation. But they
should have taken care of Mo's contract last winter when the
numbers would have been more reasonable. Instead, they took care of
everybody else and made it clear Mo was not part of their plan.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra was locked up well into the next century, even
though he had no leverage to leave until 2002. Troy O'Leary, Tim
Wakefield, Jeff Frye, and Tom Gordon were signed. Jimy Williams and
Duquette himself got extensions. And of course, Pedro Martinez was
given a six-year, $75 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no money for Mo. There was no urgency about
signing Vaughn. Then Mo harpooned himself with a drunken driving
arrest (he was acquitted) and management had the hammer.
</P>
<P>
   They used the hammer, demanding that Vaughn submit to alcohol
evaluation as a condition of any new pact. Then they kicked off a
massive public relations campaign, selling Nomar as the team's new
star. It was all Nomar all the time. Nomar was portrayed as the
anti-Mo. Duquette talked about how Nomar was a real ``baseball
player'' (as opposed to Mo, who must have been playing bocce all
these years). Nomar was a ``conditioned athlete'' (as opposed to
Mo, the sloppy town drunk).
</P>
<P>
   Nomar is the perfect Duquette player. He was drafted by Dan,
signed by Dan, promoted by Dan, and he has succeeded beyond all
expectations. Nomar says nothing controversial, considers public
relations an outside distraction, and goes about his work. Sound
like any GM you know?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all season Duquette avoided any positive mention
about Vaughn. When asked, ``Do you like Mo Vaughn?'' Duquette would
answer, ``Mo is a very good hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer was clear. The Duke didn't like Mo, probably because
Vaughn represented the previous administration. Take a good look at
the Sox roster, around the team offices, and the farm system. Most
of those who were here before Dan are gone or demoted.
</P>
<P>
   Among player personnel, Vaughn, John Valentin, and Trot Nixon
are the only holdovers from the prior regime. All have had their
chops busted by management. And now Vaughn is ready to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox of 1998 were Mo Vaughn's team. They will be Mo's
team until Mo leaves. Then they will be Dan's team and all will be
right with the Duquette Universe. The Duke must have majored in
Machiavelli at Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington, who controls the cash register, has not helped this
situation by letting Duquette snub Mo (remember the Duke talking
about Sox All-Stars Garciaparra, Pedro, and Flash when the 1999
All-Star logo was unveiled?) and by detailing the team's
negotiating strategy in the newspaper. Mo knows when he's being set
up to be the bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   If Mo goes, remember that he lit up the sky here for the better
part of the 1990s, emerging as a Sox leader of Tiantesque
dimensions. He put enormous pressure on himself in the spring of
1998, then responded with 40 homers, 115 RBIs, and almost a share
of the batting title. Remember, his last at-bat was a wall double
when the Sox needed a run to stay alive in the Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   Mo said the price would go up every day, and no doubt it has.
That's why it will be the Red Sox' fault if he goes. They'll claim
his price tag is too high if he leaves, but discerning fans know
the Sox should have taken care of Mo Vaughn long ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
