<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: CORNELL AND DUCHAMP; L.A. ART; BRIT LIT FEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Calif., Great Britain)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marcel Duchamp (1887-1968) and Joseph Cornell (1903-1972) were
friends and sometimes collaborators. Now the relationship between
the radical Duchamp (``Nude Descending a Staircase'') and the
influential Cornell, best known for the constructions called boxes,
will be explored at the Philadelphia Museum of Art in an exhibition
that will be on view from Thursday through Jan. 3. The exhibition,
``Joseph Cornell/Marcel Duchamp ... in Resonance,'' assembles 57
works by Cornell and 32 by Duchamp. Information: (215) 763-8100.
</P>
<P>
   Local Heroes
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 40 years of works by Los Angeles artists go on display
Wednesday at the Armand Hammer Museum of Art and Cultural Center at
the University of California at Los Angeles. The exhibition,
``Sunshine and Noir: Art in L.A. 1960-1997,'' complemented by
symposiums, talks and related exhibitions by other museums and
galleries, assembles more than 150 creations by some 50 artists in
many media: painting, drawing, sculpture, photography, video and
installation.
</P>
<P>
   Among the artists are Sam Francis, David Hockney, Richard
Diebenkorn, Bill Viola and Ed Kienholz. Continuing through Jan. 3,
the show, organized by the Louisiana Museum of Modern Art in
Humlebaek, Denmark, tries to reconstruct and expand the European
definition of American art by examining the contributions of these
artists and the specific cultural circumstances from which their
work arose. Information: (310) 443-7000.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution
</P>
<P>
   The literature of rebellion, the poetry of freedom and the
language of rock-and-roll are among topics to come under scrutiny
starting on Friday, when the 1998 Cheltenham Festival of Literature
opens in Cheltenham, England. In its 49th year and billed as the
world's longest-running book festival, this event, through Oct. 18,
gathers novelists, poets, biographers and academics, as well as
dramatists, cartoonists, artists, musicians and politicians, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare will be reassessed, and Giles de la Mare will evoke
the genius of his grandfather, the poet and novelist Walter de la
Mare, on the centenary of his birth. Helen Fielding (aka Bridget
Jones), John Fowles and William Boyd are also among the
attractions. As the bon mot flies, Cheltenham is 41 miles west of
Oxford. Information: 011-44-1242-22-79-79.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-04-98 1742EDT &QL; 
