<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT TREATS DEALT OUT AT BRIDGE GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there has been a decline of creativity in the American
kitchen, you can't necessarily blame Wendy, Ronald McDonald or that
hairless dog that hangs around taco parlors.
</P>
<P>
   Not nearly enough women play bridge anymore. At least not
between the hours of 1 and 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, at that hour wives and mothers are climbing into
tractor cabs, space capsules, police cars or the command bridge on
aircraft carriers. Or they are rapidly climbing the ladder in
corporate board rooms.
</P>
<P>
   That's all very well, but what kind of recipes will they be able
to pass on to future generations? That is, excluding the recipe
that begins, ``Remove pizza from box before placing in 450-degree
oven.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't capture the moments on film, but I have a strong
hunch that Beaver Cleaver's mother played a whole lot of bridge, as
did many others of her generation. And they left a legacy for their
well-fed offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the bridge-club ritual involved serving something
fattening to the ladies around the table. Sometimes it was a
luncheon dish. More often it was just a midafternoon dessert. You
could probably play bridge without cards. But you could not play
bridge without homemade fudge on each table.
</P>
<P>
   It was assumed that a homemaker who could serve a three-no-trump
treat in a card game with friends was capable of a culinary grand
slam on occasions such as Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   An enthusiastic Seattle cook named Bill Gannon recalls that his
mother's bridge club was known as ``The Hungry Eight.'' He
inherited her recipe box and decided he should share the wealth
with friends and relatives. He incorporated some of the recipes
into a Christmas booklet.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Gannon's friends reciprocated by sending him recipes of
their own so he compiled four more annual mailings. One of them
contained a recipe for the famous tomato soup served at the 4 B's
restaurants in Montana. Former Post-Intelligencer staffer Eleanor
Shaw introduced me to the soup, and to Gannon.
</P>
<P>
   4 B's Tomato Soup
</P>
<P>
   1 32-ounce can diced tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of baking soda
</P>
<P>
   9 ounces chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cream
</P>
<P>
   Into a pot dump the tomatoes, butter, sugar, soda, broth and
onion. Simmer for an hour. Heat the cream in a double boiler, add
to the soup pot. Stir and serve to six tractor drivers or eight
bridge players.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Bobbi Roumonada, whose parents founded the 4 B's, says
her father sometimes used whipping cream, but you could use
half-and-half. Bobbi also says she prefers to dump the cooked
tomato mixture into a blender or processor for just a quick hit
before adding the cream. She likes a few tomato chunks in the
finished product, but not a lot of them.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another recipe from Gannon's collection. He credits ``Bev
from Mercer Island'' for:
</P>
<P>
   Mercer Island White Chili
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pound boneless chicken breasts, diced
</P>
<P>
   3 shallots, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 18-ounce can tomatillos, drained and cut up
</P>
<P>
   1 10-ounce can chopped tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 7-ounce can diced green chilies
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon coriander seeds, crushed
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon dried oregano, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 cans white kidney beans (30 ounces total)
</P>
<P>
   Juice of one lime
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a large pot heat the oil. Brown the chicken hunks, then
remove. Add to the pot the shallots and garlic and saute until
soft. Stir in the tomatillos (Bev prefers Progresso green
tomatoes), tomatoes with liquid, the chicken broth, green chilies _
and don't forget the spices.
</P>
<P>
   Bring ingredients of the pot to a boil, reduce heat and simmer
20 minutes. Return chicken pieces to the pot and dump in the white
beans (cannellini). Cook until hot. Add the lime juice, salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Since Mercer Island is in the Gracious Living Belt, when Bev
divides the soup into four main-dish or six appetizer portions, she
offers guests chopped red onion, fresh chopped cilantro, avocado,
sour cream, shredded jack cheese and lime wedges, so they can
doctor the soup to their tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one other bit of advice:
</P>
<P>
   Never play penny-a-point bridge with a lady named Lucky.
</P>
<P>
   John Owen writes ``The Intermediate Eater'' weekly for the P-I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-04-98 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
