<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-REVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Next Georgia Tech game may make or break season
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Georgia Tech coach George O'Leary keeps telling his team to
approach this season as if it was playing 11 one-game seasons. The
Jackets's next game _ Saturday at N.C. State _ might be the one to
make or break the season.
</P>
<P>
   Beat N.C. State and the Yellow Jackets (3-1, 2-0 in ACC) are in
a position to fight Florida State and Virginia for the ACC title.
Lose to N.C. State, and Tech will have its work cut out to get to a
better bowl than the Carquest.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfpack (3-1, 2-0) has been the surprise of this college
football season, upsetting Florida State 24-7 and then following it
up with a 38-17 win over Syracuse last Thursday. Wide receiver
Torry Holt (29 catches, 594 yards, four touchdowns) is making a
case for being the top receiver in the country, and quarterback
Jamie Barnette is having a good year.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in N.C. State's loss to Baylor and near-loss to Ohio
University, and the Wolfpack vulnerabilities come to the surface,
but this N.C. State team is clearly Tech's toughest 1998 opponent
yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing with great, great effort and enthusiasm,''
O'Leary said. ``They've got their crowd behind them big time.
They're making big plays on offense and defense. Holt could be tops
in the country. What doesn't he have? He's strong. He's quick. He
can catch. He's got big hands.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what Tech has planned for Holt defensively is yet to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Jamara Clark is Tech's best cover man, but he won't
be asked to take Holt on by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anybody in the country who can cover him
one-on-one,'' O'Leary said. ``(But) If you overload on him, they've
got two other receivers who can beat you.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Tech, here are some observations by O'Leary following
Saturday's 41-13 victory over Duke:
</P>
<P>
   -Good: Joe Hamilton. Big plays on offense, like Hamilton and Dez
White hooking up for a 53-yard touchdown on Saturday. Offensive
balance.
</P>
<P>
   Creating turnovers on defense. The Yellow Jackets forced two
Duke
</P>
<P>
   turnovers and scored 10 points off of them.
</P>
<P>
   -Bad: Dropped balls. Tech had six of them against Duke.
``They're running before they have the ball,'' O'Leary said. ``You
can't do that in a
</P>
<P>
   big game.''
</P>
<P>
   -Worrisome: The health of backup quarterback George Godsey, who
pulled his hamstring at the end of Tech's practice on Thursday.
Without him against Duke, Tech had to risk playing Hamilton for the
entire game.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said the plan was if Hamilton had to come out and the
game wasn't close to use walk-on Alex Thompson. If the game was
close and Hamilton had to come out, he'd use true freshman Jermaine
Crenshaw. O'Leary said he'll use the same plan this week if Godsey
is unable to go. The difference is Thompson will have more than one
light practice day to get prepared for something besides running
the scout team in practice. O'Leary doesn't want to use Crenshaw if
at all possible, so he can redshirt him and save him a year of
eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   UP NEXT FOR GEORGIA TECH
</P>
<P>
   Opponent: N.C. State
</P>
<P>
   When: Saturday, 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Carter-Finley Stadium, Raleigh, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   TV, radio: WSB, WGST (640 AM, 105.7 FM).
</P>
