A8708 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-HUMMER-COX     10-04 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-HUMMER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves' celebration, excitement not missed by a single player
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before the games get really grim, while there is still
time to revel in small pleasures, let us visit those precincts in
the Braves clubhouse where beating the Chicago Cubs was more than a
duty.
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga had little to do with the outcome in this
division series, scoring one of the Braves 15 runs, driving in
none. The September preceding it was sleepy, with only two home
runs and nine RBIs. Still, there was no smile broader or more
genuine than Galarraga's in the champagne backwash of the Wrigley
Field visitors' quarters Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they (the rest of the Braves) get used to it, but this
is pretty special. Thirteen years and only two times in the
playoffs for me. And this is the first time I've won one. Yes, it's
really exciting,'' said Galarraga, one big, happy cat.
</P>
<P>
   So, stand back and let him roar: ``I hit .250 (in three games
against the Cubs). One-for-four, I'll take that every game if we
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've won a batting title (1993), an RBI title ('96), but this
is different. This is something special. I am really focused on
these playoffs. I want one of those rings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have managed a high level of sameness in the 1990s by
constantly changing. That's the baseball biz. Bream before McGriff
before Galarraga. And with each alteration, there comes a fresh way
to look at the Braves experience.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga proved himself a loud celebrant, whooping it up on a
Saturday night, often in his native tongue. Turns out he's a hugger
as well, slapping an unbreakable, WCW-approved hold on any teammate
or coach who happened by. And why not? At 37, he finally enjoyed
the playoffs, regardless that it was but the soup course, and a
thin broth at that. Six years in Montreal never led to anything.
His only other postseason experience was a brief flirtation in
Colorado in 1995, quickly ended by these same Braves. Bear with him
if he treats this like a major breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves can use a little giddiness at such junctures. They
can be as stiff as Oren Hatch's collar. All business, no happy
hour. New perspectives on another 100-win season and another
division series put early to bed are most welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss fits the Braves mold perfectly. Plays hard, plays
smart, plays like he means it. Where there was Blauser there is now
Weiss, playing a higher level of shortstop. This first-timer in the
Braves postseason parade brings yet another slant to October.
</P>
<P>
   When he began, Weiss thought the World Series was a logical
extension of the season. ``I break in, and like that, three
straight World Series,'' he said. Weiss was a light-hitting
infielder for the Oakland A's during their last gasp of glory
(1988-90). But then reality intruded. He never won another
postseason set, never sniffed another World Series, until signing
this year with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't take any of this for granted,'' he said. ``I realize
how hard this is. You really don't know when you're going to get
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Galarraga, lead-off man Weiss did not exactly bludgeon the
Cubs. He hit only .154, but did score the winning run in the
10th-inning of Game 2. Let 'em celebrate in peace. More will be
asked of them soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
