<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8721 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WATERWAR-COX     10-04 2282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATERWAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Chattahoochee: River in peril
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With its humid climate, vast stretches of bottomland
swamps and lazy meandering streams, the South has long been
regarded as water-rich. But that concept is fast evaporating.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the region's phenomenal growth, experts have come to
a stark conclusion: No longer is there enough water to satisfy all
of the competing demands for the precious liquid _ for consumption,
waste treatment, hydropower, recreation, irrigation, wildlife
protection, navigation and industry _ and at the same time ensure
an adequate supply for future development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current water management systems were not planned to deal
with this kind of growth,'' says David Feldman, a University of
Tennessee water expert.
</P>
<P>
   This summer's scorching agricultural drought, as well as dry
spells in the 1980s, has heightened concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Fears of future water shortages have prompted Southern states to
draw up battle lines. Virginia and Maryland are squabbling over the
Potomac River, and North Carolina and Virginia have gone to court
over the use of water from Lake Gaston along their border.
</P>
<P>
   But nowhere is a struggle over water being played out more
dramatically than the conflict pitting Georgia against sister
states Alabama and Florida. Their intense, complex and sometimes
acrimonious negotiations to divide up the waters of the
Chattahoochee and other rivers flowing through the tri-state region
are being closely monitored across the nation by water experts, who
fear the same thing is in store for their states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are huge,'' says Aaron Wolf, a water policy
specialist at Oregon State University who has consulted in national
and international water conflicts. ``The tri-state water dispute
has all the trappings of the bitter water conflicts that were waged
in the arid Western states, and even in the dry Middle East between
countries like Jordan and Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf says the settlement of the current tri-state water squabble
will be a ``turning point'' in the South's history. ``The water
wars are going to play out in areas where you never, ever thought
water would be an issue,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That may be especially true in Georgia. In exchange for
guarantees of enough water for growth over the next 30 to 50 years,
Georgians may have to pay higher electricity rates as hydropower
production is reduced. Strict limits on water for irrigation may be
imposed on southwest Georgia farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Navigation at Georgia's inland ports at Bainbridge and Columbus
may be curtailed. Industries and municipalities _ and the people
they serve _ may have to pay more to treat wastes discharged into
rivers because of less water to dilute the effluent. In metro
Atlanta, permanent restrictions on outdoor watering and other stern
conservation measures may be put in place. As early as 2025, the
metro area probably will have to find sources of water other than
the Chattahoochee.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of water that counties and cities can withdraw from
rivers and streams is set by permits issued by the Georgia
Environmental Protection Division. The permitted amounts are based
on the water needs of each locale and how much water is available
in the waterways.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be fair to our sister states in allocating water from
rivers flowing across our borders,'' says Bob Kerr, who is
negotiating on behalf of Georgia. ``At the same time, we also
expect them to be fair. If they demand that Georgia control its
growth, they must be willing to do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He and negotiators for Florida and Alabama are operating under
the authority of two interstate water compacts _ the first ever in
the South _ approved last year by the three state legislatures and
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In one compact, Georgia, Florida and Alabama are fighting over
the use of the Apalachicola, Chattahoochee and Flint rivers and
their tributaries, the so-called ACF basin. The Apalachicola in the
Florida Panhandle is formed by the merging of the Flint and
Chattahoochee in southwest Georgia. In a second compact, Georgia
and Alabama are squabbling over the Alabama, Coosa and Tallapoosa
rivers and their tributaries, the ACT basin.
</P>
<P>
   In most water wars, the conflict boils down to upstreamers vs.
downstreamers. People living upstream have first call for the
water. Those living downstream fear the upstreamers will hoard it
or make it unfit for use, leaving less water for downstream use.
</P>
<P>
   In the tri-state water war, Georgia is the upstream state _ all
of the rivers have headwaters in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Also upstream is metro Atlanta, a water glutton that sits 80
miles from the headwaters of the Chattahoochee. Seventy percent of
the metro area's 3 million inhabitants get their water from the
river and dump their treated wastes into it. An additional 20
percent get water from the ACT basin, which also includes the
Etowah River.
</P>
<P>
   And the Flint River basin, whose headwaters are just below
Hartsfield International Airport, is a main supplier of water for
fast-growing Henry, Fayette and Spalding counties and other areas
south of metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   As early as three decades ago, people in west and southwest
Georgia, southeast Alabama and northwest Florida were casting wary
eyes upstream, worried that metro Atlanta's wildfire development
and ever-increasing water withdrawals from the Chattahoochee would
rob them of water needed for growth in their own areas.
Furthermore, Atlanta's use of the Chattahoochee as a dump for waste
water meant much of the water coming downstream was too polluted
for use.
</P>
<P>
   Droughts in 1981, 1986 and 1988 _ and now 1998 _ heightened
downstreamers' concerns. The impact was more severe because growth
had increased the competition for water. During the dry spells of
the 1980s, hydropower generation and commercial navigation were
drastically reduced to conserve water for drinking and waste
treatment in metro Atlanta. Metro Atlantans faced outdoor watering
bans, with hefty fines for violations.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1986 drought _ and in this year's dry spell _ scores of
counties were declared agricultural disaster areas. Across the
South, crops worth more than $1 billion were wiped out in the 1986
heat wave. That same year, the Alabama National Guard was mustered
to truck water into cities that faced severe water shortages. Those
impacts alarmed government planners, especially those in metro
Atlanta, who feared that the consequences of future droughts would
cause greater water shortages as the region added people and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows when a drought will begin or when it will end,''
says Harold Reheis, head of the Georgia Environmental Protection
Division. ``We have to plan as if a drought is always imminent.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers announced a plan to
reallocate 20 percent of the water normally reserved for power
generation in Lake Lanier to drinking water. The plan was designed
to ensure an adequate water supply for Atlanta through 2010. But
the decision sparked a howl of protest in Alabama and southwest
Georgia. Then-Alabama Gov. Guy Hunt demanded that the reallocation
plan be suspended until the corps conducted a detailed analysis to
determine the impacts on downstream users.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, however, went ahead with another controversial plan: In
June 1990, Georgia asked the corps for a permit to construct a
4,200-acre reservoir on the Tallapoosa River only five miles
upstream from the Georgia-Alabama line. The lake was to be the
first of a dozen or so state-built regional reservoirs that would
circle metro Atlanta and ``drought-proof'' North Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the corps received Georgia's request, Alabama
sued the corps in federal court. The suit claimed that the corps,
by acceding to Georgia's demands, would be unable to operate Lake
Lanier and other federally built reservoirs in the ACF and ACT
basins in a neutral manner. Georgia's plan, Alabama said, would
vest Georgia with expanded water rights at the expense of
downstream users.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta was not going to grow at our expense,'' says Walter
Stevenson, the negotiator for Alabama. ``We felt Georgia wasn't
treating us fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Georgia intervened on the side of the corps,
and Florida sided with Alabama. Florida contended that hoarding
water upstream for metro Atlanta would jeopardize growth in
northwest Florida, as well as oyster beds and marine life in
Apalachicola Bay. With the filing of the lawsuit, the South's first
interstate water war was on. It quickly became bitter. At one
point, Georgia threatened to withhold permits for some Alabama
companies to withdraw water from the Chattahoochee.
</P>
<P>
   The downstreamers' demand for more water was perceived as a
threat to Georgia's sovereignty. A University of Alabama study says
Georgia was reluctant ``to even recognize Alabama's claim to the
Chattahoochee as the official border'' between the two states.
Georgia says the border is the west bank of the Chattahoochee and
therefore the river lies wholly within Georgia _ a right it claims
as one of the original 13 states.
</P>
<P>
   As the dispute worsened, the governors of the three states in
1992 called a truce. Out of that came an agreement, with each state
pledging to cooperate in devising a plan to share rivers flowing
through the states. Georgia's plan to build regional reservoirs was
put on hold. The states and the corps also agreed to conduct a
comprehensive study, which so far has cost about $20 million, to
analyze how much water is available in each basin, how much each
state needs based on growth projections, and the possible economic
and environmental consequences of meeting those needs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, negotiators for the three states created two
commissions _ made up of the governor of each state or his
representative, and a federal representative appointed by President
Clinton _ to devise a formula by the end of this year to divide up
the basins' waters. The commissions agreed to use findings from the
comprehensive study as a basis for negotiations, which began in
February. The study was supposed to have been completed in the fall
of 1996, but portions are still unfinished.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the negotiators say they have enough data for serious
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be sure we don't give up anything we don't have
to,'' says Kerr. ``What we give up, we give up in perpetuity.''
</P>
<P>
   In public negotiations so far, one thing is clear: No one will
get all they want. The intensity of the negotiations has caused
some acrimony. For instance, to the consternation of Alabama's
negotiators, Georgia announced in May that North Georgia's
population growth already nearly exceeds the forecasts of the
comprehensive study. The state's mid-1997 population estimates for
counties served by the two basins already approach the study's
projections for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama officials, however, accused Georgia of pulling numbers
out of ``thin air'' to support its claims for more water.
Alabamians also are wary of Clinton's federal appointee, Lindsay
Thomas, to the commissions.
</P>
<P>
   He is a former Georgia congressman and head of the Georgia
Chamber of Commerce, and Alabama officials fear he might favor
Georgia at their state's expense.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas says he will strive to be fair to all. ``My primary goal
is to look out for the interests of the federal agencies, such as
the Corps of Engineers,'' he says. The corps will play a major role
in any water allocation formula worked out by the states because it
operates the big dams on the Chattahoochee that control the flow of
the river over most of its 436 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas has the authority to concur with or veto whatever
agreements the state negotiators reach. A veto would automatically
dissolve the compacts and send the water war to the Supreme Court.
If that happens, no state may get what it wants.
</P>
<P>
   The public deliberations are now in the eighth month, but
negotiators say there is still much work ahead. Georgia was the
first state to put some numbers and a controversial proposal on the
table. In essence, its plan for sharing the waters of the
Apalachicola, Chattahoochee and Flint basin calls for maintaining
water levels in Lanier and two other reservoirs at higher levels
than in the past, which would entail reducing hydropower generation
and possibly navigation.
</P>
<P>
   Florida and Alabama are both suspicious of the plan. Florida
possibly would have to accept a reduction in flow in the
Apalachicola River. Meanwhile, Alabama's own recently unveiled plan
calls for releasing more water than normal from Lanier to increase
flows in the Chattahoochee. Georgia says Alabama's plan is
``unrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Some authorities believe the competition for water in the ACF
and ACT basins is so complex and the differences between Georgia's
and Alabama's plans so huge that the negotiators are not likely to
reach agreement by the end of the year, or for several more years.
</P>
<P>
   But Wolf, the Oregon State expert who has studied dozens of
national and international water treaties, believes water may
actually draw the states closer together.
</P>
<P>
   He notes that some analysts predicted the contest for water in
the Middle East could spark a gun-shooting, missile-firing war
there. Instead, water has proved to be a source of cooperation
among some old enemies. In 1994, for instance, Israel and Jordan
signed a historic agreement to share their water resources
amicably. ``If Israel and Jordan can do it, I think Georgia,
Alabama and Florida can do the same thing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
