<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8722 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGRICULTURE-COX     10-04 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGRICULTURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Farmers sow worry of lack of water
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAINBRIDGE, Ga. _ You didn't have to be a plant scientist to
figure out who did and did not irrigate their crops this summer in
southwest Georgia. You only had to travel the rural roads and gaze
at the fields.
</P>
<P>
   Long stretches of stunted corn and shriveled cotton baked in
bone-dry fields, while others were green or lush with ripening
crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't had irrigation, I would have been wiped out,''
says Jerry Long, 49, who runs a you-pick-it farm planted with 20
different vegetables in Decatur County. ``This is the most I've
irrigated since 1977, when we had one of the worst droughts on
record here.''
</P>
<P>
   With Georgia's agricultural losses from the summer's drought
approaching $500 million, about the only farmers in southwest
Georgia who stand to make a decent profit this year are those who
sprayed water on their fields. Those who didn't irrigate gambled on
adequate rainfall, which didn't come.
</P>
<P>
   But scores of farmers like Long believe that the free-flowing
water from their irrigation wells could become a casualty of the
water war between Georgia and sister states Florida and Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Studies by the U.S. Geological Survey and the three states show
that irrigation in a 10-county area of southwest Georgia can divert
hundreds of millions of gallons a day from the Flint and
Apalachicola rivers. The Flint flows across southwest Georgia and
meets up with the Chattahoochee at the Florida line to form the
Apalachicola, which winds across the Florida Panhandle to
Apalachicola Bay and the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the farmers say they feel caught in a squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   Downstream from them, Florida officials demand that a certain
flow be maintained in the Flint and Apalachicola to keep fish and
oysters in Apalachicola Bay healthy, especially during dry periods
_ precisely when farmers are most likely to irrigate.
</P>
<P>
   Upstream, metro Atlanta is eyeing the Flint or its tributaries
as sources of additional drinking water. One possibility is that
fast-growing Henry, Fayette, Spalding and other counties south of
Atlanta will draw more water directly from the river. Another
possibility is that Atlanta's expanding northern suburbs will be
forced to tap new water sources other than the Chattahoochee, and
thus more water will be drawn from the Flint and transferred to the
Chattahoochee basin.
</P>
<P>
   The state Environmental Protection Division issues permits for
increased water withdrawals based on supply and demand. But if
metro Atlanta is allowed to take more water out of the Flint, the
farmers say, there will be less water coming down the river and
probably more restrictions on pumping of ground water in southwest
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Florida and Atlanta to respect our rights; we have a
right to what God has put down here for us,'' says Oscar Jackson, a
Bainbridge dentist who represents the region on an advisory
committee appointed by Gov. Zell Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kerr, who represents Georgia in negotiating an agreement
with Alabama and Florida to divide the waters of the Chattahoochee
and other rivers, acknowledges that caps probably will have to be
put on irrigation in the 10-county southwest Georgia area _
including Baker, Calhoun, Decatur, Dougherty, Early, Lee, Miller,
Mitchell, Seminole and Worth counties _ to help Georgia satisfy
water needs elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers in those counties in 1996 planted 153,000 acres of corn,
317,000 acres of cotton and 179,000 acres of peanuts. Irrigation
equipment _ southwest Georgia has about 4,500 irrigation systems _
was capable of watering roughly half of that total acreage, by far
the greatest concentration of irrigated farmland in the entire area
drained by the Apalachicola-Chattahoochee-Flint river basin.
</P>
<P>
   Most farmers who irrigate in southwest Georgia draw their water
from the Floridan aquifer, a massive underground reservoir that
stores water in a huge formation of pocked and cracked limestone.
Like a giant tilted sponge, the formation sops rainwater from as
far north as Middle Georgia and drips it out through springs along
the lowlands of the Flint, south of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The water seeping from the aquifer is critical for maintaining
the flow of the Flint and Apalachicola. According to a U.S.
Geological Survey study, the two rivers lose about six-tenths of a
gallon of flow for each gallon pumped from the aquifer. During the
October low point of the severe drought of 1986, agricultural
withdrawals knocked already-low flows in the Apalachicola down by
6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the information we have indicates that southwest Georgia
farmers consume in a dry year more water for irrigation than all
the 3 million people in metro Atlanta consume, now and into the
future,'' says Harold Reheis, director of the Georgia Environmental
Protection Division.
</P>
<P>
   However, he says, about 70 percent of water used for human
consumption is returned to the rivers as treated waste water, while
very little for agricultural use gets back into the streams. Also,
farmers currently face fewer regulations than the state's other
major water users: Farmers' withdrawal permits don't expire, and
they need not report their usage. The farmers pay nothing for the
permits, and the water they withdraw is free.
</P>
<P>
   By all indications, southwest Georgia farmers will require more
irrigation. Banks are becoming more reluctant to lend money to
farmers who don't have irrigation systems. And the more valuable
cash crops and higher yields that many farmers hope to harvest
require more water. Crop yield can be as much as 100 percent
greater on irrigated acreage.
</P>
<P>
   But Reheis says the Floridan aquifer doesn't have enough water
to meet projected irrigation demands during the next 50 years,
``unless we allow the Flint to run dry, and we can't let that
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Those projections could change as numerous uncertainties about
irrigation are cleared up. Researchers acknowledge, for instance,
that their understanding of the Floridan aquifer's flow and storage
capabilities is still far from precise. Also, how irrigation should
be applied to crops under differing drought, rainfall, soil and
crop conditions is not fully understood.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr says most southwest Georgia farmers probably are aware of
the limitations on the Floridan aquifer, ``and the state will work
with them to develop strategies for conserving water.'' Replacing
wasteful irrigation systems with more efficient but more expensive
``center-pivot'' systems is one alternative. Another possibility is
drawing water from smaller, still untapped aquifers.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Long, the Decatur County vegetable grower, says Atlanta
probably deserves some additional water. ``But we deserve water for
our farms, too; people have to have food,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
