<DOCNO> NYT19981004.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8723 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APALACHICOLA-COX     10-04 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APALACHICOLA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A Harvest from the sea
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1988 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apalachicola, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   APALACHICOLA, Fla. _ For most of his 50 years, Donny Wilson has
reaped a rich bounty from Apalachicola Bay: oysters, crabs, shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   His seafood business, a whitewashed warehouse at the edge of the
bay, has survived hurricanes that wiped out huge swaths of oyster
beds and severe summer droughts that deprived the bay of freshwater
vital for the bay's succulent marine life.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he sees the next big threat coming from nearly 500 miles
away: metro Atlanta. He and dozens of other Apalachicola watermen
believe Atlanta's mushrooming growth and unceasing demand for more
water are siphoning off the fresh water that nourishes the bay's
world-famous oysters.
</P>
<P>
   ``More water for Atlanta means less water for us,'' he says.
``We don't want to pay the price for Atlanta's growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Apalachicola Bay is unique among Florida's waters. It's at the
end of the Apalachicola-Chattahoochee-Flint river basin, which
drains some 12.5 million acres in Georgia, Florida and Alabama. The
Chattahoochee's water first dribbles out of a spring on the side of
a mountain in North Georgia and then flows 436 miles across the
Piedmont and coastal plain to the Florida border, where it meets up
with the Flint and forms the Apalachicola.
</P>
<P>
   The Apalachicola winds 108 miles across the Florida Panhandle
and at the bay empties into the Gulf of Mexico. The river
transports into the bay tons of nutrients picked up from upstream,
crucial nourishment for oysters and other marine life. The fresh
water keeps the bay from getting too salty. High salinity levels
attract oyster predators such as starfish and conchs that normally
stay out to sea where the saltier water is more to their liking.
</P>
<P>
   The bay's delicate environment has made it a cornucopia for
seafood. It accounts for about 90 percent of Florida's commercial
oyster fishery and 10 percent of the nation's. Wilson sells his
seafood to wholesalers along the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Water quality experts say Wilson's concerns about Atlanta are
legitimate. They agree that metro Atlanta's demands for more water
from the Chattahoochee could cut freshwater flows into Apalachicola
Bay. But by how much is subject to much scientific debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any decrease in historical flows of fresh water into the bay
would cause some mortality to oysters and other marine life
there,'' says John Klein of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration. ``The greater the reduction, the higher the
mortality.''
</P>
<P>
   Of equal concern is the timing of the flows. The health of
oysters and other marine life depends on higher amounts of
nutrient-laden fresh water at certain times of the year, such as in
spring. Curtailing flows during those periods could be even more
destructive to the marine organisms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to have those periodic slugs of water, the peaks and
valleys,'' says Woody Miley, manager of the Apalachicola National
Estuarine Research Reserve. ``It's quite possible for the bay to
starve to death if the timing of these flows isn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why our primary concern is to maintain the historical
seasonal flows of fresh water into the bay,'' says Doug Barr, who
is negotiating on Florida's behalf with Alabama and Georgia on a
formula to divide up the waters of the basin.
</P>
<P>
   Barr and other water experts see an even bigger threat to the
bay than metro Atlanta _ the farmers in southwest Georgia who
irrigate their farms with ground water from the vast
Floridanaquifer. Farmers are most apt to irrigate from May through
August _ when the bay's oysters are most in need of fresh water.
</P>
<P>
   Irrigation by farmers in the Florida Panhandle and a sliver of
southeast Alabama, and plans to develop thousands of acres of
pulpwood forests owned by St. Joe Co. in the Panhandle, also may
affect the bay. But Georgia's irrigation practices far outweigh
whatever effects the other activities may have, state and federal
studies show.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia officials argue that some of Apalachicola Bay's problems
were brought on by Florida itself. Florida sliced a canal called
Sikes Cut through St. George Island on the outer perimeter of the
bay to allow easier access to the Gulf for barges and fishermen.
The cut has significantly increased salinity levels of the bay. In
addition, paper companies have drained tens of thousands of acres
of swampland around the bay, reducing the seasonal flows of
nutrients and freshwater from the wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   The bay's biggest freshwater contributor by far, however, is the
Apalachicola River. A controversial proposal that Georgia has
placed on the negotiating table calls for the flow in the river
near Blountstown, Fla., never to drop below a monthly average of
about 33,600 gallons (or 4,500 cubic feet) per second _ an amount
that some experts say will cause a 5 percent to 7 percent reduction
in the historical flow of the waterway.
</P>
<P>
   Barr says Florida is studying the proposal and won't comment
until the analysis is complete.
</P>
<P>
   However, Howard Marshall, a water expert with the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency's regional office in Atlanta, stood
up at a recent meeting of a committee advising Georgia's
negotiators and said, ``If Georgia gets Florida to accept this
reduction, it will be an exceptional accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Donny Wilson: ``This bay has been through a lot and bounced
back, but cutting off our rightful share of fresh water might get
it to the point where it can't bounce back. We won't let that
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
