<DOCNO> NYT19981004.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8724 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAVIGATION-COX     10-04 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAVIGATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barge traffic to Georgia's ports slows, causing fear
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ The Georgia Ports Authority's docks along
Lumpkin Boulevard here stand empty. They were built to handle
commercial barges coming 256 miles up from the Gulf of Mexico. But
no barges are in sight.
</P>
<P>
   That's the usual scene at this inland port on the Chattahoochee
River, the head of navigation on the
Apalachicola-Chattahoochee-Flint river basin, also known as the
ACF. Only 11 barges _ fewer than one a month _ checked in here in
1997. At Georgia's other inland port at Bainbridge on the Flint
River, 33 barges tied up at state docks last year.
</P>
<P>
   Shippers and operators fear there may be even fewer barges in
the future. Navigation on the lower ACF may become a footnote of
Southern history, a victim of the water war between Georgia and
sister states Alabama and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Demands for more water to fuel growth in metro Atlanta and
southeast Alabama, and providing adequate water to irrigate
southwest Georgia crops, may not leave enough water to float barges
in the ACF basin much of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried,'' says Rebecca Martin of the Tri-Rivers Waterway
Development Association, based in Dothan, Ala. ``There seem to be
clear differences in philosophy between people in North Georgia who
want more water and the people who rely on this navigation system
for various needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia officials acknowledge the possibility of a navigation
cutback. ``Georgians (may have) to more frequently use
non-navigational means of transporting goods due to a slightly less
reliable ACF navigation channel,'' says Bob Kerr, who is
negotiating on Georgia's behalf to reach a settlement in the water
war.
</P>
<P>
   That might not be so bad, say environmentalists and economists.
The National Wildlife Federation, Friends of the Earth and other
groups say the constant dredging required to maintain a
100-foot-wide, 9-foot-deep navigation channel in the basin
jeopardizes the health of fish and plants in the rivers and oysters
in Apalachicola Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Economists with Common Cause, the Cato Institute in Washington
and other organizations say that maintaining inland navigation
channels like the ACF amounts to one of the nation's most egregious
examples of pork barrel welfare. Taxpayers pay about $3.5 million
annually to maintain the ACF channel, according to the Army Corps
of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   On a cost-per-mile basis, say economists, the ACF system is
among the most costly in the nation for taxpayers to operate.
``Truckers pay their own way,'' says Stephen Moore of the
libertarian-leaning Cato Institute. ``Why shouldn't (barge)
shippers?''
</P>
<P>
   The users of the system say they feel they have few advocates.
Georgia's highest priorities for water use are ensuring enough for
drinking and agriculture; navigation ranks low on its wish list.
Florida's top goal is having enough water for oysters and other
marine life in Apalachicola Bay.
</P>
<P>
   When it authorized the navigation channel for the lower ACF
basin in 1945, Congress envisioned a dependable channel providing
an inexpensive route for fertilizer, fuel, mining and farm products
and other bulk items in an economically depressed region of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   To support navigation and at the same time provide power
generation and flood control, the Corps of Engineers built five
major dams on the Chattahoochee. Also in support of barge traffic,
riverbeds were dredged, curves on all three rivers straightened and
locks installed at three of the dams _ Walter F. George, George W.
Andrews, and Jim Woodruff on Lake Seminole at the Georgia-Florida
line. The lock at Lake Walter F. George downstream of Columbus has
a lift of 88 feet _ the second highest of any lock east of the
Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   A barge starting out at Apalachicola Bay on the Gulf could come
up the Apalachicola River across the Florida Panhandle to Lake
Seminole, where it could head east up the Flint to Bainbridge or
north up the Chattahoochee to Columbus. At one point, the corps
envisioned extending the channel to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But more than 30 years after the ACF channel opened, the system
has never come close to accommodating the 1.8 million tons the
corps predicted for it by 1990. Its best year was 1985, when 1.2
million tons were shipped in the lower ACF basin. By 1990, that was
down to 636,000 tons, and last year it was about 600,000 tons, only
a third of the projected traffic. The majority of the commerce that
moves on the rivers is sand and gravel dredged from river and lake
bottoms. Other products include fertilizer and other agricultural
chemicals, petroleum products and limited amounts of industrial
chemicals, asphalt, wood products and cottonseeds.
</P>
<P>
   President Reagan in 1983 recommended ending the federal
maintenance of waterways handling less than 5 million tons
annually. And in the 1990s, business and political leaders in
Columbus quietly attempted to close the state docks in the city,
saying that barging was outmoded and was harming the river. But an
intense lobbying effort by Tri-Rivers, barge operators and shippers
killed the proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the lower-than-predicted tonnage was that
sand in the riverbeds shifted more often than the corps had
predicted, requiring more dredging. In 1983, the corps acknowledged
that it needed 40 percent more water to provide the 9-foot depth on
a reliable basis. Much of the time, however, that water wasn't
available: Atlanta's growth and recreation on corps-built
reservoirs had triggered demands for more water upstream. There was
less water to send downriver for barges.
</P>
<P>
   The droughts of the 1980s showed the critical relationship
between upstream and downstream users. In the 1988 dry spell, more
water was hoarded in Lake Lanier to quench Atlanta's thirst, and
barge traffic on the ACF downstream was suspended for nearly three
months.
</P>
<P>
   To avert another such shutdown, the corps and barge operators
worked out a system of ``navigation windows'' in which the corps
would try to store more water in its four big Chattahoochee
reservoirs _ Lanier, West Point, Walter F. George and Seminole _
during dry spells and release it to float barges for as long as two
weeks each month.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the ACF never recovered from the uncertainties of
the droughts. The ongoing tri-state water war has created more
doubts, and the channel is stuck with a reputation of
``unreliable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reliability problem is the main reason shippers don't use
the ACF,'' says Martin. Her Tri-Rivers organization has lobbied
Congress to have the channel maintained at least 250 days a year.
``If we had a reliable channel, we could handle another million
tons a year,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia officials, however, doubt that will ever happen. One
reason the ACF never reached its full potential, they say, is that
several dams that were supposed to be erected on the Flint to help
support navigation were not built. Former Gov. Jimmy Carter in the
1970s, for instance, killed the corps' effort to build a huge dam
on the river at Sprewell Bluff because he claimed it was
environmentally unsound. Also, the officials note, shippers have
stopped transporting certain types of fuels on the system because
of Florida's tough anti-spill laws.
</P>
<P>
   Barge operators and users of the system counter the criticism,
declaring that barge traffic is the most ``energy-efficient''
transportation for moving nonperishable bulk materials. One barge,
they say, can haul 10 times more than a truck and 2.5 times more
than a railroad car. ``A barge causes less congestion, less
pollution and less noise,'' says Homer Hirt, a marketer for
Georgia's inland ports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maintaining the system may be a little expensive,'' says Ben
Bowden, 64, of Eufaula, Ala., who farms more than 6,000 acres in
Barbour County and relies on barges as an economical way of getting
bulk fertilizer shipments. ``But we have the potential for economic
development here, and we need the jobs. And we need this system to
operate reliably so that we can reach that potential.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
