<SLUG> BC-WESTWARS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Are the water wars a Midwestern omen?
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nebraska, Colorado and Kansas signed a deal in 1943 that spelled
out how much water each state could use from the Republican River.
But it's been anything but amicable among the three states.
</P>
<P>
   Saying Nebraska wasn't abiding by the compact, Kansas sued its
northern neighbor in May. Kansas claims that Nebraska has been
siphoning off too much water from the river for irrigation, leaving
it some 10 billion gallons short every year.
</P>
<P>
   The squabble may be an omen for Georgia, Alabama and Florida,
which are in intensive negotiations to divide the waters of rivers
they share. The states are supposed to agree on water allocation
formulas by the end of the year. The agreements will be binding on
all three states.
</P>
<P>
   But the conflict between Nebraska and Kansas shows that such
agreements don't necessarily settle water wars.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas alleges that Nebraska for years has illegally withheld
water from Kansas under the compact. The agreement spelled out
distribution of the Republican River's waters, with Nebraska
getting 49 percent, Kansas 40 percent and Colorado 11 percent. The
depletion, say Kansas officials, was caused by indiscriminate
drilling of water wells in the lower and middle portions of the
river basin in Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to sue a neighbor, but sometimes the neighbor
gives us no choice,'' says Kansas Attorney General Carla Stovall.
</P>
<P>
   THE CHATTAHOOCHEE:
</P>
<P>
   RIVER IN PERIL
</P>
<P>
   Midwestern omen?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
