<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SWISS TELEPHONE COMPANY PRICES ITS INITIAL OFFERING
</P>
<P>
   Swisscom, Switzerland's dominant, state-owned telephone company,
said it would sell its shares at 340 Swiss francs each, raising 7.5
billion francs, or $5.5 billion, in the eighth-biggest initial
offering of all time and the biggest in Europe this year.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Swisscom will start trading in Zurich on Monday. On
the New York Stock Exchange, its U.S. depository receipts, which
represent one-tenth of a share, will begin trading at $25.30 each.
The price is at the low end of the company's range announced in
September as the offering came under pressure from the recent slump
in world markets.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET SUCCESS SEEN IN THE STARS
</P>
<P>
   Dotted throughout Susan Miller's astrological chart is Uranus,
the all-important planet of things technological, so she had an
inkling that computers would change her life. What was harder to
predict was that her Astrology Zone site would become one of the
most popular of its kind on the Web and prompt a flurry of other
media deals.
</P>
<P>
   YEAR 2000 PROGRESS REPORTS
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to new guidelines from the Securities and Exchange
Commission, the debate over the extent of the year 2000 computer
problem is about to be infused with something that has been in
short supply: public information about how most companies are doing
in assessing and reducing their risks. The new data will appear in
reports filed with the SEC in the coming weeks summing up corporate
earnings for the quarter that ended on Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   HAND-OVER OF INTERNET APPROACHES
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration this week enters the final phase of
what has been a highly contentious more-than-yearlong effort by the
government to hand administration of the Internet over to a
nonprofit corporation.
</P>
<P>
   AD REVENUE DROPS AT SOME PAPERS
</P>
<P>
   Advertising revenue has fallen off at some newspapers, but most
newspaper companies have gained at least as much as they have lost,
despite the gyrations of the world's financial markets, according
to several newspaper executives and two economists at an industry
trade group.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING FOR A CHECK IN THE MAIL
</P>
<P>
   Late payments _ the dirty little secret of running a small
technology-based company, especially one catering to Fortune 1000
companies _ are a serious problem for many Silicon Alley companies.
While most vendors expect small businesses to pay outstanding bills
within 30 days, small companies often find themselves struggling to
get paid by companies with vast accounting departments where no one
seems accountable.
</P>
<P>
   WORST MAY BE OVER FOR CHIP MAKERS
</P>
<P>
   U.S. semiconductor companies, still in the midst of one of the
longest industry slumps, are expected to report a lackluster third
quarter, but analysts said that the worst may be over.
</P>
<P>
   AD GROUP TO EXPAND ITS MEMBERSHIP
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Advertising Agencies, in a
significant step, is opening membership for the first time to
independently owned agencies that specialize in services outside
the realm of traditional advertising, like media planning and
buying, public relations and corporate identity consulting.
</P>
</TEXT>
