<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
By LEAH GARCHIK 
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
     SOMETIMES THE OLD WAYS ARE NEW
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's much more chic to stay in an intimate ``boutique'' hotel,
says the latest issue of Bazaar, than a ``grand old establishment
place'' or a ``polyester palace.'' That notion having become
accepted, the herd is running to keep up and the trend-setters are
leaping ahead ... right back into the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that boutique hotels have become synonymous with
bad service,'' restaurateur-turned-hotelier  &UR; Brian McNally  &LR; told
the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doormen are young, handsome, dressed in black and off
doing auditions instead of carrying your bags. When the boutique
was new in New York, you could get away with it, but I don't think
you can anymore. People are bored of that. I'm tempted to get a
couple of middle-aged men on the door.''
</P>
<P>
   (In synch with this trend, the latest issue of GQ announces that
Brooks Brothers, which campaigned a few years ago to popularize
(read: go downscale) its upper-class image, is ``going upscale.''
The chain's flagship store in New York is opening a new floor
``devoted to luxury.'')
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; IMUS GOES THE WAY OF BOOK-LOVING OPRAH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Barnes and Noble has announced its institution of the Imus
American Book Awards, the richest prize in American literature.
Three winners will be chosenevery year by Barnes and Noble
customers and by radio host  &UR; Don Imus &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Grand prize is $100,000, and there will be three other $50,000
awards. (The National Book Awards' top prize is $10,000.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Robin Williams &LR;  and  &UR; James Taylor &LR;  will headline a
fund-raiser in Boston on November 23 for Senator  &UR; John Kerry &LR; ,
D-Mass. According to the Boston Herald, Williams and Kerry have
been friends since they met at an anti-war event in the '70s.
``It's a Kumbaya thing,'' said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   - The safety factor: &UR; Corey Wade &LR; , whose real name is  &UR; Gabriel &LR; 
 &UR; Macharia &LR;  and who is a former security guard for  &UR; Sylvester &LR; 
 &UR; Stallone &LR; , was sentenced to 25 years in prison for trying to kill
another Stallone security guard and trying to steal a $25,000 sword
from the boss. Wade shot the victim five times, slashed his throat
and beat him with a baton, but he survived.
</P>
<P>
   - Personals, who just barely knows the difference between a
Ping-Pong ball and a basketball, is sorry to have misidentified
 &UR; Will &LR; 
 &UR; Carling &LR; 's sport; he is a rugby player.
