<HEADER>
A8759 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      10-04 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX CEO WANTS TO ADD TOP STARTER, KEEP VAUGHN 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the morning after, John Harrington, wearing a windbreaker and
sports shirt, strode through a Red Sox clubhouse that was all but
deserted.
</P>
<P>
   He shook hands with the handful of players who were packing
their belongings in large cardboard cartons; chatted with veteran
Bret Saberhagen, who is sticking around to see the Hootie and the
Blowfish concert  &UR; tomorrow &LR; ; and greeted hitting coach Jim Rice and
Tom McLaughlin, the equipment man sorting through red socks that
will go unused until next season.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra's locker was unoccupied. Pedro Martinez was
elsewhere. So was Tom Gordon. The manager's office was empty, the
surest sign of all that the Sox' season had come to an end. No one
spends more time at Fenway Park on a game day than Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Before he left (``I'm double-parked outside''), the Red Sox CEO
took a few moments to reflect on the season just ended with the
four-game American League Division Series loss to the Indians and
touched upon the team's intentions this winter, which include
pursuing another top-of-the-rotation pitcher to complement last
year's prize catch, Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if that meant the Sox would pursue someone of the caliber
of potential free agents Randy Johnson, Kevin Brown, and Al Leiter,
Harrington answered in the affirmative.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, we are,'' Harrington said, ``if they're available
and interested in coming to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sense in going after another fourth or fifth
starter. We've got a bunch of guys we've given chances to for those
spots. If we get somebody for the top of our rotation, we'll go for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's something else out there, we'll look at it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But first they'll look inward. First baseman Mo Vaughn will be
eligible to file for free agency in less than three weeks, at 12:01
a.m. the day after the World Series ends.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington reiterated the team's desire to re-sign Vaughn, upon
whom he lavished praise, but acknowledged that he expects the
team's leading hitter (.337) and slugger (40 home runs) to test the
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timetable is his,'' Harrington said Sunday. ``Yes, we
would be interested in doing things ahead of time, and they may
have a willingness to talk to try and get a deal done, but unless
we overwhelm them, they'll probably want to see what's out there. I
think he's going to shop the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you're looking at this going into November. I wouldn't want
to mislead our fans into thinking this could be done soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington wants to make something else clear, too. He has no
intention of personally trying to cut a deal with Vaughn and his
agents, Tom Reich and Adam Katz.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Dan (Duquette) and Elaine (Weddington Steward) have to get
it done,'' Harrington said, ticking off the names of the team's
general manager and legal counsel, who have been talking with
Vaughn's agents off and on about a new deal for more than a year.
``I have to give those people the authority to develop our strategy
to take into negotiations. They have my every confidence. I take a
role, but as you know, it's the quiet kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington said he believes Vaughn wants to return. ``The
nucleus of our team is there,'' he said, ``but it would be nice to
get Mo. He's bonded with these guys, I think he prefers to stay
here, but I don't want Mo's people to think I mean he'll take a
hometown discount.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I keep saying, `We want him, too.' We take heart
that he says he wants to be here, but negotiations are
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears unlikely that the Red Sox intend to try to overwhelm
Vaughn with an offer before he declares free agency. Vaughn
rejected a four-year, $37.5 million offer at the All-Star break; it
remains to be seen if another club is willing to pay the Martinez
money ($12 million plus) Vaughn's agents are expected to seek.
</P>
<P>
   ``People blame high salaries on the owners,'' Harrington said,
``but who puts the pressure on us to pay them?''
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary list of potential suitors for Vaughn includes
Baltimore, Texas, and Anaheim, though the Orioles and Rangers must
decide what to do with their incumbent first basemen, Rafael
Palmeiro and Will Clark, both of whom are eligible for free agency.
The Angels, after yet another late-season collapse, might consider
moving Darin Erstad to center field and trading Jim Edmonds, though
Mike Piazza might also be on their list if he opts for free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto would seem to be another possibility, though the Blue
Jays' uncertain ownership situation, the faltering Canadian
economy, and the presence of up-and-coming slugger Carlos Delgado
at first base might incline them to pass on Vaughn. And while it
seems unlikely he'd want to tinker much with a team that won an
AL-record 114 games this season, Yankees boss George Steinbrenner
always seems to surface when a big-name free agent hits the market.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday Harrington said all the right things in reference to
Vaughn. ``Wasn't he great?'' he said. ``Fantastic. I'm sure his
manager would agree. He showed his leadership once all the things
that happened in the offseason were over.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I believe that what he did wasn't because this was a
contract season but because of his pride and determination. He knew
this would be a good team to play with.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington, mindful of how other top free agent pitchers signed
elsewhere while the Sox waited for Roger Clemens to make a
decision, said they don't intend to allow that scenario to unfold
this fall. If Vaughn re-signs, it is almost certain to happen by
Thanksgiving. Vaughn has indicated as much.
</P>
<P>
   And if he leaves? A few weeks ago, he laughed at the thought of
joining what he called ``the ghosts'' with which present Sox
players must cope, starting with G.H. Ruth. ``The black ghost,''
Vaughn said, cackling. ``I like that.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other decisions the Sox must make. Duquette will pass
on picking up the club option on lefthander Steve Avery, who
probably would prefer a fresh start elsewhere, and is not expected
to pick up the club option on Tim Naehring, who hasn't played in 14
months and will become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox hold a club option on Darren Lewis, the center fielder
who was everything advertised defensively and gave more than
expected offensively, but because he met a games-played clause in
his contract, Lewis has the right to become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have already attempted to re-sign lefthanded reliever
Greg Swindell, another potential free agent, and might think about
asking lefthander Pete Schourek to return, especially after his
performances at the end of the year. Lefthander Butch Henry, who
began the season in the rotation but missed all except the first
month after knee surgery, also will be a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Jeff Frye, who has two years left on a
three-year, $7 million contract, will be back next spring after
missing this season following spring training knee surgery, but he
is expected to be pushed by rookie Donnie Sadler, with Mike
Benjamin returning to his previous role of all-purpose utilityman,
if he comes back.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler is not the only young player who will get a look in camp
next spring. Outfielder Trot Nixon's stock has risen dramatically,
as witnessed by his postseason start against the Indians, and he
gives the club a cheaper alternative to arbitration-eligible Darren
Bragg should the club attempt to deal Bragg. Nixon could also wind
up being trade bait.
</P>
<P>
   And rookie pitcher Brian Rose, who was shut down in May because
of a bone spur in his right elbow, does not need surgery, team
doctor Arthur Pappas said Saturday night. ``He's healing,'' Pappas
said. ``The only question that remains is when he can begin
throwing again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox appear satisfied with their young catching platoon
of Jason Varitek and Scott Hatteberg, two players who will only get
better. DH Mike Stanley, acquired in a trading deadline deal with
the Blue Jays in July, is signed through next season and should be
back, though the club might need to find a lefthanded-hitting
counterpart if Reggie Jefferson's back doesn't improve. Jefferson
has two more years left on his contract, so he'll be given every
opporunity to win his job back.
</P>
<P>
   But if Vaughn doesn't return, acquiring a top-flight pitcher
won't fill the void he'll leave. It took the Sox two years to find
an adequate substitute for Clemens; there's no telling how long it
will take to replace Vaughn.
</P>
</TEXT>
