<HEADLINE>
TOP LINEMAN RILEY COMMITS TO TROJANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bernard Riley of Los Alamitos High School,
considered the top defensive lineman in the nation by one
recruiting service, gave an oral commitment to USC on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Riley, a 6-foot-3, 295-pound tackle, selected USC over Florida
State, Notre Dame, Michigan, Texas, Ohio State, UCLA and
Washington. He is listed as the No. 1 defensive lineman in the
country by SuperPrep magazine. Last year, Riley led the Los
Alamitos defense with 67 tackles, five sacks and five pass
deflections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it took a lot of people by surprise,'' said his
mother, Cindy Riley. ``He was getting tired of the recruiting
process and wanted to get it over with.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Riley said the main reason her son chose USC was because
he liked Trojans defensive line coach Ed Orgeron.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about coach Orgeron that excited him,'' she
said. ``He just wanted to go somewhere where he had a good feeling
about the coach. He also liked that coach Orgeron had several
players go to the NFL when he coached at Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Orgeron is also responsible for USC's other defensive-line
commitment _ Malcolm Woolridge of Boca Raton, Fla. The Trojans also
have commitments from tight end Jacob Rogers of Oxnard and
linebacker Markus Steele of Long Beach City College.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
