<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8786 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-WACKY-LADN     10-04 0317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-WACKY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEEL-GOOD MAGAZINE OF THE YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although it's been in the works for months, the timing of Sport
magazine's November issue celebrating today's heroes _ more
specifically, what's !ital!right!off! with sports _ couldn't be
much better.
</P>
<P>
   The on-field accomplishments of Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa
combined with their off-the-field humanitarian work seems to have
reversed a trend in sports coverage in which negativism once
dominated.
</P>
<P>
   Sport magazine's approach is to look into the far-reaching
effects of sports heroes with articles that a daily or weekly media
outlet might not have the time or space to devote. The athletes
chosen for the cover _ Andre Agassi, Cynthia Cooper, Dikembe
Mutombo, Troy Aikman and Derek Jeter _ represent a small part of
the warm-and-fuzzy stories in the issue that includes a forward by
former Senator (and New York Knicks star) Bill Bradley called
``Examples of Excellence.'' (Bradley also has a new book out called
``Values of the Game.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to be the `good sports people' magazine, but
we want to look beyond the sexy headlines and find the real-life
heroes who happen to be in sports,'' said Sport associate editor
David Scott. ``We're all very proud of this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigative work includes a look not only at the upside of
some athlete's foundations, but also how they can turn sour.
Jacksonville quarterback Mark Brunell, for example, raised
thousands of dollars for charity but was sickened to find out that
those he trusted to distribute the money weren't doing so.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 athletes whose actions have had a positive impact
on society are also recognized, as are the ``bad boys'' who do good
deeds such as Dennis Rodman and Marge Schott.
</P>
<P>
   The issue hits newsstands on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
