<HEADER>
A8789 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GANGSTERS-COX     10-04 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANGSTERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inmates face ugly choices, violent lives
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After spending the past four years in prison,
Brian Collins, 31, knows the routine well.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy comes in from the streets (and) the first thing that
happens is he gets checked _ by blacks, whites, everybody,'' said
the Mineral Wells resident who is serving 10 years for theft.
``This is how it goes, man. These dudes are going to charge you up
and see if you got heart, see if you're going to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most want money, sometimes sex.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to fight or you're going to tell the police
(guards) you need protection'' and get moved to a one-man cell.
</P>
<P>
   Collins says he chose the former.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he also chose the Aryan Circle, a white-supremacist
group well-known inside prison for fights against black and
Hispanic convicts. Collins says he is a major in the group, and he
proudly shows off the AC tattoo on his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Is he racist?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think I probably am,'' Collins said. ``I'm the type of
person that ain't going to go out and try to hurt people just
because I don't like them. I'll probably just try to stay away from
them. But if somebody does something to me or someone I love, I'm
going to take care of my business with them.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened a year ago at another prison when, as he
explains it, a member of a Hispanic gang ``stole something from one
of my brothers. We asked for it back and they said that we was a
bunch of whores. So I went and took care of business.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses. ``I caught him right out there on that (cellblock)
run. Stabbed him with a welding rod.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shouldn't have stole.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe ``Flaco'' Saldivar, 51, spent more than 20 years in Texas
prisons before he joined a gang.
</P>
<P>
   And when he did, in 1993, he had little choice, he says. He was
from San Antonio, so he had to go with the Mexican Mafia. Like
black and white convicts split into gangs along racial lines,
Hispanics in Texas prisons mostly split by hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured if (other gangs in prison) were going to target me
as the enemy and I'm going to have to suffer the consequences, I
might as well join up and see if there are benefits to reap,'' said
Saldivar, serving a life term as a habitual thief.
</P>
<P>
   He was soon moved to solitary confinement, with members of that
gang.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that in lockup I wasn't in actual danger of being
assaulted by anybody. . . . A lot of the members I had met back in
the '60s and '70s . . . and I thought that if I joined up I could
help them out in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   He did.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Saldivar sits in a solitary cell at the Estelle
High-Security Unit outside Huntsville. He said he tries to stay
busy, so as to not ``let insanity or old age catch up with me.''
</P>
<P>
   And while he hopes he eventually will be paroled, he concedes he
may well die in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur Jones Jr. was 15 when he came to prison. Gerald Ford was
president and Texas prisons were still segregated.
</P>
<P>
   ``You felt you had that right'' to be segregated, recalls the
38-year-old convicted robber, serving a life term for shooting a
store clerk during a Beaumont robbery.
</P>
<P>
   By 1984, Texas prisons had been desegregated by a federal judge,
and racial tensions exploded. Gangs started forming and warring.
Beatings, stabbings and killings bloodied prison cellblocks almost
every day.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, one of only a few black convicts in a dorm at the Ramsey
prison farm outside Houston, was marked for death by two members of
the white-supremacist Aryan Brotherhood as part of their initiation
rite into the gang.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was targeted because I was African-American,'' Jones says.
``That was all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They caught me in the dorm. . . . I grappled with one, got his
shank. I threw him off, and (the other one) who was supposed to be
watching out then came at me. I stabbed both. One died. I was
acquitted in a trial. It was self-defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Jones was placed in a maximum-security cellblock with
members of the Self Defense Family, one of the first black prison
gangs in Texas. Prison officials tagged him as a member, too, even
though he insists he never was.
</P>
<P>
   Since then he has served time in 11 different Texas prisons,
including more than three years in solitary confinement. Prison
officials list him as a suspected member of the Mandingo Warriors,
another black prison gang, a tie he also denies.
</P>
<P>
   During his 22 years in prison, Jones says, he has seen a gradual
rise in racial and ethnic tensions. ``It's more pronounced across
the board now,'' he says. ``You're dealing with a lot of
individuals in here who are highly uneducated . . . who are not
used to dealing with a problem in the right way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a dinosaur. I've seen the system all different ways. And
it's not good the way it was then. Or now.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenton Keith Ford says he knows firsthand about violence and
hate and why convicts join gangs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, newly arrived on the Hilltop Unit near Gatesville to
serve a 15-year sentence for burglarizing a Tyler home, Ford said
he faced a choice: fight or be raped by other convicts. For
protection, he said, he joined the Aryan Brotherhood, a
white-supremacist prison gang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, if you're white . . . you pay protection or give sex or
whatever they want,'' he said. ``I wasn't raised to be a racist any
more than any other white kid. But when I got to prison, I saw it
was different in here. Here, people can learn to hate.''
</P>
<P>
   At another prison, that hate exploded in a crude bomb _ a small
plastic mouthwash bottle filled with toilet tissue and match tips _
that he ignited with a cigarette lighter and threw into a black
convict's adjacent cell. It grew with the more-frequent fights he
had with black convicts, altercations that broke his jaw, knocked
out two teeth and left him with swollen testicles.
</P>
<P>
   Moved in 1995 to another cellblock where most of the convicts
were black, Ford said, he was overpowered and raped by a convict.
``I'd been turned out. . . . I couldn't fight anymore,'' Ford said,
explaining that in return for sex twice a week, the other convict
bought him commissary items _ chips, shampoo, candy, all common
barter in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do what you have to to stay alive in here. That's the way
I see it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford now ponders his future from a one-man isolation cell at the
Hughes Unit outside Gatesville, where his sentence has been
extended to 23 years because of a new felony charge resulting from
the bomb incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a breeding of hate in prison? Yes,'' he said. ``I'm
bitter. I'm angry because I'm stuck down here and my life is
getting away. How come I gotta ride with somebody to survive?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hate. But once people live around this
mentality in prison, they can hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
