<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Secret codes of crime concealed in books, letters
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ ``God Bless You and Your Family,'' read the
printed birthday greeting. But inside the back flap of the card
were scribbled numbers carrying a much more ominous message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Code,'' explains Irma Fernandez, who helps oversee the prison
system's gang enforcement program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message was reporting to a member of an Hispanic prison
gang that an assault had been successfully carried out. We got it
instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Fernandez headed the five-member unit at the
Estelle prison here _ part of the more than 50 specially trained
corrections officers across Texas who pore over thousands of pieces
of mail each day, intercepting and deciphering coded messages to
and from gang members in a script more suited to a James Bond movie
than prison. Sometimes the messages are written in numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they are dots atop words in a handwritten letter.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they are hidden behind a stamp or disguised in a
drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, officials at another Texas prison
confiscated an elaborate pencil sketch of a nude woman on a
background of flowers, drawn by a member of a Hispanic gang. In the
background was a message ordering a killing.
</P>
<P>
   A similar message was hidden in a crude drawing of a cave man
chiseling letters in a rock, done by a member of a white
supremacist gang. It too was confiscated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gangs have been using codes for years, and we've been
intercepting them for years,'' said Sam Buentello, the prison
system's top gang expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've tried just about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Example: Letters written with invisible ink _ made by convicts
with urine or with cleaning fluids _ that are readable when heat is
applied with an iron or hair dryer.
</P>
<P>
   Example: Almost-invisible messages that are typed with a
ribbonless typewriter on the margins of a letter or in the folds of
an envelope. The recipient can read the message after lightly
tracing over the areas with a pencil.
</P>
<P>
   Example: Magazines and books that have words underlined on
random pages. By leafing through the pages, either front to back or
vice versa, a convict can read the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``By breaking the codes, we've been able over the years to stop
a number of crimes,'' Buentello said.
</P>
<P>
   He said thwarted crimes included murders of police officers, a
state judge, even prison officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``You name it, inmates have probably tried it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buentello and Fernandez said all correspondence to and from
confirmed gang members in prison _ except for that with their
lawyers _ is examined each day by gang intelligence officers.
</P>
<P>
   Along with coding, the officers look for things such as whether
a convict is still active in a gang, Buentello said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the coded messages, this communications system
has its own vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   When a girlfriend or other visitor delivers a message verbally,
it's called ``sending a kite.'' Letter writers' mention of a
``green light'' can be code for a murder.
</P>
<P>
   The solution?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not stopping the flow of mail to and from prison gang
members _ even between convicts in different prisons, officials
said. That is something that was forbidden years ago by federal
court orders.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, said Fernandez, ``We read the mail. We know what's
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
