<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOSTER CAN FILL PLAYMAKER'S ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If his performance eventually meets his potential,
if he one day joins Freeman McNeil, Gaston Green, Karim
Abdul-Jabbar and Skip Hicks in the UCLA tailback pantheon, perhaps
he'll call Saturday the game that started it all.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman DeShaun Foster showed his stuff against Washington
State _ the strength and speed that made him one of the nation's
top prep runners last year, the vision and balance that could make
him one of the nation's top college runners in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
   In UCLA's 49-17 victory, Foster gained 185 all-purpose yards. He
rushed for 94, caught passes for 14 more, returned punts for 34 and
kickoffs for 60.
</P>
<P>
   Were some of his yards against Washington State's second-team
defense? Yes. Does it matter? Not a lick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made one move,'' UCLA offensive coordinator Al Borges said,
marveling. ``There was a safety blitz, (Foster) was trapped in the
hole, and he left the guy in his shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster's voice is soft as his play is loud. Nestled in a far
corner of UCLA's locker room _ with Cade McNown a few feet to the
right and Jermaine Lewis a few to the left _ Foster admitted that
after six weeks he finally feels comfortable with the offense and
his role in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting better with the speed of the game and knowing the
offense,'' he said. ``The first couple games, I was hesitant. I
wasn't hitting the holes as fast as I should. Now I'm just
running.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins need it. Oh, do they. The next two weeks might
determine their season. Conquer Arizona and Oregon, and they're on
course for a New Year's in Pasadena or Tempe. Lose both, and they
probably seal a second-tier bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Foster is essential to their success _ both as Freddie
Mitchell's replacement on returns and as a ballcarrier. The
tailback rotation of Foster, Lewis and Keith Brown sounds great.
Against Washington State, it looked great. But in the biggest
games, against the best teams, UCLA needs its playmakers, and
Foster is a playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid could be a phenom before he leaves,'' Borges said.
``He's that skilled. He's tough to tackle and he has great
vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster is one of several true freshmen who must contribute
during the Arizona-Oregon doubleheader. Nose guard Ken Kocher
(sprained ankle) and linebacker Robert Thomas (broken hand) are
critical to the defense reaching its potential. Both are expected
to play more as their injuries heal.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the veterans immune from introspection. McNown must
improve on his 52.5 completion percentage the last two games. The
dropped passes must end. UCLA had 11 penalties against Washington
State, 29 in three games; that won't cut it. The defensive line
must generate a pass rush so the cornerbacks aren't left in single
coverage. The special teams must continue to make plays.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the coaches have plenty to teach. If the Bruins don't
eliminate mistakes, their winning streak will end at 13 games
Saturday night in Arizona Stadium, where they haven't won in 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our margin for error will be a heck of a lot less,'' Borges
said. ``We've got to become more disciplined.'' &QL; 
REPORT CARD
</P>
<P>
   Game: 3
</P>
<P>
   Result: UCLA 49, Washington State 17
</P>
<P>
   Record: 3-0
</P>
<P>
   This week's GPA: 3.15
</P>
<P>
   Cumulative GPA: 3.09
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback _ Best ball of the day was Drew Bennett's touchdown.
Cade McNown's passes floated as if he had mechanical difficulty.
Better get it corrected this week. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Running backs _ Jermaine Lewis played like a No. 1 back trying
to clear his name. So did DeShaun Foster. Are there enough carries
to go around? Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Receivers _ Danny Mitchell _ err, Farmer _ made big plays. Tight
ends had one huge drop (Ryan Neufeld) and a slew of great blocks
(Mike Grieb). Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line _ The big fellas came to play: 256 yards rushing,
no sacks and more pancakes than IHOP. Now, about those penalties.
Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line _ Only six tackles, but that's deceiving. UCLA
played most of the game with just two linemen because of Wazu's
spread formation. This week: Get healthy. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers _ Best game of the season for LBs, especially
ubiquitous Tony White. Ryan Nece and Ali Azziz came off the bench
and created havoc. One request: more Robert Thomas. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs - First-time starters Tod McBride and Ryan
Roques avoided killer mistakes. Marques Anderson played with
spirit. If they could just clone Larry Atkins. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Special Teams _ Chris Sailer, still without a field goal, boomed
his kickoffs. Good returns from DeShaun Foster, and TWO blocked
punts. Stop the presses! Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Coaching: _ From pregame speech to deferring coin toss, nickel
defense, blocked punts and 32-point win, a solid job all around.
But 11 penalties will doom them in Tucson. Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
