<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON'S WORDS RAISE CONCERN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fact Mike Tyson is disturbed is no secret to anyone who is
conscious. However, an interview with the former champion in
Playboy magazine this month gives the Nevada State Athletic
Commission more reason than ever to be concerned about his
stability.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, he comes off as more enraged than ever in
spite of what he says are constant efforts to keep his
unpredictable emotions in check.
</P>
<P>
   One comment alone should give pause to Nevada commissioners, who
are considering whether to relicense Tyson after he chewed off a
portion of Evander Holyfield's ear last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm going to blow one day,'' he told the magazine.
``But I'm going to make sure that when I blow, my kids are fine.
There's not much more of this (bleep) I can take. I'm going to blow
one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try very hard, I'm doing a very good job, sir. I'm doing a
very good job. I'm just really angry these days. Really, really
angry. This whole year has been a total retrospect of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it's difficult to understand what Tyson says.
However, his tone is clear.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson !ital!is!off! ready to blow any minute. It could happen
anywhere _ including the ring.
</P>
<P>
   __ More Tyson: The situation in Nevada is a mess.
</P>
<P>
   First, the commission implies Tyson will be reinstated if he
receives a satisfactory evaluation from an independent
psychiatrist. Then, after he's tested, they say he has to explain
an alleged assault.
</P>
<P>
   Then Tyson's handlers are unable to get the evaluation to the
commission in time for the scheduled Oct. 3 hearing, which is
postponed to Oct. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Then Tyson's people decide they don't want the results of the
evaluation released to the public, even though he agreed to do so
at a hearing in Nevada last month. Then a judge says he can't
prevent the commission from making the evaluation public, a
decision that has been appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the doctor who performed the evaluation said he
doesn't want to release it because of doctor-patient
confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   And Tyson's people are reportedly attempting to settle the
assault charge out of court to make it go away.
</P>
<P>
   It's an absolute circus with an overabundance of clowns. It
didn't have to be this complicated. This is boxing, though.
</P>
<P>
   __ Class act: With his loss to Floyd Mayweather, we might have
seen the last of Genaro Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   If so, he should be remembered as one of the finest boxers and
one of the classiest gentlemen of his era. He handled himself with
remarkable grace over a long career, in which he was champion for
all or parts of seven years.
</P>
<P>
   His comments after Saturday's fight are typical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father Time caught up with us,'' he said. ``He's a true
champion and he'll be champion for a long time. He was just too
quick for me. I've been with inexperienced fighters before, but
nobody was as quick as him. I intended to go out there and beat the
best and he proved that he was better than the best.''
</P>
<P>
   No fighter has more to be proud of than Hernandez _ even if he
was largely overlooked by the public.
</P>
<P>
   __ Floyd the champ: With his victory over Hernandez, the new WBC
super featherweight champion became the first 1996 Olympian to hold
a world title.
</P>
<P>
   Mayweather, 21, surprised some people who believed he needed
more seasoning to beat Hernandez, but he certainly has the natural
ability. The nephew of former champ Roger Mayweather has uncommon
boxing skills and quickness.
</P>
<P>
   Now, does he have enough ability to beat a top-flight opponent
nearer his own age, Angel Manfredy, against whom he might defend
his title in December? The same doubters will be out for that one:
Manfredy is a complete and resilient fighter. And he's only 23.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be another fascinating matchup. And, if Mayweather takes
it in lieu of a mismatch that could earn him a few easy dollars, he
should be commended. Boxing needs more brash young boxers willing
to fight anyone.
</P>
<P>
   __ Whitaker back: Unbeaten heavyweight Lance Whitaker of Mission
Hills, out since May because of a cut, is scheduled to face Dan
Conway on the undercard of the Alex Stewart-Ezra Sellers card on
Thursday in Kansas City, Mo., on Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker (16-0, with 14 knockouts) was cut during his May 1 bout
against Ray Butler, whom he stopped in six rounds. The wound healed
but was reopened while he was sparring with Everton Davis a few
months later. All together, Whitaker has had 25 stitches.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-8, 245-pounder was depressed after the second
incident and, even when it healed, worried it would happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``After sparring, I would look in the mirror and see if I was
OK. Every time,'' he said. ``I wanted to see if it had healed,
whether I gave it enough time. It was hard, it really was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's OK, though. My right hand was hurting. The time off
gave that time to heal and I worked on some (noncontact) things in
the gym. I think the layoff probably did me some good.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker believes he'll be ready to face a top-10 contender next
year but is in no hurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really just looking forward to this fight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Goossen-Camacho fight nearer: Pat Goossen, the father and
trainer of P.J. Goossen of North Hollywood, said a deal to fight
Hector ``Macho'' Camacho on Dec. 12 is near completion, but he is
taking nothing for granted in this unpredictable business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll believe it when P.J. is in the ring,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
