<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS USC TEAM WILL NOT BE FAZED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the exhilaration that followed USC's 35-24
victory over Arizona State, it's only natural that a few brash
answers flow off the lips of players and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this is a long season, but the goal is crystal clear _
to make it to Pasadena,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on our way to the Rose Bowl,'' echoed linebacker David
Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   No need to dampen anyone's enthusiasm, but it seemed like nearly
everyone forgot the Trojans had just defeated a 2-2 team playing on
the road without its star quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Or that a running back (J.R. Redmond) had sliced through the
Trojans' defense for more yards (214) than all but five tailbacks
in the 988 games USC has played football.
</P>
<P>
   Or that USC was inexplicably lined up to kick an extra point
while trailing 24-19 in the third quarter. Only an Arizona State
penalty allowed the Trojans to come to their senses and attempt a
successful two-point conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Or that freshman quarterback Carson Palmer seemed to be coming
in awfully late to provide a lift to the struggling offense.
</P>
<P>
   Or that the Trojans were flagged for another 108 yards in
penalties, including three infractions that occurred on a kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   These are just minor inconveniences, apparently, because USC
clearly believes it can win games this year. It doesn't matter how
many minutes the defense is forced to stay on the field each week,
it never gives up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody has to go down and it's not going to be us,'' free
safety Rashard Cook said. ``Sometimes, it might get to you (being
on the field so long), but a teammate might tell you, `We've got to
stop them.'''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter how long the offense fails to score points,
its confidence remains unshaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making progress,'' Hackett said. ``It is slow on
offense, but it is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Where recent editions of USC teams might be considered a little
weak on character, this year's version has no such problem. It's
the main reason the Trojans always believe they can overpower a
team in the fourth quarter _ unless it's Florida State, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Credit the strong mental makeup to Hackett. Some of his
decisions might be questionable _ like the clock management at the
end of the first half _ but Hackett has rebuilt the Trojans'
eroding confidence. USC (4-1, 2-0) believes it can win games again,
even if the early breaks go against the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no way we were going to let Arizona State come into
our house and beat us,'' Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   This might still prove to be a rebuilding year, but it's fair to
say the Trojans might not drop a game this season to an inferior
opponent. Big deal? Well, remember the loss to Cal in 1996? That
game drained much of the enthusiasm away from the Trojans and was
hugely responsible for a 6-6 season.
</P>
<P>
   Even last year's loss to Washington State jarred the team's
confidence. The Cougars went to the Rose Bowl, but it was a painful
experience to lose to Washington State in Los Angeles for the first
time in 41 years.
</P>
<P>
   So far, USC is beating the teams it is supposed to beat. Arizona
State (2-3, 1-2) is in a free fall right now, but most of the USC
players had never experienced a victory over the Sun Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't beaten them in two years,'' wide receiver R. Jay
Soward said. ``It feels good to beat Arizona State.''
</P>
<P>
   And right now, USC is feeling good about itself. &QL; 
REPORT CARD
</P>
<P>
   GAME: 5
</P>
<P>
   RESULT: USC 35, Arizona State 24
</P>
<P>
   RECORD: 4-1
</P>
<P>
   THIS WEEK'S GPA: 2.58
</P>
<P>
   CUMULATIVE GPA: 2.58
</P>
<P>
   QUARTERBACKS _ So Mike Van Raaphorst is the starter and Carson
Palmer is the closer? Next time, the Trojans better not wait until
they're trailing in the eighth inning to bring in the closer. B
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING BACKS _ Chad Morton better get healthy fast. On the
bright side, Ted Iacenda made the catch of the night on the
two-point conversion. D
</P>
<P>
   RECEIVERS _ While everyone watches R. Jay Soward, Larry Parker
quietly made all the important early catches. Can someone please
find Mike Bastianelli? B+
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSIVE LINE _ As long as the quarterback escapes a major
injury, it's breathe-a-sigh-of-relief time. The pass protection
seems to be getting better, sort of. C-
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE LINE _ Marc Matock's broken ankle will be a big loss
since the Trojans are weakest at tackle. And just when Ennis Davis
is developing into an impact player. C
</P>
<P>
   LINEBACKERS _ Ho hum. Chris Claiborne had two sacks and knocked
out ASU QB Ryan Kealy. David Gibson broke up three passes and
returned an interception for a TD. This is where the Trojans are
winning games. A-
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE BACKS _ Thankfully, they never had to see what Kealy
might have done. At least they held star receiver Lenzie Jackson to
a pair of catches. C+
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL TEAMS _ Antuan Simmons' blocked punt sealed Arizona
State's fate, and was his second blocked kick of the season. This
is a major improvement area from last season. B+
</P>
<P>
   COACHING _ Why were they trying to kick an extra point down
24-19, before ASU committed a silly penalty? All that matters is
that the players now have a winning attitude. B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
