<HEADER>
A8900 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-?-?-BOS &LR;      10-04 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-?-?-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Citing public ``horror'' at the political maelstrom
surrounding President Clinton's sex scandal, Representative Henry
J. Hyde, chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, expressed a
``hope and prayer'' Sunday that the panel would decide by New
Year's Day whether to seek Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's panel will vote Monday or Tuesday on whether to recommend
initiating the second impeachment inquiry of a president this
century _ and the first since Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   With several polls finding that the public favors a swift
congressional response to Clinton's crisis, Hyde issued his ``New
Year's resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats, meanwhile, said that Speaker Newt Gingrich is
controlling the impeachment process and trying to prolong the
inquiry into the 2000 presidential election season for political
gain.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee is likely to reject a Democratic
proposal that would set a Thanksgiving deadline to complete the
investigation. Under the GOP plan, which is expected to be approved
by the committee by tomorrow and the full House by Friday, the
panel would conduct an open-ended inquiry into allegations that
Clinton committed perjury, obstruction of justice, and witness
tampering stemming from his affair with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how New Year's resolutions sometimes get broken, but
it's my hope and prayer that we could finish by New Year's,'' Hyde
said on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet with Hyde holding out the possibility of expanding the
investigation to several other matters, Democrats on the Judiciary
Committee said the inquiry could drag on indefinitely. ``If all you
do is Lewinsky, you can't make that last more than a couple of
months,'' Representative Barney Frank, Democrat of Newton, said on
ABC's ``This Week.'' ``What I am afraid we are going to get is an
impeachment in search of a high crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, 74, an Illinois Republican, said he recognizes how much
damage the matter has already caused the country and how
devastating the future consequences could be. Hyde was elected to
the House in 1974, just months after the Judiciary Committee voted
to impeach President Nixon, which led to Nixon's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our politics'' has suffered ``a serious blow,'' Hyde said.
``The name-calling, the negativity, the throwing of mud, the
institution of the White House, the presidency and Congress itself
_ people are looking at this in horror.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as Hyde prepared to preside over the impeachment
hearings, he said that if the House votes to impeach Clinton, the
Senate would not convict him in the current climate. A conviction
would require a vote of two-thirds of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't get that two-thirds bipartisan vote in the Senate''
in the current atmosphere, Hyde said. ``They won't do that until
the American people move, and they have to move from where they
apparently are, if the polls are true.''
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment proceedings are likely to produce moments of
high drama and low comedy as the Judiciary Committee enters a new
frontier in considering allegations stemming from a president's
sexual life in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But there will also be political sideshows, as several
developments underscored Sunday. Notable among them was a full-page
ad in The Washington Post in which Hustler magazine and its
publisher, Larry Flynt, offered as much as $1 million to
individuals who can prove they committed adultery with members of
Congress or high-ranking government officials.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ross Perot, the Texas billionaire and former
presidential candidate, pressed his campaign for Clinton's
resignation by likening Clinton's ``lust for power'' to Adolf
Hitler's and alleging that Clinton's affair with Lewinsky may have
been associated with drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Perot, appearing on C-SPAN's ``Washington Journal,'' provided no
evidence to support his claim of possible drug use.
</P>
<P>
   The White House did not respond directly to Perot's remarks but
cited a statement last week by former spokesman Michael D. McCurry.
He said Perot's comments ``indicate the good judgment the American
people had when they failed to elect him president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, former President Gerald R. Ford broke his silence on
the Clinton scandal by laying out a scenario to resolve the matter
without impeaching Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine ... a Presidential appearance in the closing days of
this year, not at the rostrum familiar to viewers from moments of
triumph, but in the well of the House. Imagine a President
receiving not an ovation from the people's representatives, but a
harshly worded rebuke as rendered by members of both parties,''
Ford wrote in an op-ed article Sunday in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Many Clinton allies support Ford's plan, but Republican leaders
are balking. ``I don't think you should start advocating what the
punishment might be until you know what the facts are,'' said
Senator Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Lott also said he was not sure he could trust the Clinton
administration in pending budget talks because, he said, White
House officials have privately threatened to shut down the
government for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They basically have told me, `We'll wait and see. If it is to
our advantage to shut down the government we will; if it is not, we
won't,''' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokeswoman, Linda Ricci, denied Lott's
allegation. ``The administration has been very clear we do not seek
or advocate a shutdown,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Judiciary Committee meets Monday, the panel's chief
lawyer for Republican members, David P. Schippers, is expected to
recommend dropping one or more of 11 allegations against Clinton
that the committee received last month from independent counsel
Kenneth W. Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both parties have said they see insufficient
evidence, for example, to support Starr's assertion that Clinton
abused the power of his office when he invoked executive privilege
to try to prevent his lawyers from testifying before a grand jury
about their personal conversations with him.
</P>
<P>
   However, Schippers also plans to recommend investigating
additional charges that Clinton lied under oath in testifying
before a federal grand jury and in a civil deposition in the Paula
Corbin Jones lawsuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
