<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-DEFENSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Freshman QB leads Georgia to 28-27 upset of sixth-ranked LSU
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ Last week, Hurricane Georges swept just east
of the Louisiana coast, leaving LSU and Baton Rouge pretty much
unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, the sixth-ranked Tigers weren't so fortunate
with Quincy.
</P>
<P>
   Quincy Carter, Georgia's freshman quarterback, whipped through
Baton Rouge with a fury, leading the 12th-ranked Bulldogs to a
shocking 28-27 upset of LSU. Carter, making only his fourth career
start, passed for 318 yards and two touchdowns to stun a crowd of
80,792, the second-largest ever at Tiger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, 4-0 overall 2-0 in the Southeastern Conference, now
faces a much-anticipated showdown next week with third-ranked
Tennessee in Athens. If Georgia vaults into the top 10 today as
expected, it would be the first matchup of top 10 teams in Sanford
Stadium since No. 3 Auburn and No. 4 Georgia met in 1983.
``Tennessee is a big one,'' senior defensive end Antonio Cochran
said. ``It's been a long time coming. They've beaten us seven
straight times and it's about time it should end.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia could have its best shot in recent years with Carter,
the former Parade All-American from Southwest DeKalb High. Carter,
who entered the game as the nation's ninth-rated passer, thrust
himself among the nation's best, using his toughest test to date as
a coming-out party in front of a national television audience on
ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Carter completed his first 15 passes, tying Eric Zeier for the
Georgia record, and led the Bulldogs to touchdowns on their first
three drives. He completed 27 of 34 passes, and added 41 rushing
yards on 14 attempts. Carter even had a 36-yard reception on a
halfback pass to set up Georgia's third touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's apparent that Quincy can make all the plays a lot of
other guys can't,'' Georgia coach Jim Donnan said. ''I knew he was
a good player, but that was big, going out and playing like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's saavy and poise in Georgia's final drive was uncanny.
</P>
<P>
   Facing third-and-6 at the Bulldogs' 24 with less than three
minutes remaining, Carter barely got away a pass as he was hit by
LSU nose guard Anthony McFarland. Georgia's two-way player and
Heisman Trophy candidate, junior Champ Bailey, beat free safety
Mark Roman for the pass, giving the Bulldogs a clinching first down
at the Dogs' 45.
</P>
<P>
   ''Quincy just threw it up there for me to go get it,'' Bailey
said. ''It was right where it needed to be, where the defensive
back couldn't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Five plays later, Georgia running back Robert Arnaud gained 6
yards on third-and-3 at the LSU 37 for a first down, which sent the
large contingency of Georgia fans in the south end zone into a
frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was good to see us operate like that,'' said Donnan, who
huddled his team on the sidelines before its final drive. ''With
the game on the line and in the clutch, we didn't give them the
ball back. I just told the team that the game was on the line and
we couldn't give the ball back. I told them we needed to get three
first downs, but I didn't think we'd get them like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter was the story of the game, but Georgia's defense, porous
throughout the entire contest against LSU's one-two punch of
quarterback Herb Tyler and tailback Kevin Faulk, came up big late.
</P>
<P>
   On consecutive possessions in the fourth quarter, the Bulldogs
forced LSU into field goals after the Tigers drove inside the
Georgia 20. Chris Chauvin kicked a 41-yard field goal with 5:08
left to pull LSU within one, 28-27.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Chauvin kicked a 34-yard field goal with 10:27 left to
make it 28-24.
</P>
<P>
   ''The defense in the second half was just what we had to do,''
Donnan said. ''We gave up some yards, but we held them to two field
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   After a wild first half, in which touchdowns were scored on the
first five possessions and the teams left tied at 21-21, Georgia
opened the third quarter by holding LSU to a punt, only its second
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs took over at their own 25 and moved deep into LSU
territory. On second-and-10 from the LSU 17, Carter threw for
senior flanker Tony Small in the end zone. Small, who finished with
eight catches for 81 yards, pulled the ball away from free safety
Ryan Clark for a 17-yard touchdown. Hap Hines' extra point made it
28-21 with 8:16 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's defense struggled in the first half, but held Faulk to
only 88 yards on 17 carries. Tyler completed 16 of 26 attempts for
205 yards and two touchdowns, but in the fourth quarter, he was
incomplete on his only attempts and was sacked twice.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's our job to keep them out of the end zone,'' Cochran said.
''This was a big game, but the next one is even bigger. It's going
to determine who's ahead in the SEC East and it's big. It's really
big.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
