<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8907 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS05-COX     10-04 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Dwight stuff: Falcons' rookie starts 51-23 assault on
Carolina
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When rookie Tim Dwight showed up at Falcons passing
camp in June, teammates noticed right away that he was different.
So Atlanta Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler hung a nickname on
him in no time flat. ``Mutt,'' Chandler called him, and the moniker
seems to fit.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight, a 5-foot-8, 181-pounder from Iowa and the Falcons'
smallest player, stood out again Sunday in the Georgia Dome. His
93-yard touchdown on the opening kickoff opened the floodgates, and
Atlanta proceeded to massacre the Carolina Panthers 51-23.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, which included an NFL-record three touchdowns in 48
seconds to start the second half, had the Falcons (3-1) tied atop
the NFC West standings with San Francisco and New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, who caught a 22-yard pass from Dwight off a reverse
play to set up a Morten Andersen field goal and a 17-3 halftime
lead, was smiling about Dwight's performance after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight, after all, is not like his teammates. They drive
luxurious cars; he drives an old Isuzu Pup pickup truck. The truck
is borrowed from a friend at the University of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes there's a tendency for rookies to not go all out
because they're still learning,'' Chandler said after completing
12-of-20 passes for 189 yards, two TDs and two interceptions.
``Mutt's come in here and been a live wire. He's a funny little
sucker to be around, too. He just goes all out.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight, who returned four kickoffs for 169 yards, rushed twice
for 7 yards from the tailback position and completed the first pass
of his career, seemed unfazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just call me a utility man,'' he said. ``I don't care where I
play; just put me on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' first-ever sweep of Carolina didn't sit well with
the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when you were a kid and your mom sent you to karate
class and the bully slapped you anyway,'' said Carolina linebacker
Michael Barrow. ``Tell everybody to pray for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' onslaught was that bad.
</P>
<P>
   On the first possession after Dwight's kickoff return, Atlanta
drove 56 yards in five plays and took a 14-0 lead on a 30-yard pass
over the middle to wide receiver Tony Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Then things got ugly after halftime.
</P>
<P>
   After catching a 13-yard pass, Carolina reserve tight end Luther
Broughton got hit by strong safety William White and defensive end
Lester Archambeau and fumbled the ball into the hands of Falcons
cornerback Ronnie Bradford.
</P>
<P>
   An 11-play, 78-yard drive ended with a 1-yard touchdown run by
fullback Bob Christian, and Atlanta led 24-3 with 6:27 left in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina running back Fred Lane turned the ball over on the next
play from scrimmage after Archambeau caused, and recovered, the
fumble. Chandler passed to tight end O.J. Santiago down the middle
for a 26-yard scoring pass to give the Falcons a 31-3 lead with
6:01 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On the Panthers' next play from scrimmage, wide receiver Muhsin
Muhammad caught a short pass over the middle, tripped over his own
feet, and fumbled into the hands of a stunned White, who returned
it 18 yards down the left sideline for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got our butts beat,'' Carolina quarterback Kerry Collins
said. ``We're terrible. We're bad. I don't know what to say. We're
embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolina had called the Falcons 19-14 victory on Sept. 6 a
fluke, and the Falcons appeared motivated by the statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't go out and say things about a team you have to play
again,'' Falcons middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To read something like that,'' said Atlanta running back Jamal
Anderson, who had 117 yards for the first back-to-back 100-yard
games of his career, ``'it's disappointing when somebody blatantly
disrespects you like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, White, who added an interception in the fourth
quarter, was talking about how good everybody is feeling right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we keep believing, and going out and playing the
way we're capable of playing, everyone will jump on the
bandwagon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The next step comes in New York on Sunday, when the Falcons play
coach Dan Reeves' old team, the Giants, in the ESPN Sunday night
game. The Giants (2-3) pose another hurdle for a Falcons team that
is trying to prove itself. Atlanta has won nine of 12 since last
season's 1-7 start, but has yet to bet a team with a winning
record.
</P>
<P>
   Their three victories have come against teams that are a
combined 0-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the middle of last year, we've beaten the teams we're
kind of supposed to beat,'' Reeves said. ``If you want to take that
next step . . . we got to start beating some of the better teams,
some of the teams that are in the playoff hunt. (The Giants) were a
playoff team last year, and they're . . . the defending NFC East
champions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
