<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-BISHER05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Just who are these guys, anyway?
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ What kind of a tournament field is this?
Ben Crenshaw and Tom Kite, Ryder Cup captains past and present; Tom
Watson, Sandy Lyle, David Frost, Jim Furyk and Jay Haas can't make
the cut, then we wind up with a dogfight down the stretch between a
player who got his start coaching a college team, Willie Nelson's
personal pro, the pro from surgery and the only Aussie in Harris
County. Oh, and the ever-present Skip Kendall, who always seems to
pop up, popped up again with a 63 while nobody was looking.
</P>
<P>
   So at the end of a weathery Sunday, the defenseless old Mountain
View course heaved mightily, rejoicing to see the 1998 Buick
Challenge tournament cast get out of town. Callaway Gardens hadn't
seen such a field as this since the PGA moved its tournament to
this family resort, and when all was done, the Australian took home
the loot. It was the second time Steve Elkington had won this
tournament, but this time he had to take it one more hole.
</P>
<P>
   For the first 54 holes, the tournament belonged to Fred Funk,
the former coach from Maryland. Over the last 18, Elkington caught
and blew past like the cartoon critter, the roadrunner. The playoff
lasted one hole, on which Funk hit his tee shot in a fairway
bunker, his escape shot caught the lip and the rest was purely
academic. In fact, Funk started to shake Elkington's hand in
surrender before he holed out his par putt.
</P>
<P>
   It was ironic, for Funk is known for his driving accuracy, if
not his distance. ``Hitting straight has been my bread and
butter,'' he said, ``and two bad drives kept me from winning in
regulation, then I hit my worst drive of the week on the playoff
hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather was the players' best friend. Heavy rain left the
fairways soft, the greens receptive and the air oppressively humid.
Early morning fog nearly delayed first tee times. If it had been an
airport, planes couldn't have landed. Then near the conclusion, sun
shining bright, streaks of lightning broke through and held up play
a short time. Only the leaders were left on course, Elkington,
Funk, Bill Glasson, the star from surgery, and J.L. Lewis, the
Texas pro from Willie Nelson. Elkington himself might be called the
pro from Buick, for he is a member of the carmaker's stable of
players.
</P>
<P>
   He birdied 17 and 18 for 65. Funk birdied 17 but was a foot wide
on 18 for a 69, a tie at 267, setting up the playoff. Still, ``Just
get in a playoff, I said to myself,'' Elkington said. ``Jack Burke
(a great name from another era and neighbor near Houston) once told
me, `There's nothing wrong with a playoff. It's just two of you.
You eliminate 140 other guys.' So I was really hoping for a
playoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Elkington had won here four years ago, Funk a year later, but
this one hurt, cut him deeply. Conditions were perfect for scoring.
Of those who made the cut, only two players finished over par, Guy
Boros, whose daddy was Julius, and Iain Steel, a rookie from
Scotland. As for the Tour Championship, coming up later this month
at East Lake, there was little movement in the field, though
Kendall's 63 did move him up within easy striking distance. And
Funk won't go home and lick his wounds. Second place moved him
safely into the field for the pot-at-the-end-of-the-rainbow
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Elkington has a long-shot's chance, but for now it's on to
Scotland for the Dunhill Cup, one of those international affairs.
He'll represent Australia with Craig Parry and Stuart Appleby.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
