<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-SENIORTENNIS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Connors uses BTI final to finally defeat Wilander
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jimmy Connors achieved Sunday what 20 years on the ATP
Tour never wrought _ a victory over Mats Wilander. Connors won 6-2,
6-1 in the final of the BTI Champions, ending a five-match losing
streak in a rivalry that's been dormant for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of my better matches in about six years,'' Connors
said. ``That's a day that maybe you have once or twice a year,
where you go out and everything works, and even when you're late
you hit a shot good enough to keep you in.''
</P>
<P>
   Connors, 46, is 15-3 on the tour this season, and two of the
losses came when he withdrew with a foot injury. He's won five of
the eight tournaments he's entered and took over first place in the
points standings from John McEnroe with this victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first Nuveen Tour event for Wilander, who must be
granted wild cards to play until he turns 35 next August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't kid yourself, he'll get better in a hurry,'' Connors
said. ``He hasn't played that many matches. He's been away from
tennis for a while, and he's no different than anyone else. It'll
take him a while.''
</P>
<P>
   All five previous Connors-Wilander matches were played between
1984 and '88, after Connors had turned 32. Wilander won five Grand
Slam singles titles in that span and reached No. 1 in the world for
20 weeks at the end of 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt like anyone was stronger than me mentally then,
and I didn't think Jimmy Connors was,'' Wilander said. ``I had a
game where I could run his balls down, I could mix my game up, play
topspin and hit a lot of slices, and I could do it on different
surfaces. ... I realize now that's why I was as good as I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilander didn't seem surprised, though, that a man 12 years
older than him could win so decisively.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, Jimmy was in the semifinals of the U.S. Open
seven years ago, and that was the last year I played the tour
full-time,'' Wilander said. ``He's one of the few guys that's kept
playing the whole time and never put his racquet down for more than
a month or two, which is very wise. He's not much different now. He
played unbelievably.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Johan Kriek and Mel Purcell defeated local qualifiers Ned
Caswell and Howard Herr 6-4, 7-6 (7-5) in the doubles final.
Caswell and Herr, both teaching pros, split $4,000 for the week....
Sunday's announced attendance was 2,160, bringing the week's
eight-session total to 12,826, the lowest among the 11 U.S. stops
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
