<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-MEETING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO JOIN EXTRAORDINARY IMF SESSION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER   AND PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton joins an extraordinary meeting
Monday of 22 nations on the global financial crisis, there are new
pressures on a bedrock principle that has guided US economic policy
for the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Cold War ended, the United States has argued that
investors should be able to move their money to companies anywhere
in the world that will use it productively, and that governments
should get out of the way most of the time. Through the free
movement of capital, the reasoning went, the wealth of industrial
nations could help emerging nations build strong factories, labor
forces, and economies.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, top finance officials from the seven major
industrial nations meet here with counterparts from 15 developing
nations to survey a far different world from the one that US policy
envisioned. One-quarter of the globe is in recession, and millions
of people have slipped into poverty. US job growth is slowing, and
fears of a worldwide slump have cut stock values worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even some US allies are calling for new constraints on
markets and on investors, whom they blame for making the Asian
crisis worse by their panic withdrawal of billions of dollars from
Asian nations, leaving companies bankrupt and workers without jobs.
</P>
<P>
   France said Sunday that some nations, in times of crisis, should
be able to restrict investors from moving money into or out of a
country.
</P>
<P>
   The Commonwealth of 54 countries, which includes Britain and its
former colonies, said nations should be able to suspend debt
payments in a crisis without triggering default. And some people,
including leaders of developing nations and economists well in the
US academic mainstream, are proposing more radical solutions, such
as a more powerful International Monetary Fund or a global Federal
Reserve Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, nobody knows what the one true path is, and I'd
like to see a somewhat forgiving attitude toward countries that try
different policies to find out what that path is,'' Paul Krugman,
an economist at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology who has
become a leading thinker on the crisis, said in a speech Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very contentious thing,'' said Morris Goldstein, a
former IMF official who is now with the Institute for International
Economics, a Washington think tank. ``For a lot of these countries,
this is their Great Depression. As people get more desperate, you
get more desperate solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   The financial crisis, which began in Thailand 16 months ago and
spread to Russia, Brazil, and elsewhere, challenges the US position
that investors should be able to place their money freely or to buy
and sell any currency. It is a relatively new idea. While
supporting free trade in goods, many nations, including industrial
countries, maintained restrictions on money flows and investment
into the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Challenging the US view, countries with relatively closed
economies, such as China and India, have remained relatively stable
in the current crisis, while disaster has struck South Korea,
Thailand, and other nations that opened themselves to foreign
investors. These nations suffered as investors, who poured $100
billion into emerging Asian nations in 1996, caused havoc by
withdrawing that amount in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Prompting alarm in the West, Malaysia recently followed the path
of China and India, suspending trading in its currency while
invoking tough new limits on removing money from the country. Some
Western leaders expressed fear that other nations would decide to
``check out'' of the global economy in desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's meeting was called six months ago as ripples from the
Asian crisis spread across the globe.
</P>
<P>
   It will bring the so-called Group of Seven industrial nations _
the United States, Japan, Britain, Germany, France, Italy, and
Canada _ together with 15 emerging market nations to discuss the
``global financial architecture,'' a broad term that refers to the
IMF, the World Bank, and other agencies that were created to keep
the world economy running smoothly and to help developing nations.
The ``architecture'' also refers to a range of laws, as well as
business practices of private companies, for carrying out global
investment.
</P>
<P>
   These nations are considering many proposals that could help the
world economy in the short run.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Japan have lowered interest rates in
recent weeks, which spurs economic activity in those countries, and
European nations are under pressure to do the same. Japan has
proposed spending $30 billion of its own money to aid the ailing
economies of its East Asian neighbors. And Western nations appear
to be backing a package of rescue loans from the IMF, which they
largely control, to Brazil, the largest economy in South America,
which threatens to become the next victim of the financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's meeting is likely to consider proposals that will
help the world economy in the long term, ideas aimed at preventing
the next global crisis. Generally, the people trying to fashion a
new system fall into three camps, divided by their view of free
markets and liberal investment rules:
</P>
<P>
   _The Incrementalists. They include many Western officials, such
as Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin. In their view, free markets
generally work well. The main problem, they argue is that investors
sometimes make bad decisions because they are deprived of good
information by banks, companies, and governments, particularly in
developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, a host of anti-fraud rules and the
Securities and Exchange Commission allow people to invest with
confidence. Rubin and others want the global finance system to
develop something equivalent. They talk of requiring more
``transparency,'' which generally calls on foreign companies to
adopt American-style accounting practices that allow investors and
lenders to see more clearly into the financial workings of their
business partners.
</P>
<P>
   They also focus on the need for US-style bank regulation to
prevent the kind of reckless borrowing and lending that many said
was at the root of the Asian collapse.
</P>
<P>
   _Freer-marketers. Broadly speaking, they want to remove all
controls on investors, and they tend to believe that agencies like
the IMF distort markets and force investors to make bad decisions.
Representative Jim Saxton, Republican of New Jersey, one of the
leading IMF critics in Congress, said emergency loans, like the
type the IMF offered last year to South Korea, Thailand, and
Indonesia, are counterproductive, as they encourage investors to
place risky bets in the belief that the international community
will bail them out.
</P>
<P>
   _The ``Plan B'' types. Like Krugman, the MIT economist, they say
the Western prescription has failed, and it is time to try a Plan
B. Generally, they say governments should be able to put more
constraints on markets and investors.
</P>
<P>
   Some advocate capital controls to keep ``hot money'' from
flowing too quickly in or out of a country. A country could impose
a tax on investment or follow Chile, which until recently required
companies that borrowed foreign money to place 30 percent in the
Chilean central bank as a reserve that could be used if conditions
worsen. Others are calling for a ``super-IMF'' or global Federal
Reserve Bank, which would bring the same kind of stability to the
world economy that the US Fed has to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Another set of proposals would address the fact that many
emerging nations are mired in debt, which has only become harder to
pay off as their currencies have fallen in value. Some nations owe
so much to lenders that they have little money to spend in their
own economies to spur growth. These nations might be able to set
new terms for repaying their debt, or even suspend payments without
incurring penalties from the IMF or other global institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Although US officials have been vague about their plans, some
analysts said they expect the United States will eventually endorse
an approach similar to that used during the debt crisis of the
early 1980s. The United States agreed to partly guarantee what was
called ``Brady bonds,'' which were issued by the debtor nations and
given to lenders in return for writing off their loans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufauthor &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This story was reported by Aaron Zitner in Washington and Peter
G. Gosselin in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
