<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-VOTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDOSO HEADED FOR REELECTION IN BRAZIL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO _ President Fernando Henrique Cardoso appeared to
be headed for victory Sunday in his bid to become Brazil's first
re-elected leader, in elections that seemed driven more by economic
worries than by political ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's Superior Electoral Tribunal said early in the evening
that with 16.3 percent of ballots counted, Cardoso had 50.9 percent
of valid votes, just enough to avoid a second-round runoff. A
leftist candidate Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva, had 34.4 percent of
valid votes, according to the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   There has been little doubt in this country of 164 million that
the 67-year-old Cardoso, a popular Social Democrat, would win. But
his victory demonstrated the hope by Brazilians that he could
strengthen an $800 billion economy that has been rocked over the
past two months by crises in Asia and Russia, and whose collapse
could threaten markets and companies in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has lost nearly $30 billion in foreign capital since
August, prompting a steep rise in interest rates. The country's
currency, the real, appears headed for devaluation. Government
officials have met recently with the International Monetary Fund
and other agencies to negotiate a package of loans, but no
agreement has been announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard from people in places like New York's stock
market speak about Brazil'' by pulling out their investments, said
Joao Mendonca, 22, a local worker for Cardoso's Social Democratic
Party. ``Now it's time for Brazilian people to speak up with their
votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso, a former finance minister, was the architect of the
1994 anti-inflation plan that now appears to be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   He persuaded Congress last year to lift a ban that had
prohibited executive office holders from serving two consecutive
terms. Now Cardoso needs congressional approval for three new
constitutional changes he has proposed to slow the government's
growing deficit and to restore investor confidence in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   As an intense sun bore down on this beach-ringed resort city of
5 million residents Sunday, voters dutifully cast their votes as
the law demands for citizens over 18. Throughout the country,
Brazilians reported to elementary schools, government bank branches
and post offices, which for the day were converted into polling
precincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been cloudy lately, so the sun feels especially good,''
said Yvonne Rodrigues, an ebony-haired 24-year-old hotel worker who
cast her ballot in the morning and spent the afternoon at
Copacabana beach with two friends. ``The beach can either be a
distraction from voting or it can be your reward, depending on what
kind of person you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Even along Avenida Atlantico, the glittery drive that runs the
length of Impanema and Copacabana beaches, there was plenty of
politics to be seen and heard. Youngsters waved larger-than-life
banners promoting candidates, beach vendors peddling peanuts and
beer wore campaign hats, and the white marbled sidewalks were
coated with flyers.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Protasio cast his ballot the way most urban voters do,
electronically, by punching a number into a small box. An image of
the candidate assigned to that number appeared on a screen. Another
button must be pressed to confirm the selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the most important issue is our ecology and making sure
we use our resources in the best way possible,'' said Protasio, a
28-year-old computer worker and volunteer for the Green Party who
voted for one Cardoso's opponents, Ciro Gomes. ``Yes the economy is
important, but it's all tied together, economy and ecology.
</P>
<P>
   After casting their ballots, voters receive government-issued
receipts as proof of their vote. Those who do not vote run the risk
of being called before an administrative judge and cut off from
some public services, such as obtaining a passport.
</P>
<P>
   Marinha Lopes, a 55-year-old waitress in a family-owned
restaurant, did not mind the voting requirement on a day when it
seemed that most everyone headed for the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the beach type because I don't really have the body
for it,'' said Lopes, who voted for Cardoso. ``Besides, I think
it's important to vote and to help keep the economy going strong.
He's the only one who can do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
