<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-OFF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS FISHER'S PRICE TO PAY
</HEADLINE>
 THE WALL-COLUMN-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The poster outside the Sears store at the Media City Center in
Burbank, Calif., invited customers in Sunday to the store's new
licensed-apparel section to meet Derek Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers' new starting guard?
</P>
<P>
   Well, around here, he's known as ``Guard, Basketball Star.''
</P>
<P>
   He plays for the Lakers, but nowhere did it _ or could it _ say
so. NBA lockout rules were strictly enforced.
</P>
<P>
   The photos he signed for a steady stream of fans showed him
dribbling a ball in what unmistakably looks like a Lakers uniform.
Except the team name is erased.
</P>
<P>
   On the racks around the table at which he sat, there was more
NFL gear than NBA stuff. In fact, there was nothing with the Lakers
name on it except for a few stacks of hats that they found in the
warehouse and brought out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA won't ship any licensed merchandise right now,'' said
a store rep. ``Otherwise we'd be selling out.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, a relative pauper in a league of ruthless
multimillionaires, could only half smile when anyone asked when
he'd be back with ... that team we're not supposed to mention. And
many asked, especially the hundred or so who lined up an hour
before his 1 p.m. arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Four-year-old Rudy Rodriguez of Sun Valley, whose parents
brought him all decked out in a Lakers uniform, got his gold shorts
signed, shook Fisher's hand and said: ``We'll see you at the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' said Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Fisher admitted: ``It affects more people than you think.
When they ask, all I try to do is keep the conversation going
somewhere else. I mean, I've done three of these store signings in
the last few months, and I love meeting people, but I don't want to
be doing this all winter.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Then we have Magic Johnson, who isn't that far removed as an
NBA player and will always be a heartbeat away from another
comeback. He owns 1/20th of the Lakers _ so does that mean he even
covers one of the 12 players' full salary?
</P>
<P>
   So the guy who should've given up public speaking when his
talk-show producers muzzled him a few months ago shows up on CNN to
rap about the NBA lockout and exclaims: ``The owners are doing
their part ... we're doing our part.'' He follows it up with:
``We're the ones flying them on private planes all over the place.
When I played, we had to get up at 4 or 5 in the morning to catch
6:30 or 7 a.m. flights. We had to go through the airport, eat the
airport food like everybody else. Now ... they don't have to mess
with their bags like we did when I played....''
</P>
<P>
   First, save it for someone who owns a Stradivarius. Second, you
left out the part about how sometimes, when they had unheated spas
at the team hotel, the players had to walk 10 miles through the
snow to use the whirlpool at the arenas....
</P>
<P>
   __ Meet Jim Rome Thursday at Tower Records on the Sunset Strip.
Bring cache....
</P>
<P>
   __ Meet Mark McGwire tonight on ``Late Show with David
Letterman.'' Maybe Mr. Mighty-Mite will show Dave his own ``stupid
human trick:'' _ he can made 70 baseballs disappear....
</P>
<P>
   __ We don't need no stinkin' Jim Leyland anyway. Not in our
smoke-free dugout....
</P>
<P>
   __ The wrongful termination lawsuit that former AM-1150
nighttime co-host Joey Haim filed against the station and the
Dodgers will be allowed to proceed in the state court rather than
federal court, a judge has ruled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers will do no better in Joey's case than they did
this season,'' said attorney Steven Siegal.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Haim: ``I appreciate people who've said they miss me on the
air and I'm sorry listeners have to stomach the new nighttime
snoreathon.''...
</P>
<P>
   __ The LPGA's Danielle Ammaccapane signed a deal with the NFL to
wear the colors of the team in the city where she's playing that
week. So when the tour comes through L.A., she'll be wearing ... uh
... nothing.
</P>
<P>
   __ Get past the fact Mike Tyson uses the naughty word 67 times
in his November Playboy interview. The gist of it _ he knows people
have used him and he's simply angry about it _ is the first Q-and-A
with Tyson that accurately portrays him as !ital!the!off! raging
bull....
</P>
<P>
   __ Playboy teases to its December issue with a blurb about a
pictorial of Katarina Witt that ``will knock your skates off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
