<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANTZ' HAS VIEWERS MARCHING IN, SETS OCTOBER RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Moviegoers swarmed the nation's multiplexes to
view ``Antz'' as the computer-animated comedy topped a robust box
office by setting an October record with an estimated
$16.8 &UR;  &LR; million &UR;  &LR; weekend total, studio sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of ``Antz,'' the much-anticipated first animated
film from DreamWorks SKG, was showing at 2,449 theaters and
eclipsed the $16.6 &UR;  &LR; million roll-out for ``Stargate'' in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   It also edged the opening of Robin Williams' spiritual drama,
``What Dreams May Come,'' which debuted with $15.5 &UR;  &LR; million at
2,526 theaters, and the third weekend of the action-comedy ``Rush
Hour,'' which brought in $15 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,701 sites.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's other major opening, slapstick comedy ``A Night at
the Roxbury,'' also turned in a solid performance in fourth place
with $10 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,865 theaters, underscoring the strength of
the market during what is traditionally a slow period. Weekend
overall grosses were up 29 percent over the same weekend last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``These results feel just like a summer weekend, and they're
incredible numbers for October,'' said Robert Bucksbaum, president
of the Reel Source forecasting service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has become a 12-month-a-year business with enough variety
of genres for all audiences,'' noted analyst Arthur Rockwell of
Drake &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antz,'' featuring the voices of Woody Allen and Sharon Stone,
opened six months earlier than originally planned and has a
seven-week lead on The Walt Disney Co.'s computer-animated comedy
``A Bug's Life,'' co-produced with ``Toy Story'' creator Pixar
Animation. Analysts said the early success of ``Antz'' is unlikely
to detract from ``A Bug's Life,'' expected to be one of the holiday
season's top performers.
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR;  &LR; `Antz' has obviously succeeded very well for a non-Disney
animated film, but I don't think it will have much impact on `A
Bug's Life,' which has a built-in audience and a strong buzz,''
Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum predicted ``Antz'' will beat the $63 &UR;  &LR; million taken in
by ``Beavis and Butt-head Do America,'' the top non-Disney animated
movie, due to strong support among all audiences.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks distribution chief James Tharp said ``Antz''
attracted strong support in all regions and age groups, leading to
the addition of an additional 250 theaters next weekend, which is a
three-day holiday for many filmgoers due to Columbus Day on Monday.
``We think we'll hold interest very well,'' Tharp added.
</P>
<P>
   The performance by ``Antz'' came amid competition from Major
League Baseball playoffs and surprisingly strong interest in ``What
Dreams May Come,'' a PolyGram release delayed from the summer.
Bucksbaum said the solid numbers for ``Dreams,'' in which Williams
seeks reunification with his wife in the afterlife, reflect
audiences' strong interest in films with spiritual themes such as
``City of Angels'' and ``Michael.''
</P>
<P>
   New Line's ``Rush Hour'' also continued to draw well, going past
the $84 million mark after only 17 days. Within the next two weeks,
it should become the 10th movie this year and 176th in Hollywood
history to join the list of films topping $100 million in domestic
grosses.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum said ``A Night at the Roxbury,'' based on characters
created by ``Saturday Night Live'' stars Will Ferrell and Chris
Kattan, benefited from Paramount's strong trailer and the absence
of other new films aimed at the teen-age market.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of thrillers in their second weekends took the next two
spots, with MGM's ``Ronin'' grossing $7.2 million at 2,487 sites to
edge Sony's ``Urban Legend'' with $7 million at 2,257 locations.
Finishing a still-strong seventh was ``There's Something About
Mary'' with $3.6 million at 2,177 theaters to bring the comedy's
82-day total to $158.2 million for 20th Century Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary,'' in its 12th week, is now the 51st-highest domestic
grosser ever after ``The Firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 were the third weekend of Universal's
family drama ``One True Thing'' with $2.7 million at 1,620
theaters, DreamWorks' 11th weekend of ``Saving Private Ryan'' with
$1.7 million at 1,510 screens and Disney's fourth weekend of
``Simon Birch'' with $1.5 million at 930 theaters. The fourth
weekend of Miramax's fast-fading ``Rounders'' was 11th with $1.1
million at 1,475 sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' has grossed $184.3 million after 66 days
and is now the 29th highest domestic grosser after ``Snow White and
the Seven Dwarfs.''
</P>
<P>
   Artisan's limited opening of horror-thriller ``Dee Snyder's
Strange Land'' generated unimpressive returns with $355,000 at 315
theaters, while Fox Searchlight's shipboard comedy ``The
Imposters'' debuted with a moderate $325,000 at 66 sites.
</P>
<P>
   Year-to-date business is near $5.1 billion and 12 percent ahead
of the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antz,'' ``What Dreams May Come'' and ``Rush Hour'' will face
competition next weekend from the opening of Disney's ``Holy Man''
with Eddie Murphy. Disney is also generating strong early buzz for
the Oct. 16 debut of ``Beloved,'' starring Oprah Winfrey as a
runaway slave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
