when employers' health insurance costs were surging 15 percent a
year, the giant Sprint Corp. was quick to shift to health
maintenance organizations and their businesslike management of
medical care. Sprint's costs promptly stabilized. Today, its
comprehensive benefit program stands as a model of what Congress
and industry envisioned four years ago when they rejected President
Clinton's health plan and left the health-care system to the tides
of the marketplace. Yet along the hallways at Sprint headquarters
here, the great expectations for managed care have dimmed. By Peter
