<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8933 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-NASCAR-RAIL-COX     10-04 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-RAIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Breaking down the UAW-GM 500
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first 100: Wild and wet. Jerry Nadeau got it started,
hitting the wall in the fourth turn on the first lap. Steve Grissom
followed, slapping the wall in turn two on lap 11. Then came Jeff
Gordon, who started 26th and moved to the front on lap 70, beating
Mark Martin out of the pits. Next came the weird part. The race was
red-flagged on lap 94 due to water seeping under the wall on the
backstretch. And, would you believe that Darrell Waltrip started
43rd and was 13th when the race was red-flagged. Racing resumed
after a 42-minute delay.
</P>
<P>
   Lap leaders: Martin (60), Ernie Irvan (14), Ward Burton (10),
Gordon (7), Derrike Cope (6), Bobby Labonte (3). Retired: David
Green. Under caution: 24 laps.
</P>
<P>
   The second 100: On the restart, Gordon went backward before
settling into third behind the Pontiacs of Ward Burton and Irvan.
Waltrip's ride lasted only three more laps before an oil pressure
problem put him behind the wall and the race under caution. Ward
Burton again led on the restart, followed by Irvan. Gordon settled
into third while Martin remained fifth. Waltrip returned to the
race on lap 126, but three laps down. Caution on lap 132 and on
restart Gordon regained the lead. This time Martin came out right
behind Gordon and regained the lead on lap 148 and opened a five
car-length lead. Gordon comes back on lap 171 to lead. The demons
that sidelined Dale Jarrett last week at Martinsville turned up
here on lap 174 with an over-heating problem in his Taurus causing
him to go a lap down.
</P>
<P>
   Lap leaders: Martin (22), Gordon (40), Ward Burton (25), Irvan
(12), Brett Bodine (1). Retired: Bobby Labonte, Dick Trickle. Under
caution: 44 laps:
</P>
<P>
   The third 100, plus 34Martin regained the lead on restart caused
by the cars of Johnny Benson and Rick Mast wrecking in turn two.
That was nothing compared to the 10-car pileup which followed on
lap 203. It was started by Bobby Labonte, who lost control, got
sideways and slammed into the wall, and everybody wrecked behind
him _ Terry Labonte, Ricky Rudd, Rusty Wallace, Jeremy Mayfield,
Kyle Petty, Dale Earnhardt, Sterling Marlin, Mike Skinner and Kenny
Irwin. When the dust settled, Martin took the lead on the restart,
pulling away to a six-car lead, while Gordon slowed, falling to
sixth, apparently due to a deep dent on the left side of his
bumper. Jerry Nadeau became his salvation, bringing out the
caution. It didn't help Gordon, however. His crew could not repair
the dent, leaving his spoiler an inch short.
</P>
<P>
   Lap leaders: Martin (133), Michael Waltrip (1). Retired: Nadeau,
Irvan, Rudd. Under caution: 67 laps
</P>
<P>
   Today's impactIf you call Martin gaining 39 points on Gordon an
impact, this is it.
</P>
<P>
   Who was hot Martin totally dominated this one. He led six times
for 215 laps and won by 1.110 seconds, an eternity in this sport.
</P>
<P>
   Who was not Jarrett ran into hard luck again. He blew an engine
last week at Martinsville and finished 42nd, burying his Winston
Cup championship hopes, and was 24th Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Points update The top five: Gordon, 4475; Martin, 4283; Jarrett,
3918; Wallace, 3,801; Jeff Burton, 3,672.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know? Bill Elliott started 29th and finished a
hard-earned 11th. . . Asked if he had any close calls Sunday, Jimmy
Spencer answered, ``Oh yeah, I drug a spoiler around the race
track, some hood came underneath my car from Johnny Benson. I
missed Dick Trickle and Ernie Irvan by the skin of my teeth when
they wrecked, and I missed a bunch of other accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week's story line It's on to Talladega and restrictor-plate
racing, which neither Gordon nor Martin hold close to their hearts.
Of the two, Gordon may be the best-prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
