<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mark it down: Martin's on a roll after seventh win
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Mark Martin pulled off his best imitation of
Jeff Gordon and then some Sunday, leading 215 of the 334 laps and
driving away from the field to win the UAW-GM Quality 500 at
Charlotte Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was Martin's seventh of the year and third in the
last six weeks. And it cut 35 points from Jeff Gordon's Winston Cup
lead as the season turns the final bend with six to go.
</P>
<P>
   His margin of victory was 1.110 seconds over runner-up Ward
Burton. There were 11 cautions for 65 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Track position was everything and we had good track position
most of the day,'' Martin said. ``There were an awful lot of good
cars today that could have had a chance to win. But most of them
had trouble today.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was one of them. He started 26th and it wasn't until lap
76 that he led for the first time. He would lead three other times,
but never in a dominating manner as he has in previous races. He
was slow to get started on restarts and his long runs were often
cut short by the 11 cautions that ate 65 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we dodged a lot of bullets today,'' Gordon said.
``We were fortunate to get the car back to fifth. We got some
damage on one of those wrecks, and the car just wasn't the same
after that. I thought it was going to be a great battle here for
the championship and a great battle for the race until that
point.''
</P>
<P>
   It likely would not have mattered. Martin drove as on a rail,
taking his Taurus wherever he wanted. And over the final 133 laps,
he led all but one.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how frustrating it is to win and not be able to shake
Gordon, Martin laughed and said, ``Do I look frustrated? This is
the greatest year of my life. I don't see how anybody can could
look at this year and think it was a failure. Today was a great day
for this race team.''
</P>
<P>
   It was almost a great day for Ward Burton, who seemed most
capable of filling up Martin's rear view mirror. He tracked him
over the final 90 laps, but never got to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guys have some awesome motors, and it showed today. But I
was a little bit loose going in (the turns) all day,'' Burton said.
``I know we had him beat on motor. We were just off on chassis a
little bit. I can't complain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
