<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY WINS IN CLOSE CALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ It took 10 minutes Sunday to identify
California's best hope for next month's Breeders' Cup Turf _ 2
minutes, 2 seconds to run the Oak Tree Turf Championship and 8
minutes to pore over the photo finish.
</P>
<P>
   Military, the front runner with Corey Nakatani riding, and
Bonapartiste, a French-bred with Chris McCarron aboard, hit the
wire together after 1\ miles. Santa Anita officials called for
three prints of the black-and-white photo before certifying that
Military was the winner by half a nostril.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the longer ones,'' steward George Slender said
of the deliberation.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Military's number 2 was posted on the tote board,
most in the crowd were guessing it was a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have been happy with a dead heat,'' said Wally Dollase,
trainer of Saudi Prince Ahmed bin Salman's Military.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-year-old son of Danzig was the fans' 3-1 third choice
behind 5-2 Bonapartiste and 4-5 River Bay, who'd finished first and
second in front of Military in the Del Mar Handicap last month.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Del Mar defeat, Military had won a pair of minor
races, his first since coming over from England.
</P>
<P>
   Dollase thought correctly that Military would improve with the
move to Santa Anita, reasoning his European temperament would
prefer the serenity of the larger backstretch and his long body
would prefer the gentler turns.
</P>
<P>
   Nakatani took full advantage of Military's edge in early speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping he'd be three lengths in front at the top of the
stretch, and gosh-darn it if he didn't do it,'' Dollase said. ``I
thought that guy (Bonapartiste) was going to go by him, but he dug
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonapartiste made it close. River Bay finished a distant third
in the five-horse race, giving jockey Pat Day another high-profile
flop in Southern California this year, to go with Gentlemen and
Touch Gold.
</P>
<P>
   The $300,000 Oak Tree Turf Championship, which was known as the
Oak Tree Invitational when it produced Breeders' Cup Turf winners
Great Communicator (1988), Kotashaan ('93) and Northern Spur ('95),
is the first Breeders' Cup prep on the Santa Anita schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Next are Saturday's Oak Leaf for 2-year-old fillies and Sunday's
Norfolk for 2-year-olds, and the Oct. 17 Goodwood Handicap. Silver
Charm returned from Kentucky to Santa Anita Saturday night to train
for the Goodwood.
</P>
<P>
   The seven Breeders' Cup races will be run Nov. 7 at Churchill
Downs.
</P>
<P>
   Dollase said he expects to run Military in the $2 million
Breeders' Cup Turf, though he acknowledged the 1{-mile distance
might be too much for the colt.
</P>
<P>
   Military gave Dollase and Prince Salman their second stakes
victory Sunday. Sapphire Ring, ridden by Gary Stevens, won the
$73,230 Possibly Perfect for 3-year-old fillies.
</P>
<P>
   Two-year-old Proud Louie and jockey Jose Valdivia Jr. won the
$100,000 California Sires Stakes by nine lengths for trainer Jose
Silva and Tricar Stables.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-04-98 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
