<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA VAULTS INTO CONTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Don't look now, but the Arizona Wildcats are on the
move again. Most people figured that if a team from Arizona was
going to wind up in the Fiesta Bowl in Tempe this season, it would
be the Arizona State Sun Devils, but a last-second loss to
Washington in the season opener basically took all the devil out of
ASU, which never did recover, with Saturday night's loss to
Southern California the latest effort in futility.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State has dropped so low coach Bruce Snyder's team must
worry about finishing above .500, never mind the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the team in Tucson. The Wildcats have quietly
been winning each week and steadily climbing in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Their latest triumph has vaulted the Wildcats from 14th to 10th
in the AP writers poll and 11th in the coaches poll (coaches always
are a little slow in making jumps like that, most likely because
they have to study the films first).
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake. The Wildcats are climbing. And if you
happened to catch the ending of Saturday night's remarkable
come-from-behind 31-28 win over Washington, climbing can be taken
literally.
</P>
<P>
   Here was the situation: Washington leading, 28-24; Arizona on
the Husky 9-yard line; 4 seconds left. Arizona quarterback Ortege
Jenkins, with nowhere to throw the ball, took off on a desperate
final sprint to the end zone. He reached the 4 and was about to be
sandwiched by three Washington players.
</P>
<P>
   But in a you-had-to-see-it-to-believe-it move (and even then
it's hard to accept), Jenkins somersaulted over the Huskies'
Marques Hairston and Brendan Jones into the end zone for the
winning score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get him in the gymnastics program,'' said teammate
Marcus Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins had a perfectly logical explanation for his move. ``I
wasn't going through them,'' he said. ``So I went over them.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever or however, Arizona is 5-0, has won nine games in
succession over the last two seasons and can make itself the major
contender in the Pac-10 and perhaps even a long shot to make it to
the Fiesta Bowl if it beats No. 3 UCLA Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Before you write off Arizona against the Bruins, consider this.
The teams have split the last 10 meetings and next week's game will
be played in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Another out-of-the-pack team is Georgia, which also is unbeaten
and eked out a 28-27 win at Louisiana State Saturday night. A win
over No. 4 Tennessee Saturday will put the Bulldogs in prime
position to get to the SEC title game in Atlanta in December.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Normally, we don't approve of coaches putting a gag order on
their players with the media after their games, but Washington
coach  &UR; Jim Lambright's  &LR; explanation made sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm protecting them from the stupidity of what went on,'' said
Lambright after enduring his second loss in succession.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of stupidity, the NCAA has struck again, according to
Arizona officials. Arizona cornerback  &UR; Chris McAlister  &LR; has to miss
the UCLA game. Why? Because he took out a loan to buy disability
insurance, which the NCAA said is fine. But McAlister took out a
loan for $3,000 more than the $11,000 disability payment, which the
NCAA said is a violation, so McAlister has to sit out a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody ought to be angry,'' said Arizona coach  &UR; Dick
Tomey &LR; . ``It's unfair and a gross abuse of power.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winning is winning at any level and two-time defending Division
3 national champion Mount Union is still at it, with a 32-game
winning streak that is the longest in college football ... Ohio
State's 27-9 victory over Penn State Saturday gave coach  &UR; John
Cooper  &LR; a 23-22-3 record against ranked teams in his 11 seasons in
Columbus, which doesn't sound all that impressive for a perennial
contender like the Buckeyes. But after the 1992 season, the
Buckeyes were only 3-13-2 against ranked teams under Cooper ...
UCLA's 49-17 win over Washington State was only the second time in
eight seasons the Bruins have won their Pac-10 opener ... When
Colorado beat Oklahoma Saturday, it marked the fifth straight time
the Buffaloes have beaten the Sooners. No other team _ including
Nebraska _ has been able to beat Oklahoma more than three straight
times ... Navy's loss to West Virginia marked the 22d straight loss
against a ranked team for the Midshipmen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame has had first-half problems all season, getting
outscored, 79-23, in the first half of its first three games. That
was not a problem against Stanford, however, as the Irish rolled to
a 28-3 halftime lead before coasting home, 35-17 ... Is anyone
surprised that Syracuse is 2-2 after the first month? ... Curry has
won two games in the last three weeks after going winless last
season. Just shows you what a good coach _  &UR; Steve Nelson  &LR; _ can do
for a team ... Florida coach  &UR; Steve Spurrier  &LR; was not happy after
the Gators' lackluster 16-10 win over Alabama. ``The Gators don't
play like champions anymore,'' muttered Spurrier ... Game of the
Year in the Big East is looming on Halloween _ Temple, which has
yet to win a game, against hapless Rutgers, which has a 1-point win
over 1-AA Richmond and a victory over Army ... Wonder what would
have happened to Oklahoma State if its ``home'' game had been
played in Stillwater, instead of Kansas City's Arrowhead Stadium,
where Nebraska's crowd gave the Huskers a home-field edge, one they
needed in a 24-17 win that ended with Oklahoma State on the Husker
1-yard line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
