<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday 10/4/98. Photo clients
will automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or
may download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 4, 1998 -- VAN-GOGH-EXHIBIT-FLOATER,
10-4 -- Visitors viewing Vincent van Gogh's ``Self Portrait as an
Artist'' Sunday in Washington at the National Gallery's ``Van
Gogh's Van Goghs'' exhibition. The museum expects 4,000 to 5,000
visitors a day will see the 72 works, most from Amsterdam's Van
Gogh museum, through Jan. 3. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Oct. 4, 1998 -- BBO-STRAWBERRY, 10-4 -- Danny
Mecka, 12, of Lodi, N.J., at Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center
Sunday, holding a card for Darryl Strawberry, from him and fellow
Little Leaguers. ``To Strawberry,'' the card read, ``I always
looked up to you when I was young. Get well.'' Strawberry underwent
surgery to remove a cancerous tumor from his colon on Saturday.
(Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CULLMAN, Ala. -- Oct. 4, 1998 -- BEERLESS-BLAST, 10-4 --
Residents of Cullman, Ala., standing for the Pledge of Allegiance
during the opening ceremonies of the town's 17th annual beerless
Oktoberfest. Cullman County is dry, bone dry, and has been for 60
years. And that creates something of a culture clash at this time
each year, as the descendants of the German immigrants who settled
this area honor their heritage in a way that the volk from the old
country simply would not understand. The county voted itself dry in
the late 1930s. (Alan S. Weiner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOMBAY, India -- Oct. 4, 1998 -- INDIA-GANDHI-2, 10-4 --
Gopal Godse, 78, with four others in the picture behind him,
conspired in the killing of Mohandas K. Gandhi. Gopal Godse's
brother, Nathuram, was executed. Now, a play about the killer, ``I,
Nathuram Godse Speaking,'' has been shut down after only seven
performances, banned as a threat to law and order on the strong
recommendation of the national government. (John Giannini/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOMBAY, India -- Oct. 4, 1998 -- INDIA-GANDHI-1, 10-4 --
Pradeep Dalvi, whose play about the killer of Mohandas K. Gandhi,
Nathuram Godse, has been banned in India. The drama won no fans in
the Hindu nationalist-led government in New Delhi. Despite sold-out
shows, ``I, Nathuram Godse Speaking,'' has been shut down after
only seven performances, deemed a threat to law and order on the
strong recommendation of the national government. (Celia W.
Dugger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Oct. 4, 1998 -- ONLINE-ASTROLOGER-MEDIA, 10-4
-- Susan Miller, whose Astrology Zone is one of the most popular of
its kind on the Web, sees her role as that of giving broad advice
rather than specific predictions. Ms. Miller is no longer surprised
by the variety of people who are interested in her line of work.
``The Web allows people who might not otherwise admit an interest
in horoscopes to check out the stars in relative privacy,'' says
Ms. Miller. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SUNNYVALE, Calif. -- Oct. 4, 1998 -- HITECH-TEMPS, 10-4
-- John Drew , left, chief executive of INS, and Donald McKinney,
chairman. INS, founded in 1991, does not manufacture equipment. It
does not run computers. It does not re-engineer business processes.
What INS does do is design, manage and secure communications
networks. The company does it so well that it has become the
network engineers' engineer -- the expert that the network experts
can turn to when they need a specialist's touch. (Sam Morris/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Oct. 4, 1998 -- VIACOM-BLOCKBUSTER, 10-4 --
Sumner Redstone, the chairman of Viacom Inc., says he is intent on
increasing Blockbuster Video's market share by ``providing more
copies of hit films.'' The results from this ``Satisfaction
Guaranteed'' campaign are already evident. In the second quarter of
1998, which ended on June 30, same-store sales improved more than
12.8 percent from those in the quarter a year earlier. (Marilynn K.
Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
