<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT &LR;      10-04 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY with RON ALEXANDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   I heard this exchange in the breakfast room of my hotel during a
recent trip to London. Over the hubbub of Japanese, French and
Saudi guests ordering from Greek and Pakistani waiters, a woman was
explaining the scene to her young daughter. ``Darling,'' she said.
``It's just like New York; no one speaks English.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURA J. WARREN
</P>
<P>
   A typical New York example of anthropomorphism, overheard by
Michael Parley. A woman in Riverside Park chastising her dog: ``You
have to learn to not bark so much,'' she said in all seriousness.
``It's not good. It's so ...'' (pause while she searched for the
right word) ``... manipulative.''
</P>
<P>
   When Wilma Askinas' husband, Milton, decided to take a memory
course, she signed up for a course on automobiles that was held at
a different location but on the same night, at the same time. Both
prepared themselves, he with a book on memory, she with a tool
chest filled with shiny new tools. On the appropriate night, Mrs.
Askinas went off to her class. When she returned, she found her
husband asleep on the couch. ``How was the course?'' she asked. ``I
forgot to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a reception, marking the end of the academic year for
graduating psychiatry residents. A man whose wife was one of the
graduates was left on his own for a short time. The man, who wishes
to remain anonymous, was surrounded by what he called a
sophisticated group of well-known professors, residents, spouses
and other members of the psychiatric community. He was amused and
impressed at the exchange he overheard between two of the
professors.
</P>
<P>
   Professor No. 1: ``I want to apologize to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor No. 2: ``Oh really? For what?''
</P>
<P>
   Professor No. 1: ``Well over the past six months or so, I feel
that I've been rather short with you. I haven't been supportive of
your work and I don't think that I've treated you with the respect
that you deserve. But I just wanted you to know that this has
nothing to do with you. I've been having some personal problems and
I never meant to bring these problems to work.
</P>
<P>
   Professor No. 2: ``Oh no, no, no. Don't be silly. It's an honor
to be the object of your transference.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a one o'clock performance of ``Saving Private Ryan'' and
Dorothea A. Hecht had bought a bag of popcorn to munch and lunch
on. Several minutes into the picture, she felt a tap on her
shoulder and heard a sharp chastising voice: ``Aren't you ashamed
of yourself? Men are dying in the water and you're eating
POPCORN!''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hecht kept on eating, but _ discretion being the better part
of valor _ not before she changed her seat.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Brous and her husband, Philip, were grocery shopping at
a supermarket recently. The market was being renovated, which meant
that a number of items had been temporarily relocated. Philip Brous
asked an employee where he could find English muffins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mister, we don't carry foreign breads,'' was the reply.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   A hot day this summer found me at Kennedy Airport's
International Arrivals Building, awaiting the arrival of loved
ones. The customs doors would swing open, and sometimes a few
people would drift out and other times large groups would appear,
all pushing overloaded luggage carts.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly there was a collective gasp as a dark-haired young
woman walked out alone. She stood before us dressed in an elaborate
floor-length white wedding dress and veil. The huge crowd burst
into spontaneous applause as she made her way down the walkway.
</P>
<P>
   When she got to the end, she started back. At that moment, a
young man, holding a small bouquet of flowers, came out of the
crowd. As he shyly touched her arm, she turned to him and they
embraced. We burst into applause once again, but as the couple
walked out, we were left with questions:
</P>
<P>
   Was this her intended? Was this their first meeting? Were they
going directly to the wedding ceremony? Where was her luggage?
</P>
<P>
   _ SUSAN MAINZER RUBIN
</P>
<P>
   The scene: Fast-food restaurant with an advertised special of a
slice of pepperoni pizza and a 16-ounce soda, all for $2.75. Otto
Salamon places his order but asks for a small soda instead of the
large one. He moves down the aisle to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Cashier, punching her computer-driven register: ``That's
$4.75.''
</P>
<P>
   Salamon: ``What happened to the $2.75 special?''
</P>
<P>
   Cashier: ``That's for pizza with a large soda. What you got
there is pizza with a small soda. For that we have to charge you
extra.''
</P>
<P>
   Salamon: ``How can we get the special price then?''
</P>
<P>
   Cashier: ``We can buy a large soda instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Salamon returned to the counter to make the exchange. The
counter man tossed his small soda in the garbage and handed him a
16-ounce container. Salamon returned to the cashier, paid his $2.75
and remarked that the whole thing made no sense.
</P>
<P>
   Cashier, with an are-you-stupid-or-what look: ``Then how come
it's in the computer?''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Lerner thinks that perhaps this note, written by her
granddaughter Jacklyn when she was 7 years old, may be a child's
version of being boiled in oil. Jacklyn had reached the end of her
patience with her little sister and dashed off a warning:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Allison, I am sueing you! You are going to be punished in
a quart of law. Love, Jacklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   TAXI, TAXI
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to New York cabbies
</P>
<P>
   My travel joys return
</P>
<P>
   Each time I take a taxi
</P>
<P>
   And their origins I learn.
</P>
<P>
   Back to West Africa
</P>
<P>
   Three times I went last week
</P>
<P>
   And Haiti is a regular
</P>
<P>
   For the broken French I speak.
</P>
<P>
   When English is unusable
</P>
<P>
   And the route from A to B
</P>
<P>
   Is indirect with meter racing
</P>
<P>
   Those pleasant feelings flee.
</P>
<P>
   _ CARLYN PARKER
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   My wife thought it would be nice if I picked out a perfume for
her. I had never done this before, so I didn't know what to expect
when I walked into Bloomingdale's perfume department. I endured
sales pitches and smelled printed tabs of paper, which cheerful men
and women handed me after spritzing them with the corresponding
brand's scent. At one counter, I was offered a jar of coffee beans
to clean my nose's palette.
</P>
<P>
   After half an hour, during which I sampled 24 different
perfumes, I could barely discern the nuances among scents _
citrusy, flowery, earthy. I finally settled at one counter and
spent about 10 minutes among five different perfumes.
</P>
<P>
   After much thought, I made my decision. Later that day, proud of
my accomplishment, I called my wife. She began laughing when I told
her what I had selected. It was the perfume she always wore.
</P>
<P>
   _ GILBERT GJERSVIK
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
