<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-VIEWING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS PAY LAST RESPECTS TO FORMER L.A. MAYOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE CONDON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- To Leana Babineaux, there was one big difference
in Los Angeles after Tom Bradley was elected in 1973 as the city's
first African-American mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of color were able to take part in what was going
on inside City Hall, instead of standing at the door looking
inside,'' said Babineaux, a 52-year-old resident of South Central.
``We were very happy when he became mayor. It was like we were
standing forward with our chest out.''
</P>
<P>
   Babineaux was one of thousands of Los Angeles residents who
filed past Bradley's body Sunday at a public viewing at the South
Hall of the Los Angeles Convention Center. Bradley, who retired in
1993, died after a heart attack Tuesday. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services will be held Monday for Bradley at 10 a.m. at
the First African Methodist Episcopalian Church at 2270 S. Harvard
Blvd. Vice President Al Gore, California Gov. Pete Wilson, Lt. Gov.
Gray Davis, Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan, Los Angeles County
Supervisor Chair Yvonne Brathwaite Burke, LAPD Chief Bernard C.
Parks and Los Angeles City Council President John Ferraro are
scheduled to speak.
</P>
<P>
   While Monday's service will mark the city's official farewell to
Bradley, people at the viewing Sunday said it gave them the chance
to reflect on how the mayor had touched their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``By showing up and saying goodbye to Tom, they are showing how
much he was loved by the people of Los Angeles,'' Riordan said
after he visited the Convention Center on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Jackson, 63, said she first met Bradley in the 1960s, when
he was a councilman and she asked him to come speak to a
Parent/Teachers Association meeting. Later she invited him to speak
at her church. Both times he accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was such a gracious man, you could approach him,'' Jackson
said, a retired teacher's assistant for Los Angeles city schools.
``He worked to open up City Hall not just for black people but for
all people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mischelle (cq) Baker said she knew Bradley because she is
related to one of his nieces. Still a teen-ager when Bradley was
making his rise politically in the 1960s, Baker said he was a role
model for her. His election as mayor in 1973 was a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It let me see I could reach a lot farther than a lot of people
in my family had,'' said Baker, now an industrial engineer at
Northrop-Grumman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was opening up all the doors so people like me and my son
could walk through them a little easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's family on Sunday issued a statement thanking the
hundreds of volunteers who have helped the family in the past few
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Words cannot really express our gratitude to the people who
have come by the house, sent notes and gifts, and offered to help
in any possible way. Today's public viewing at the Convention
Cemter and tomorrow's celebration of Tom Bradley's life would not
have been possible without our remarkable friends and many
volunteers. I know my father would be so thankful to everyone who
has helped in many ways,'' said Lorraine Bradley, the eldest
daughter of the five-term mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Rivera, a 40-year-old East Los Angeles homemaker, said she
decided to attend the viewing because Bradley always made sure to
be there for important events in her community when he was mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always involved with the community. He was at every
store opening, he was in every parade,'' Rivera said. ``He united
the races. We still need him to continue his work.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also an important role model for young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children looked up to him. If he could do it, if a
sharecropper's son could become mayor, they could do it too,''
Rivera said.
</P>
<P>
   Vernon Watkins, a union representative for the American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, flew in from
Washington, D.C., for the services. Watkins had been part of many
negotiations with Bradley over the years regarding employees
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understood the plight of the working man,'' said Watkins,
who campaigned for Bradley in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran on a slate of coalition politics. The idea was to
include everybody, and it worked,'' Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing at the downtown skyscrapers in the distance, Watkins
said Bradley was as responsible as anyone for the development of
the city's most important business center.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the skyline and think, It all happened on his
watch,'' Watkins said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
