<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-POLL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Top 10 again
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Are these Bulldogs for real?
</P>
<P>
   College football fans may get an answer to that question next
Saturday when Georgia meets Tennessee in a Southeastern Conference
showdown in Sanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Following Saturday night's stunning 28-27 upset at LSU, the
Bulldogs made the biggest leap in the latest college football
polls. Georgia jumped five spots to No. 7 in both Associated Press
and USA Today/ESPN coaches' polls, released Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, which dropped a notch to No. 4 in the AP poll and
remained at No. 5 in the coaches' poll, has won seven straight
games against Georgia. The Volunteers, who have won the last five
contests by an average of 18 points, came away the 17-9 winner at
Auburn on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Not since legendary Bulldogs coach Vince Dooley stalked the
sidelines has Georgia been host to a game of this magnitude. The
contest has been sold out for months, and both teams enter this
week unbeaten at 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Athens hosted a game between a pair of top 10
teams was 1983, when No. 3 Auburn beat the No. 4 Bulldogs 13-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs have been riding the right arm of freshman
quarterback Quincy Carter of Southwest DeKalb High, who threw for
318 yards and two touchdowns on 27-of-34 passing against LSU.
Carter, who has played three seasons of minor league baseball in
the Chicago Cubs organization, has been one of the nation's best
players this season, leading the SEC and ranking third nationally
in passing efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could accomplish much more during the first two
months of his collegiate career, Carter replied: ``Yeah, beat
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
