<SLUG> BC-GEN-CSUNNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW POWER IN PIVOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One area that needs to be shored up for the Cal
State Northridge women's basketball team is defense, and the
coaching staff has taken a step toward doing exactly that. Myiesha
Jones, a 6-foot-5 center at Merritt College in Oakland, last week
made an oral commitment to attend CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like their staff,'' Jones said. ``They're friendly.
I'm used to a family atmosphere and that's what they have there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who will have two years of eligibility at CSUN if she
qualifies academically, isn't considered a big scorer _ she
averaged six points per game last year _ but she should bring
defense and rebounding to a Matadors squad that went 14-14 last
season. Jones averaged almost 10 rebounds and four blocked shots
per game last season at Merritt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the CSUN coaches) told me it was going to be a lot of
hard work,'' Jones said. ``I know I have to start weightlifting and
run and have physical workouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones played at Castlemont High before attending Merritt. She
was also recruited by Fresno State.
</P>
<P>
   It's against NCAA rules for coaches to comment about recruits
before a national letter of intent is signed. Jones can sign in
November.
</P>
<P>
   __ Not exactly Big Bear: Basketball practice begins in less than
two weeks and final arrangements are being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the CSUN men's staff will be taking a retreat to plan
for the upcoming season. They'll sequester themselves in a local
hotel room for three days this week to talk hoop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll spend three days talking about basketball and beating
each other up,'' coach Bobby Braswell said. ``We have two new guys
on the staff this year (Andre Chevalier and Eric Brown) so we have
to go through every play so they know how to teach it and how to
execute it.''
</P>
<P>
   Braswell, whose Matadors are expected to contend for the Big Sky
championship, said he won't settle on a starting lineup until the
first game nears.
</P>
<P>
   __ Visitation rights: One luxury afforded the men's basketball
coaching staff this season is a methodical approach to the
recruiting process.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors have just one scholarship to offer for next season,
though that could change if Rico Harris forgoes his senior year for
the NBA draft. Now that the summer evaluation period is over,
recruits will begin making official visits.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland High guard Kent Dennis is expected to visit CSUN Oct.
23-25. Dennis could well wind up at CSUN because of familiarity.
Chevalier was his former coach at Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN is also trying to schedule a visit for Long Beach Jordan
guard Craig Calloway.
</P>
<P>
   __ When to start?: Men's volleyball doesn't kick into gear until
after the new year, but the NCAA does allow teams to practice for a
specified duration in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still up in the air as to when we'll (begin), either
Oct. 19 or Oct. 26,'' coach Jeff Campbell said. ``You're only
allowed 22 weeks (during the year), so you have to pick and
choose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
