<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-NOTES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Putts mar Glasson's solid outing
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ Bill Glasson's best finish of the year, a
tie for third in Sunday's conclusion of the Buick Challenge,
brought $102,000 to his 1998 earnings and an immeasurable amount of
personal satisfaction. The Evel Knievel of the PGA Tour, Glasson
has seen more recovery rooms than interview rooms and isn't fully
recovered from his third elbow operation. Were it not for a pair of
three-putts on the back nine, Glasson might have been slipping his
battered body behind the wheel of a new Buick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to win this one, but I didn't play well enough to
deserve to win,'' Glasson said after failing to birdie the 18th
hole for a shot in the playoff with Steve Elkington and Fred Funk.
``Today I just didn't hit the shots when I needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Glasson birdied three of the first four holes to take the lead
from Funk, then stalled on the back nine, shooting even-par for a
69 and 72-hole score of 20-under 268. With a cold putter and a slow
pace of play, Glasson eventually lost his early momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mind started to wander,'' he said. ``I think the pace of
play really killed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Glasson moved to 82nd on the money list with $340,131 _ not bad
for only 10 events _ and will defend Oct. 15-18 at Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall's 63 low for day
</P>
<P>
   Skip Kendall pushed himself within possible reach of the Tour
Championship at Atlanta's East Lake Golf Club Oct. 29-Nov. 1 with a
9-under 63 Sunday for 5th place. He moved to 33rd on the money list
with the $60,000 check, just behind Smyrna's Stewart Cink.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot,'' Kendall said of a shot at East Lake. ``I
figure I have to make about $200,000 the next four weeks. That's my
goal, but I know I've got to play good.'' . . . Defending champion
Davis Love III ended the tournament with a 66 to tie for 14th at
13-under, but never contended. Departing quickly for the airport,
Love passed over the Mountain View course in his jet while the
leaders were finishing. . . . Atlanta's Billy Andrade, able to
generate nothing better than a 70 Sunday, also tied for 14th and
actually dropped a spot in the money list, to 42nd ($680,181), when
passed by winner Elkington. ``I just didn't get anything rolling,''
Andrade said, ``but I'm still pretty happy with my play.Change in
plans
</P>
<P>
   With his surprise win, Elkington moved to 40th on the money list
with a gain of $270,000 and is an outside shot for the Tour
Championship. ``This may change my schedule,'' he said. . . .
Columbus' Larry Mize tied for 14th after a 67-67 weekend. . . .
David Duval closed with a 69 and tied for sixth at 15-under-273.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
