<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elkington prevails over Funk in playoff
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ Considering the way things had been
progressing all week at the $1.5 million Buick Challenge, it seemed
only a matter of time before they cut the ribbon on Fred Funk
Boulevard, commemorating another win here by the former Maryland
golf coach, and proclaiming his as the Official Comfort Zone of
Callaway Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Funk, the new sign on the property is more
likely to designate Steve Elkington Way.
</P>
<P>
   After battling viral meningitis and recovering from another
sinus surgery this year, hey, how scary could a duel on the back
nine and a sudden-death playoff turn out to be? For Elkington, the
35-year-old Australian with the swing as sweet as a slab of
honey-bourbon ribs, it became just what his battery of doctors
ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Elkington's previous win at the Buick Challenge came four years
ago, when the tournament was still searching for credibility. This
one materialized with 19 of the top 30 money-winners on the
property as Elkington, after a final-round 65, made a par on the
first hole of a sudden-death playoff to defeat Funk for the
$270,000 first prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playoffs are a crapshoot,'' Elkington said after his ninth PGA
Tour win. ``That's why they call it sudden death.''
</P>
<P>
   Both players had finished regulation play at 21-under-par 267,
tying Davis Love III's 72-hole record from last year. But when Funk
(69), who could drive a ball down a bowling lane, put his tee shot
on the playoff hole (the 18th), into the fairway bunker and then
slapped into the lip coming out, Elkington smoothed an 8-iron
safely to the green and two-putted from 15 feet for the win.
</P>
<P>
   From Saturday's back nine through Sunday's, Elkington, starting
the final round four shots behind Funk and trailing Bill Glasson by
three, went 13-under par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that last 27 holes is about as good as I can play,''
Elkington said. ``I got a little better each day.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a coronation, Funk found consternation by bogeying
the 9th and 14th holes on errant drives into the Mountain View
Course's perilous rough and then repeating the oddity in the
playoff. His 7-iron from 184 yards caught the lip and squirted his
ball into the fairway. His third settled into deep rough right of
the green, basically ruling out a chip-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disappointing to lose because I had the tournament
all week and my bread and butter is hitting fairways,'' Funk said.
``I just ran into a buzzsaw with Elkie making all the birdies. I
didn't do my end of the bargain to finish it off.''
</P>
<P>
   After the year's medical woes, maybe Callaway will again
springboard Elkington. He won the PGA the year following his
54-hole, rain-shortened decision here in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like a sickly person,'' said the Houston
resident, unfazed by Sunday's humidity. ``I hope it's all behind
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Glasson, who finished third at 20-under, missed a chance to join
the playoff by sliding a 15-footer by the hole at 18. Atlanta's
Billy Andrade (70) tied for 14th. Georgia Tech amateur Matt Kuchar
(71) tied for 58th.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
