A9105 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-COLUMN-SFCHR     10-04 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAIGHTENING UP AN INTOLERABLE OFFICE MANAGER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ILANA DEBARE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 Q:  I'm a secretary at a real estate company with a horrid office
manager. She ridicules the people who work for her, spreads rumors
and berates her subordinates arbitrarily. The situation is so bad
that six secretaries left in the past year. When we try to complain
to the managing broker, who is the office manager's boss, he just
laughs it off. Is there anything we can do?
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; A:  &LR; You've got one of the worst possible workplace dilemmas
here _ a boss who's a bully and higher-ups who don't seem to care.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth making one more appeal to the managing broker, this
time focusing on the high staff turnover and how your boss'
behavior is hurting the firm's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Has the company spent thousands of extra dollars to hire temps
because of turnover? Have sales been hampered because the office
staff is too demoralized or distracted to get the work done?
</P>
<P>
   ``Be extremely clear about your motives _ that you're bringing
this forward because it affects people's work and productivity,''
said Daniel Oestreich, an organizational development consultant and
author of the new book ``Driving Fear Out of the Workplace.''
``Just telling him that `this doesn't feel good' will not be as
effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Oestreich, who is based in Redmond, Wash., suggests offering
some solutions along with your complaints. You might ask the
managing broker to counsel your boss on certain behaviors _ for
instance, telling her not to spread rumors. Or you might ask him to
hire an outside team-building expert, who could assess your boss'
skills and coach her on how to be a better manager.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's a good chance the managing broker may still
turn a deaf ear. Then you have two options. One is getting together
with your co-workers and trying on your own to set some limits on
the boss' abusive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next time you see her belittling someone publicly, you
need to step in and say, `That's an unacceptable statement,' ''
said Ron Namie, a Benicia psychologist who counsels employees on
how to handle bad work situations and has a Web site called the
Work Doctor at www.workdoctor.com. ``Then the others need to step
in and back you up.''
</P>
<P>
   The other option is to do what those other six secretaries did _
quit and find a new job where you're treated with more respect.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Q:  &LR; I was employed by a computer contracting firm that sent
me out on assignments to a number of different clients. After my
last assignment ended in mid-August, the firm didn't have any more
work lined up for me but kept me on the payroll anyway. I kept
getting paychecks through the end of August, but then the checks
stopped coming. Last week, I got a letter from the company dated
September 20 saying they had terminated me as of August 28. Can
they fire me retroactively like that?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; A:  &LR; Many high-tech contracting firms pay their contractors
only for those days that they're actually assigned to clients. Your
firm seems to handle things differently, keeping people on payroll
during gaps between assignments.
</P>
<P>
   But that distinction doesn't matter here. The point is that an
employer can't fire you retroactively _ from this or any other job.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take a more traditional job as an example. If you were
employed as a teapot-maker, and you showed up at the teapot factory
for eight hours every day, the company couldn't tell you on
September 20 that it wasn't going to pay you for all your work
since August 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't keep an employee around for three weeks and then
say, `Hey, we terminated you three weeks ago,' '' said Charles
Thompson, an employment lawyer with Hanson Bridgett Marcus Vlahos &AMP;
Rudy in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Your situation seems a little less clear cut because the company
didn't send you out on any assignments. ``The interesting thing is
that this person wasn't doing any work during those three weeks,''
Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   But you were still legally on the company's payroll all that
time. You presumably stayed by the phone, waited for assignments
and didn't look for other work. So the company should have paid you
for those three weeks, just as if you'd been busily making teapots.
</P>
<P>
   And your next step should be to file a claim for unpaid wages
with the California Labor Commissioner, at (415) 557-7878.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Q:  &LR; I moved from Michigan to Colorado in March 1997 to take a
job with an electrical distributor. The salary was lower than I
wanted, but the owner made a verbal promise that after a year I'd
be eligible for an annual profit-sharing bonus of at least $14,000.
The year went by, but the owner then told me I would not be
eligible for profit-sharing until after my second year. This
created major financial problems for me, and I ended up resigning
from the firm because of this dispute. Can I sue the company for
breach of contract?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; A:  &LR; You need to check if the company's profit-sharing plan
is covered by the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974
(commonly known as ERISA), the federal law that governs pensions
and health benefits, according to Robert Truhlar, an employment
lawyer in the Denver suburb of Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   Some small employers have informal profit-sharing plans that
aren't covered by ERISA. But larger employers often draw up a
formal plan and file it with the Internal Revenue Service as an
ERISA plan, which can get them some tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   If this company's plan is an ERISA plan, it would be governed by
federal pension law _ and you might not be able to file a breach of
contract suit. You'd have to take any complaints to the U.S.
Pension &AMP; Welfare Benefits Administration.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But if it's not an ERISA plan, you could certainly sue for
breach of contract, according to Truhlar.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was a verbal promise, company officials would probably
claim they told you from the start that profit-sharing wouldn't
kick in until after two years. It would be their word against
yours. But you'd still have a strong case if you could produce
supporting evidence, such as notes you made after the hiring
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   One interesting point: You'd have an even stronger legal case if
this dispute occurred in California rather than Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Section 970 of the California Labor Code prohibits
``solicitation of employees by misrepresentation'' _ inducing a
worker to relocate for a job by misrepresenting the job. So in
California, you'd be able to sue not just for breach of contract
but also for violating the state labor code.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado has a similar law but, according to Truhlar, it's
rarely enforced in situations like yours.
</P>
<P>
   Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways,
San Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco, Calif.
94103. Or send e-mail to workways &LR; sfgate.com. Or call (415)
764-2815. We can't respond to each query, but we will answer as
many in print as we can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
