<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UW KICKING GAME CAN NO LONGER GO WITHOUT HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The caller to ESPN's national sports radio show early
Sunday morning was frantic.
</P>
<P>
   She was dialing ``Pigpen,'' the Las Vegas-based host, from
Seattle, demanding accountability for the source of her disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle, you're on. But no more whining about the Huskies,''
Pigpen sneered.
</P>
<P>
   The woman had been at Husky Stadium on Saturday night, bundled
up in Gore-Tex and purple pride as she watched a young, patchwork
Husky team attempt a resurrection of pride and momentum in a
football season trounced by the previous weekend's drubbing at
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of Saturday night's adventure in the rain?
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies should have, could have beaten Arizona, the woman
said.
</P>
<P>
   But any chance for resurrected pride and hope in 1998 was
crushed when Arizona quarterback Ortege Jenkins performed a Kerri
Strug gold medal somersault on the heads of the poor Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   After a stalwart attempt by the Husky defensive line to stop the
final Arizona drive, the cagey 'Cat QB vaulted himself into the
cool night air, then landed feet-first in the end zone to seal a
spectacular, come-from-behind Pac-10 win.
</P>
<P>
   But like most astute Husky fans, the caller understood the
Huskies' bitter 31-28 defeat was not decided by that amazing
80-yard scoring drive that all of Husky Nation will be forced to
relive as long as ``SportsCenter'' and other highlight shows replay
Jenkins' victorious work of acrobatics.
</P>
<P>
   The caller understood that the culprit in this unforgiving
defeat was the black hole known as the Husky kicking game. Her
outrage was warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an alumni, I want to know where my kicker is!'' the caller
said.
</P>
<P>
   And you know what? That sad, mad caller was speaking for all
Husky fans: Where have all the kickers gone?
</P>
<P>
   If UW coach Jim Lambright has an answer, it comes a week too
late (at least) to do his dispirited team or his peeved fan base
any shred of good.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, walk-on place-kicker Nick Lentz left the Washington
program. Lentz's disgruntled departure over the lack of a
scholarship put Lambright in the compromised position of sending
redshirt freshman Jim Skurski out on the field Saturday night to
perform one of the most important jobs in football.
</P>
<P>
   Skurski had connected on all of one field goal in his Washington
career.
</P>
<P>
   It should never have come down to this. The Washington kicking
game should not be relegated to holding your breath and praying
that field goals and extra points are not the difference between a
win and a bitter, unforgettable loss.
</P>
<P>
   It makes you wonder if Lambright ever took a look across the
lake last season to his old buddy, Dennis Erickson. Special-teams
debacles led to four losses for the Seahawks last season. Fixing
that broken part was priority No. 1, which explains why a new
punter and new special-teams coach, Pete Rodriguez, were brought
in.
</P>
<P>
   Glaring holes demand immediate attention, college or NFL.
</P>
<P>
   True, Lambright was willing to accept responsibility for this
botched game. His pain was evident in the post-game news
conference, when he was visibly shaken and driven to ``shield'' his
players from media questions.
</P>
<P>
   But the real way for Lambright to have avoided having to
announce ``I'll save my poor team for answering about this
disastrous loss'' was to have looked at the Husky record book. That
way, Lambright would see there is no way a shaky kicking game is
going to go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington tradition for place-kickers is rich. Chuck
Nelson's 1982 field-goal percentage (25 of 26 field goals made for
96.2 percent) is still an NCAA record.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Jaeger, who also went on to a stellar NFL career and is now
kicking for the Chicago Bears, set a record for 80 field goals
during his 1983-86 Husky career.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lansford went for two seasons when he did not miss an extra
point, booting 71 of 71 over 22 games in 1978 and '79.
</P>
<P>
   Before Lentz walked out last week, he already was in limbo. He
had claimed a quadriceps pull. He had been placed in equal standing
with Skurski, although all this turmoil seems easily traced to
Lentz's contention that he was told he would be rewarded with a
scholarship if he contributed to the team.
</P>
<P>
   With his 7-for-10 field-goal kicking in 1997, Lentz was the
second-leading scorer for the Huskies _ which only proves that
kickers, even the most average, can make the difference. And Lentz
was the first ray of hope that the Huskies' kicking game could at
least connect on 50 percent of its attempts.
</P>
<P>
   In a college football world of diminished scholarship
opportunities, the Huskies have had the added displeasure of the
lingering effects of their Pac-10 sanctions. If this has made the
Husky coaching staff blind to the dangers of praying a walk-on
kicker will be the answer, this last week should prove the ultimate
eye-opener.
</P>
<P>
   Lambright obviously feels bad for letting down the players who
did everything they could to beat Arizona. Freshman tailback Willie
Hurst and backup quarterback Marques Tuiasosopo were weapons enough
to get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   But as bad as Lambright feels, just think about poor Jim
Skurski, who missed two field goals and an extra point Saturday,
with two of those attempts blocked.
</P>
<P>
   If you are going to put a kicker on the field to ensure
important wins are signed, sealed and delivered, then it has to be
a kid good enough to earn a free ride. It's time for the Huskies to
sign, seal and deliver on this crucial part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
