<SLUG> BC-NCI-SOFTWARE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCI DROPS COMPUTER NETWORKS TO FOCUS ON SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAN FOST  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Network Computer Inc. isn't making networked computers any more.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The onetime division of Oracle instead moves toward its new
corporate focus today, announcing a software product that it says
will help hook up a variety of consumer products to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike earlier NCI releases, which touted future products
without actually showing any concrete realities, the eNavigator not
only has a powerful ally in Alameda software firm Wind River
Systems, but it's already shipping in a consumer product in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past six to eight months, there's been nothing short of
a wave of consumer electronic devices that have gone digital before
our very eyes,'' said Dave Limp, vice president of marketing for
Foster City's NCI. ``They're just a small increment away from going
from being digital appliances to being information appliances. This
software will allow manufacturers to make that leap.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that, as microchips wind up in a range of machines _
from cars to refrigerators _ those chips will need software to run
them. While Wind River already makes software that controls things
like a car's anti-lock brakes, traffic lights, factory floors and
the Mars Pathfinder, it wants NCI's software to hook those devices
into the Internet and other computer networks, and to provide
graphics to make the devices easier to use.
</P>
<P>
   NCI's eNavigator is now just running in a $1,000 Fujitsu
InterTop, a handheld computer that is larger than a PalmPilot but
smaller than a laptop. The software allows InterTop to handle
e-mail and Web browsing.
</P>
<P>
   NCI is betting that people will want other digital devices _
whether a telephone or a gas pump or a Nintendo 64 video game
console _ to hook up to the Internet not for complete Web browsing,
but just to pull select pieces of information. For instance, a game
player could hook up with other gamers, or a gas pump could
download and display advertising, or a phone could check e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of thing is going to make the Internet pervasive in
people's lives in the next few years,'' Limp said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Curt Schacker, vice president of marketing for Wind River,
said the graphic interface also is important. The software could be
used, he said, to make a home-irrigation system easier to run, as
well as to hook it into a water utility's network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are marketing this technology to people building all sorts
of things,'' Schacker said.
</P>
<P>
   According to analyst David Card with Jupiter Communications in
New York, the software fits with NCI's emerging strategy to focus
on television. The company had its genesis in database software
giant Oracle's war on Microsoft, and Oracle chief executive Larry
Ellison's desire to supplant personal computers with low-cost
networked computers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Card said, NCI _ which remains primarily owned by Oracle,
with Netscape Communications Corp. also holding a big stake _
concedes that the PC is not going away any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, NCI is letting its technology partners figure out how
to use its software in corporate networks while it focuses its own
efforts on software for interactive television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jupiter is much more bullish on NCI's opportunities to take
the software into television sets than other devices,'' Card said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
